<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CyanideDeaths 3rdLd-Writethru a0770 05-09 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyanide Deaths, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0770,0845</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Convicted in First Product-Tampering Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 21st graf ``Information about...'' to restore first
reference to Dwyer.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court jury convicted a woman Monday of
killing her husband and another woman by lacing their
Extra-Strength Excedrin with cyanide in the nation's first trial in
a death by product tampering.
   The 12-member jury deliberated almost five days before returning
the verdict against Stella Nickell. One juror held out for
acquittal until the final vote, said the jury foreman, Murray M.
Andrews, 55,
   Mrs. Nickell, 44, of suburban Auburn, was convicted on each
count she faced, two of causing death by tampering with a product
involved in interstate commerce and three of tampering. The first
two counts could result in life sentences.
   King County Prosecutor Norm Maleng said he would wait until
after sentencing, scheduled for June 17, to decide whether to file
state murder charges.
   When the verdict was read by the clerk, Mrs. Nickell bowed her
head.
   The charges stemmed from the June 1986 deaths of her husband,
Bruce Nickell, 52, and of Sue Katherine Snow, 40, also of Auburn.
Both died after ingesting the poisoned painkillers.
   The deaths touched off a nationwide tampering scare and prompted
Excedrin manufacturer Bristol-Myers Co. to recall its capsuled,
non-prescription medications.
   Seven people died in Chicago in 1982 from cyanide-laced
Extra-Strength Tylenol, but those deaths remain unsolved.
   John Weisberg, spokesman for the New York-based Bristol-Myers,
said the company was ``gratified by the jury's verdict, and
particularly appreciative of the efforts of the FBI and other law
enforcment authorities.
   ``Product tampering is intolerable to society. When it occurs
every effort must be made to identify those responsible and to
bring them to justice,'' he said.
   ``We're very pleased it's finally over. It was a tough case for
the jury to decide,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Joanne Maida,
who said she would ask for an ``appropriately severe'' sentence.
She did not elaborate.
   Ms. Maida said she hoped ``it will be a deterrent'' to future
drug-tamperers.
   During the trial, Ms. Maida portrayed Mrs. Nickell as an ``icy,
hard human being,'' unhappy in her marriage and beset by financial
problems, and accused Mrs. Nickell of poisoning her husband to
collect on his life insurance policies.
   Ms. Snow was an innocent stranger caught in Mrs. Nickell's
scheme to make her husband's death appear random, the prosecutor
said.
   But federal public defender Thomas Hillier said Mrs. Nickell was
the victim of a daughter who lied when she said her mother had
discussed killing Nickell with a drug overdose or by hiring a hit
man.
   The prosecution said Mrs. Nickell put tainted painkillers on
shelves of local stores to make her husband's death appear random
and to lead doctors, who had concluded Nickell died of emphysema,
to the true cause of his death.
   Only Mrs. Nickell had the motive, opportunity and ability to
commit the crimes, Ms. Maida told the jury in closing arguments May
2.
   Hillier called Mrs. Nickell's daughter, Cindy Hamilton, 28,
unreliable and noted that pharmaceutical companies had offered a
$300,000 reward to anyone who provided information leading to an
arrest.
   Further, the prosecution could not link Mrs. Nickell to cyanide
purchases, Hillier said.
   Earlier Monday, a juror said she had received an anonymous phone
call Friday in which the caller asked, ``Don't you all know that
she failed the lie detector test?''
   Information about the polygraph test had been kept from the
jury, but U.S. District Judge William Dwyer said neither the
panel's trouble reaching a decision nor the phone call would force
a mistrial.
   He gave Hillier a choice of substituting an alternate juror for
the one who received the phone call, but Hillier declined.
   Ms. Maida said in her closing arguments that Mrs. Nickell's plan
failed because she was careless in mixing the poisonous capsules,
greedy for insurance benefits and owned two of the five tainted
bottles of painkillers found.
   The odds of one person buying two bottles of cyanide-laced pain
capsules at different stores on different days were
``astronomical,'' Ms. Maida said, noting that more than 15,000
bottles had been examined in the Seattle area.
   Ms. Maida also told jurors that Mrs. Nickell might have gotten
away with the scheme if she had been more careful about the bowl
she chose for mixing the potassium cyanide with Anacin and Excedrin
painkillers.
   Mrs. Nickell, a tropical fish enthusiast, used a bowl
contaminated with Algae Destroyer, a compound used to clean fish
tanks, the prosecution alleged. Traces of the compound were found
in the five tainted bottles of Excedrin and Anacin, Ms. Maida said.
   Mrs. Nickell also tripped up in leaving fingerprints on library
books about poisons and cyanide, Ms. Maida said.
   But Mrs. Nickell testified she did the library research to find
out more about her husband's death and to protect children from
dangerous foliage around her rural home.
</TEXT>
