<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 0048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-AdvertisingAntics Bjt   05-09 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Advertising Antics, Bjt,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Election's Not Over, But There Were Clear Winners and Losers
Among Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only a handful of television viewers witnessed
one of the best ads of the 1988 presidential campaign _ 10 seconds
of Al Haig stuffing pizza into his mouth at a New Hampshire eatery.
   ``It got on the air one day before he withdrew,'' said Jay
Bryant, Haig's media consultant. The ad showed a
mischievous-looking Haig using his fingers to subdue some errant
pizza cheese, and instantly turned the off-putting general into a
likable human being.
   Political media observers, from academics to admakers, say few
if any TV spots this year have broken new technical ground or
connected emotionally with voters.
   Among the notable exceptions was Democrat Dick Gephardt's
``$48,000 Hyundai'' spot _ a trade tirade aimed at Korean tariffs
that price U.S. autos out of the Korean market.
   ``The populist impulses in the Hyundai ad, the defiant
expression, identified with the electorate's feeling of
powerlessness,'' said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, a professor and
author of two books on political ads and speeches. ``It was a
moment of empowerment. It let the voters feel good.''
   Jamieson also nominated the pizza ad, saying it forced the
viewer to reconsider Haig's somewhat negative and militaristic
image. The clear message was that ``if you knew him, you'd like
him,'' she said.
   The short spot shows Haig with a piece of cheese hanging between
his mouth and his pizza slice. He pulls it up to his mouth with his
finger, realizes he's on-camera, and winks.
   Meanwhile, a narrator is saying with mock seriousness, ``Former
Secretary of State Alexander M. Haig. The man with the best
credentials of anyone to be president, who's also a lot more like
you than you think. Vote for him.''
   Also on the air for only one day was another favorite _ a Bob
Dole ad questioning whether George Bush had left any legacy in the
numerous jobs he has held. The ad depicts a man's shadow walking
across a virgin expanse of snow, crunching as he goes, yet leaving
no mark.
   ``After 20 years of walking in the footsteps of giants, isn't it
odd that George Bush has left no footprints at all?'' a narrator
asks. ``It's almost like he was never there.''
   ``That was the most effective line he had going. It was a good
ad. It had the ring of truth and it was appealing,'' said Larry
Sabato, a professor, analyst and author.
   But Dole, coasting on his Iowa victory, didn't use the ad in New
Hampshire. Nor did the campaign carry out plans to reshoot it in
the sand for use in Southern Super Tuesday states. It aired once in
Florida, snow and all, then was pulled.
   ``They were believing the press clippings that they were on the
way to the nomination,'' said Sabato. ``I almost think Dole thought
it was time for healing (after Iowa). And he was trying to lower
that negative of being too harsh.''
   Other effective ads included Gephardt's attack on Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis for promoting Belgian endive as a remedy for
farm woes, and Dukakis ads mocking Gephardt's populist message and
flip-flops on issues.
   Jamieson makes a case for Dukakis's standard biographical ad _ a
fast-paced montage of photographs that begins and ends with the
printed words, ``A president for the 90s.'' It is being used
virtually everywhere and has been the only Dukakis ad on the air in
several states.
   ``It suggests solidity and stability and puts in place basic
premises about what he's done,'' Jamieson said. ``It's not the
funniest, it's not the glitziest, but it is the most effective
except for the Hyundai ad.''
   Haig, Bruce Babbitt and Pete du Pont won nominations for the
worst TV spots of the campaign season, as did the
information-packed Al Gore ads produced by David Garth for the New
York primary.
   ``The Gore spots in New York were awful, disgraceful. They were
just tepid. I felt they were very poorly communicating Gore's
message,'' said Sabato.
   Du Pont was skewered for visual gimmickry and amateurish
production. Jamieson cited one spot in which ``he rotates like a
statue and you see his squared-off jaw and he looks straight into
the camera. I expected it to be an ad for aftershave.''
   Babbitt ``looks very strange'' in many of his ads, Jamieson
said. Haig's initial ads ``made him appear rather evil. They
emphasized his harsh nature,'' said Sabato.
   The early Haig ads tried to put the best face on Haig's military
background by noting, for example, that no wars were started by
presidents who had been generals. But they used ponderous music and
ominous images and some gave the impression of ``Julius Caesar
returns to the Rubicon,'' said Jamieson. ``It was almost
terrifying.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
