<DOCNO> AP880509-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 0214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Delegates     05-09 0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Delegates,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Challenge Of Delegate Seating Likely, Campaign Chairman
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson will probably challenge the
seating of delegates at the Democratic convention in July because
it appears party officials will not act on his objections to the
selection process, his campaign chairman says.
   Willie Brown, speaker of the California Assembly, said he and
other Jackson advisers have spoken to Democratic National Committee
chairman Paul Kirk and other party leaders about Jackson's
insistence that the delegate totals roughly correspond to the
popular vote.
   But those talks, Brown said, are ``not so far productive,'' and
the campaign will likely make challenges to the delegate slates of
states where it believes the selection has been unfair.
   ``I think we are going to end up having to make them because I
don't think it's (the discussion) going to be productive,'' Brown
told The Associated Press on Saturday.
   In recent days, Jackson has said he is appealing to party
leaders for ``some measure of fairness,'' but he has shied away
from any indication that he would make an official challenge or
employ the kind of attack he made in disputing party rules in 1984.
   Jackson uses Puerto Rico as an example _ in that contest, he won
the popular vote but the governor awarded all of the island's
delegates to Michael Dukakis. Party rules allow for such practices,
although in many states the delegate allocation is tied directly to
the popular vote.
   A successful challenge could narrow the gap of roughly 600
delegates between Dukakis and Jackson and make the delegate tallies
more closely reflect the popular vote, which currently stands at
some 37 percent for Dukakis to 28 percent for Jackson.
   ``If we can mount some credential challenge on fairness, this
thing doesn't have to be over,'' Brown said when asked about the
conclusion by some observers that Dukakis all but has the
nomination locked up.
   Jackson has said he will talk with ``super delegates'' from
congressional districts where he won the popular vote, and appeal
for their support even though they are not bound to follow the vote
totals.
   Super delegates attend the convention by virtue of their
position as public or party officeholders.
   On Sunday, Jackson took that a step further, saying that white
Democratic officeholders, especially those in the South who have
benefited from the black vote, should be willing to support him on
that basis.
   He singled out North Carolina Sen. Terry Sanford and former
North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt, who angered Jackson supporters by
endorsing Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.. Gore narrowly defeated
Jackson in the North Carolina primary.
   ``It's reasonable to expect that Sen. Sanford will endorse my
campaign. That's a reasonable expectation,'' Jackson said in
Greensboro, N.C., noting that the black vote was crucial to
Sanford's 1986 election.
   Sanford is a super delegate.
   Jackson has also hinted that his supporters might stay away from
the polls in November if they perceived he was being treated
unfairly. He indirectly raised the possibility again on Sunday.
   ``We define our friends by their willingness to be fair and to
be just,'' Jackson said. ``One thing about politics, it does not go
up and down. It goes round and round. Anything that goes around
comes around.''
   Regardless of the outcome of the race for the nomination,
Jackson officials are confident their delegate strength will ensure
their influence on the party platform, and are working on what
issues they want to include.
   ``We won't have to worry about getting every plank we want
considered,'' said Brown.
   In the meantime, Jackson is unveiling the themes that he hopes
will increase that strength in California, the nation's biggest
delegate prize.
   Jackson has an active and broad organization of supporters but
he, like Dukakis, must figure out how to appeal to the wider
population in this state of 25 million that appears to lack
enthusiasm for this year's election.
   Most Democratic officeholders so far are sitting out the
campaign, apparently reluctant to endorse either Jackson or Dukakis.
   Many of them had earlier endorsed one of the five Democrats who
have since dropped out of the race.
   Brown characterized his non-endorsing colleagues in the state
legislature and other neutral politicians as mostly ``mainstream
traditional Democrats'' who would not be expected to endorse the
liberal Jackson and who don't feel they know enough about Dukakis.
   Jackson has been targeting women, environmentalists, Hispanics,
gays and peace activists, and continuing to sound his anti-drug and
anti-Reaganomics themes.
   Brown said campaign strategists are to meet this week to
determine what kind of television commercials will be aired in what
campaign manager Gerald Austin said will be about a $2 million ad
campaign.
   California ``is a hotbed for peace'' and Jackson's positions on
peace in Central America and the Middle East and Africa should sell
well, especially on the state's more than 140 college campuses,
said Brown.
</TEXT>
