<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WVaGovernor 1stLd-Writethru a0402 05-09 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WVa Governor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0402,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moore Spokesman Calls Payoff Allegation `Garbage'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: In 4th graf INSERTS quote marks and starts new graf to show
matter NOT attributed to Price; picks up 5th graf prvs, ``Arch
Moore...''. Johnie cq in 4th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN L. HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former political boss convicted of
corruption in a mountain coal mining county charged in a national
news broadcast Sunday that he turned down a $12,000 payment from
Gov. Arch Moore Jr.
   The NBC News broadcast, two days before an election in which
Moore is locked in a tough primary battle with Morgantown
millionaire John Raese, brought an angry response from the
governor's spokesman.
   ``As a former journalist, I think it's a piece of garbage,''
said spokesman John Price.
   ``The governor said that 16 years ago, he had no idea of the
existence of Johnie Owens.''
   Owens, the former Mingo County political boss, charged that
Moore offered him money to buy his organization's backing in 1972.
   ``Arch Moore laid down in the back seat of a car holding $12,000
up in his hand like a common criminal instead of a governor and
begged me to take it,'' Owens said on the broadcast.
   ``The governor said it's strange that 36 hours before West
Virginians go to the polls, a supposedly responsible network would
air the comments of a convicted felon,'' Price said.
   A federal court last month sentenced Owens to 14 years in prison
on four charges stemming from his role in a 1982 conspiracy to sell
the Mingo sheriff's job.
   Raese said he was dismayed by NBC's pre-election broadcast of a
previously unaired excerpt of a WSAZ-TV interview conducted on
April 19 as Owens was about to report to prison.
   ``I'm very saddened by the whole event,'' Raese said. ``It's a
dark moment for Republican politics in West Virginia.''
   Moore, a Republican, beat Democrat Jay Rockefeller _ then
secretary of state, now a U.S. senator _ by 600 votes in Mingo
County in 1972 despite a 7-1 voter advantage for the Democratic
Party.
   The last Republican to win an election in Mingo County before
that was Herbert Hoover in 1932.
</TEXT>
