<HEAD>Poll Indicates Mississippians Overwhelmingly for Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STARKVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Likely Republican presidential nominee
George Bush shows a significant lead over Democratic candidates in
Mississippi in a
   poll conducted by Mississippi State University.
   The survey found Vice President Bush would receive 59 percent of
Mississippi's vote, compared with 41 percent for leading Democratic
hopeful and Michael Dukakis if the election were held now.
   It showed Bush leading Jesse Jackson by 65-35.
   The survey of 433 likely voters was conducted by telephone
between April 11 and 24. The poll numbers were figured to rule out
undecided votes. The margin of error was plus or minus 6 percentage
points.
   Poll director Stephen Shaffer said the survey found that 94
percent of the registered Republicans said they would support Bush
against Dukakis, while Dukakis got only 69 percent of the
Democratic voters.
   ``Dukakis is especially hurt among independents, who favor Bush
by 74 percent to only 21 percent for the Democrat,'' he said.
