<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 0245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ecuador-Election     05-09 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ecuador-Election,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ecuadoreans Elect Left-Leaning President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rodrigo Borja, a center-left lawyer who
promised to distance his administration from the current
government's pro-U.S. foreign policy, was elected president of
Ecuador.
   Borja, 52, leader of the Democratic Left Party, defeated
populist Abdala Bucaram, 36, in an runoff on Sunday to select a
successor to conservative Leon Febres Cordero, Washington's closest
ally in South America.
   With the vote count virtually complete, Borja had 1,631,747
votes to Bucaram's 1,401,153 votes. Nearly 450,000 votes were blank
or nullified. More than 4.6 million Ecuadoreans were registered to
vote.
   Bucaram, speaking on national television from his power base in
Guayaquil, the country's largest city and its major port, conceded
defeat Sunday night and congratulated Borja.
   ``There are no excuses. Dr. Rodrigo Borja is the president of
Ecuador,'' said Bucaram, a fiery campaigner who had sworn to
``punish the oligarchy'' if elected.
   Speaking over television in Quito, Borja said, ``Thank you,
Ecuador, thank you.''
   It was Borja's third bid for the presidency. He was narrowly
defeated by Febres Cordero in a bitterly fought runoff in 1984 and
has pledged to reverse his foe's free-market economic policies.
   But he also told Ecuador's business community not to be
frightened by his election. ``Our victory should not make anyone
nervous. No one should set off a financial panic,'' Borja said
Sunday night. ``We intend to respect private enterprise.''
   Borja has promised to back a moratorium on payment of Ecuador's
$9.2 billion dollar foreign debt if creditors don't agree to
negotiate easier terms. ``I do not believe it is possible to pay
the foreign debt under the conditions they want to collect,'' he
said in a recent meeting with foreign correspondents. ``Either we
pay the debt or we develop the country. We can't do both things at
the same time.''
   The Febres Cordero government suspended payment on the debt last
year after severe economic damage from devastating earthquakes.
   Borja and Bucaram defeated eight other candidates in the first
round of elections Jan. 31 to qualify for the runoff. Febres
Cordero, of the Social Christian Party, came in third, a sign of
his government's low popularity.
   The victory by the left-leaning Borja and Bucaram sent tremors
through Ecuador's financial circles. The Ecuadorean currency
plunged in value from 275 sucres to the dollar to nearly 500 sucres
since the first round of voting.
   Borja has said he plans to establish exchange controls and
restrict imports to protect Ecuador's dangerously low dollar
reserves. He also plans price controls on basic consumer goods.
   He says he will seek close ties to the non-aligned movement and
re-establish diplomatic relations with leftist-led Nicaragua.
Febres Cordero severed relations in 1985 after an argument with
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega.
   Borja will be sworn in Aug. 10 for a four-year term. He will be
the third elected president since democracy was restored in 1979
after nine years of civilian and military dictatorships.
   Borja will confront the challenge of a governing a nation that
is in its deepest recession since it began exporting oil in the
early 1970s.
   The economy shrank 3.5 percent last year, thanks in great
measure to the sharp drop in the price of oil, Ecuador's major
source of income. Inflation is running at an annual rate of 70
percent, the highest level since 1983, and less than half the work
force has full-time employment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 0248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SovietCartoons     05-09 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Cartoons,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Soviet Cartoon Exchange Paints Picture Of Rosy Glasnost</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Wiley in 11th graf cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet artists are trying to draw the
cultural gap between the two countries to a close, and the idea has
people laughing.
   The traveling ``USSR-USA Cartoon Exchange'' features cartoons
from both countries that sponsors hope will erase walls of
misunderstanding.
   Is it working?
   ``Da!'' exclaimed the show's curator, Eric Swenson of San
Francisco. ``Big yes!
   ``Cartoons communicate the universal, wordless art that can make
people laugh,'' he said during the show's debut here this weekend.
``I'm overwhelmed by the instant rapport the artists from the two
countries develop. Listen to the sound in this building.''
   The sound Saturday in the gallery was laughter. Through a live
``videophone'' hook-up, about 10 U.S. artists serenaded a group of
Soviet artists in Moscow. They requested ``a typical American
song'' and got ``Take Me Out to the Ball Park.'' The Americans got
a long-distance ovation.
   ``I'm literally blown away by the quality and the humor,'' said
Brian Bassett, editorial cartoonist for the Seattle Times who draws
the syndicated comic strip ``Adam.''
   ``I guess that's an indication of how little our two cultures
have touched,'' he said.
   Iuri Ivanov, a 41-year-old cartoonist from Moscow on hand for
the opening, picked his favorite American exhibit of the 40 being
shown and sent it electronically to his colleagues in Moscow.
   ``I like it because it's stupid,'' Ivanov said, not being
critical. ``It describes the stupidity of the situation perfectly.''
   The cartoon by Wiley of San Francisco showed a complacent Soviet
Bear and casual Uncle Sam standing in front of two television
cameras, one camera Soviet, the other Amercian.
   The lens in the American camera shows the bear trying to devour
Uncle Sam. Conversely, the lens in the Soviet camera shows Uncle
Sam with a gun to the bear's head.
   ``Very definately the perceptions are changing,'' Ivanov said.
``The more of these type of exchanges, the more this picture won't
be true.''
   Not even the most optimistic of the 50 or so people at the
opening saw rosy Soviet-U.S. relations being painted with one
stroke of the brush. Ivanov, however, hailed increased cultural
exchanges made possible by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's policy
of glasnost, which has opened doors for Soviet artists.
   The few political jabs in the cartoons shown by the Soviet
artists were light, and any political satire tended to generalize.
Bureaucracy was lampooned, not the bureaucrats.
   In one of Ivanov's watercolors, a man tied to a noose serves as
the clapper in a bell. A smiling man in a uniform swings from the
hapless clapper's feet.
   ``The common man suffers so others can enjoy,'' Ivanov
explained. But he quickly pointed out the picture isn't
representative of capitalism or communism.
   ``It's like that everywhere,'' he said.
   Some Americans are slow to accept glasnost as anything more than
a concept, he said.
   For instance, he pointed to a picture by Milt Prigee, editorial
cartoonist for the Spokane Spokesman Review.
   The cartoon shows a man behind bars, with the familiar smiley
faces drawn around it along with the Soviet sickle and the word
``glasnost.''
   ``The artist doesn't understand the situation of glasnost,''
Ivanov said. ``The bars are cut. That was a problem before, but not
anymore. Things are immensely better under Gorbachev.''
   Asked for an example, Ivanov replied, ``For example, I am here.''
   The show continues here through June 7 before heading to Los
Angeles, Dallas, Atlanta, Chicago and Washington, D.C. After that
it moves to the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
