<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BadWriting     05-09 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bad Writing,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It Was A Dark And Stormy Paragraph</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What makes a good sentence go bad?
   ``Like an expensive sports car, fine-tuned and well-built,
Portia was sleek, shapely and gorgeous, her red jumpsuit moulding
her body, which was as warm as the seatcovers in July, her hair as
dark as new tires, her eyes flashing like bright hubcaps, and her
lips dewy as the beads of fresh rain on the hood; she was a woman
driven _ fueled by a single accelerant _ and she needed a man, a
man who wouldn't shift from his views, a man to steer her along the
right road: a man like Alf Romeo.''
   That awful thing was submitted to the annual Bulwer-Lytton
Fiction Contest by 20-year-old journalism student Rachel Sheeley of
Franklin College in Indiana. It brought her to the top _ or the
bottom _ of the heap of more than 11,000 entries.
   The top honor _ or, again, the lack of it _ was announced Sunday
by San Jose State University Professor Scott Rice, founder and
``grand panjandrum'' of the literary disgrace he calls ``the
Baltimore Orioles of literature.''
   Whether a boon or bane for the winner's career, Rice points out
that the competition is not a joke-writing contest. ``It really
takes a very good writer to deliberately write bad,'' he said.
   The contest trashes the battered memory of 19th century English
writer Edward George Earle Bulwer-Lytton, whose turgid style is
captured in the opening line of one of his novels: ``It was a dark
and stormy night. ...''
   Rice notes that Bulwer-Lytton also is remembered for such
ringing cliches as ``The pen is mightier than the sword'' and ``The
Great Unwashed.''
   The contest also is a gentle reminder to the world of letters
that it is OK to lighten up, forget the grammar books for a minute
and have some fun, to ``approach the language recreationally as
well as practically,'' Rice said.
   For her effort, Sheeley wins a word processor. This, Rice noted,
illustrates the computer-terminology adage, ``Garbage in, garbage
out.''
   Awards also were made in selected categories.
   Brian W. Holmes of San Jose won in puns: ``Once a month, when
the moon is full, Reverend Jim Bleaker and his lovely wife Teddi
invite members of the church to the parsonage for an evening of
hymn singing, followed by cookies, tea, and a frenzied orgy on the
lawn outside, making sure, of course, to take all the usual
precautions for safe sects.''
   Joan Mazulelwicz of Liverpool, N.Y., won for purple prose: ``The
silent snow fell relentlessly, unceasingly, mercilessly from the
sordid, sullied surreality of the sky as if some enormous, ethereal
diner were shaking grated parmesan on the great, soggy meatball
that was earth.''
   Michael Stratford, Miles City, Mont., won for science fiction:
``Shirley doubted that her alien escort, composed as he was of
vegetable matter, seaweed, and a thick coating of swampy muck,
would be a suitable date for the Intergalactic kegger, but he
turned out to be a real FUNGI.''
   R.B. Nelson, Nottinghamshire, England, won for detective novel:
``With the radio squawking that a 4711 was in progress at 37th and
127th, Murphy knocked car 495 into 3rd and headed up 5th at 70,
little reckoning, as he thumbed his .38, that this would be the day
when his number came up.''
</TEXT>
