<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Edge Downward</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with closing figures; picks
up 5th pvs: Dealers said...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar steadied against the Japanese yen Monday
after opening lower in Tokyo, while stock prices dropped in a
market traders described as lusterless.
   The dollar opened at 124.73 yen and then edged up to close the
day's session at 124.87 yen, down 0.01 yen from Friday's close.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which shed 46.62 points during last Saturday's half-day session,
continued to slide downward, losing 223.47 points or 0.81 percent
to end the day at 27,264.30.
   
   Dealers said the lack of major market-affecting news is
contributing to a sluggish U.S. currency, and market participants
are watching the dollar's weak showing after the release Friday of
favorable U.S. unemployment figures.
   According to figures released by the U.S. Labor Department,
unemployment in the United States fell to a 14-year low of 5.4
percent in April as the demand for American exports fueled
employment prospects for industry workers.
   An exchange dealer at a major Tokyo commercial bank, who
requested anonymity, said market participants were taking a
``wait-and-see position'' Monday.
   Share prices opened higher in early trading, but fell as
investors decided to sit back, said Yoshio Shimoyama, a trader with
Nikko Securities.
   ``Trading slowed down about midmorning due to a lack of market
incentives after the holiday period,'' Shimoyama added.
   Japanese markets were closed Tuesday to Thursday for national
holidays.
   Share prices for heavy electricals like Hitachi and Toshiba, as
well as light electronics including Sony, fell in the morning
session. Also down were some automakers and precision equipment
makers such as Canon.
