<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YachtSeized     05-09 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yacht Seized,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crew: $2.5 Million Yacht Singled Out For Seizure Under Drug Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crew members on a $2.5 million yacht
seized under a U.S. drug policy called ``Zero Tolerance'' say the
Coast Guard unfairly targeted the craft and was thrilled to find
some marijuana seeds and stems.
   The 133-foot Ark Royal, a white fiberglass floating villa
trimmed with teakwood and polished brass, was escorted into port
Sunday night to be turned over to the government under the
month-old order to seize any vessel carrying even a tiny amount of
drugs.
   ``It's punishment for no just cause,'' said John Koch of San
Diego, one of the six crew members, which included one woman.
``It's just a lot of malarkey.''
   The Coast Guard cutter Tampa stopped the yacht Saturday in the
Yucatan Channel between Cuba and Mexico, and a search turned up
less than one-tenth of an ounce of marijuana, authorities said.
   ``They followed us for maybe one or two hours,'' Koch said.
``They didn't respond to any of our radio calls ... they didn't let
us out of their sight.''
   But Capt. Norman Saunders, commander of the Coast Guard Key West
station, said such searches are random, and the yacht was not
singled out as an example.
   ``We generally look at any northbound vessel going through that
area,'' Saunders said. ``The Yucatan Channel is a natural
bottleneck from the Caribbean to the Gulf of Mexico.''
   Coast Guard officials say the vessel initially was stopped for a
courtesy boarding to check paperwork and safety equipment, but a
full search was ordered after marijuana residue was found in a
trash can.
   ``They found five seeds in a trash can and they rooted through
the whole place,'' said a crew member, who gave his name only as
Roy. ``Ten seeds and a couple of stems are all they found.''
   Crew members say the Coast Guard party then came aboard with
saws and drills hoping to find more illegal drugs, but the yacht's
captain refused to allow any more searching until the ship reached
port.
   Koch said the yacht departed from San Diego more than a month
ago and was headed to Fort Lauderdale and then to the Mediterranean
for charters.
   ``It's the most beautiful boat I've ever seen,'' said Coast
Guard Ensign William Brewer, part of the search party. ``The inside
of it looks like something out of `The Great Gatsby.'''
   The yacht is decorated in art-deco style, and contains works of
art, a grand piano and two Jacuzzis, Brewer said.
   The Ark Royal's registered owner is Michael J. Rogerson,
president and chief shareholder of Tomima Corp., said Coast Guard
Lt. John Felker. Neither Rogerson nor any passengers were on board,
said Felker.
   The American Civil Liberties Union said the seizure was
excessive.
   It violates a sense of proportionality, said Mary Coombs, a
member of the ACLU Miami chapter. ``It's putting people at enormous
risk with no effective way of protecting themselves,'' she said.
   Boater Ken Seger said the Coast Guard is trying to seize private
vessels and sell them as a way of making up money it lost from its
recent $100 million budget cuts.
   But Key West charter boat captain Steve Knowles said he is
refusing anyone on his boat who intends to use drugs.
   ``It's fine if you want to do it, but not on my boat,'' he said.
``I don't want to lose my boat and lose my whole livelihood.''
 
</TEXT>
