<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-Pool     05-09 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Pool,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Navy Explodes Mine In Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The following dispatch is from Robert Kearns of
Reuters, the press representative in the Pentagon news pool in the
Gulf.
   ABOARD THE USS COPELAND (AP) _ U.S. Navy divers have exploded a
mine found drifting in the northern Persian Gulf by the missile
frigate Simpson.
   The mine found Sunday was the first discovered in the area since
the U.S. missile frigate Samuel Roberts was nearly sunk by a mine
last month.
   Also Sunday, three motor boats raced toward a convoy of U.S.
ships, but veered off. A Navy official said they were probably
operated by smugglers.
   Lt. Cmdr. Mark Van Dyke, a Navy spokesman, told a Pentagon media
pool the Simpson reported the mine was 85 miles southwest of Farsi
Island, where the Iranians have a military base. Navy divers
detonated it an hour later.
   Van Dyke said the mine was an encrusted Myam-type mine that
apparently had broken loose from its mooring.
   The Myam is smaller than the type of mine containing 250 pounds
of explosives that holed the Roberts on April 14 off Qatar, 140
miles southeast of Farsi, wounding 10 crewmen.
   President Reagan has accused Iran of laying the mines to disrupt
gulf shipping. In retaliation for the Roberts mining, he ordered
attacks on Iranian oil platforms April 18.
   That led to a string of clashes between U.S. and Iranian ships.
The U.S. Navy claimed it sunk three Iranian warships and damaged
three others.
   A multi-national mine sweeping force has detonated at least six
mines since the Roberts was hit. French warships have reported
finding other mines further south in that period.
   The U.S. Navy, backed by the British, French, Belgians and
Italians, has dealt with scores of mines in or near the gulf since
last summer.
   Sunday's mine discovery came as shipping traffic picked up in
the waterway after a lull caused by last month's clashes.
   But the shipping community remains edgy. Tehran has sworn
revenge for its losses last month.
   Earlier Sunday, three fast-moving motor boats raced across the
Strait of Hormuz, gateway to the gulf, toward a U.S.-escorted
convoy.
   One darted under the Copeland's guns across the warship's bow.
That jarred already jittery nerves aboard the convoy ships as the
whaler-type boat sped past into the wake of the supply ship USS San
Jose and the oil tanker Ranger.
   All three unidentified boats then disappeared into the
sweltering haze, heading toward the Oman coast.
   The Copeland's captain, Cmdr. G.M. Ziller Jr., radioed a warning
to the apparently unarmed boats, but raised no response.
   Ziller said they may have been smugglers who decided to ignore
what he joked was the ``law of gross tonnage'' by zipping in front
of the heavily armed 3,600-ton frigate. ``I don't think there was
any hostile intent,'' he said.
   The convoy passed within range of Chinese-made Silkworm missiles
on the nearby Iranian coast.
   The pace of U.S.-escorted convoys has returned to what it was
before the April 18 fighting and Iranian navy ships have all but
disappeared.
   Four convoys have moved through the strait in the past week and
navy officials say the escort operations will continue as needed.
   Iran's 354-foot supply ship, Booshehr, glided within 2,500 yards
of the 3,700-ton missile frigate USS Jack Williams early Saturday.
   The two ships sailed past each other without incident in the the
closest encounter between the two navies since last month's battles.
   Some U.S. Navy officers believe the Iranians are licking their
wounds and deciding what went wrong before making the next move.
   ``I think they're doing what we would be doing in the same
situation,'' the skipper of the 24,000-ton San Jose, Capt. Willard
J. Halley, told the media pool Saturday.
   ``They're figuring out what happened to the chain of command and
who's responsible and what should be done about it.
   ``This could be a lull while they work on the next step,'' he
said, noting a long-standing split between the regular Iranian Navy
and the Revolutionary Guards who have attacked neutral shipping
with armed speedboats.
   Since the April 18 fighting, Reagan has laid down new rules for
U.S. warships patrolling the gulf, allowing them to help
non-American ships under attack if U.S. intervention is requested.
   The Navy has 28 warships in the region, including an aircraft
carrier-led task force stationed in the north Arabian Sea.
</TEXT>
