<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LongDistanceValedictory     05-09 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Long Distance Valedictory,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Valedictorian to Stop at Nothing for Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT UPTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just because she'll be 12,000 miles
away at the time of her high school graduation, Susan Lynne
Harrison isn't stopping at anything to fulfill her duties as class
valedictorian.
   The 18-year-old senior from New York state's rural Chenango
County is planning to deliver her speech by phone to her 17
classmates next month. She'll be on the island of Tasmania, south
of Australia.
   ``We initially were just sitting talking with her before she
left fantasizing about what we might be able to do and then decided
we would do it,'' Assistant Superintendent Frederick Kirsch said of
Harrison, who's been an exchange student since February.
   Because of the time difference, Harrison will actually be
speaking at 4:30 a.m. the day after graduation. Mount Upton High
School officials aren't sure how much the phone call will cost.
   Harrison's mother, Janet, will accept her daughter's diploma at
graduation. The high school senior will return from Tasmania in
August, and she plan to enter Syracuse University to study
communications.
   Harrison's not taking any chances on missed connections,
officials said. She's mailing a tape of her speech ``just in case''
and is sending a written copy to be read by a classmate if all else
fails.
</TEXT>
