<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-09 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Firms Against Yen; Stocks Slide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed in dealings against the Japanese
yen today after opening lower in Tokyo, and stock prices continued
to slide due to a lack of market incentives, traders said.
   After opening at 124.73 yen, the dollar firmed in afternoon
trading to close the day at 124.87, down 0.01 yen from Friday's
close.
   ``The dollar is continuing to hover around the 124-125 yen range
of the past two weeks because of the absence of market-influencing
news,'' said a Mitsubishi Bank exchange dealer, who requested
anonymity.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
fell 223.47 points, or 0.81 percent, closing the day's session at
27,264.30. The index declined 46.62 points during last Saturday's
half-day session.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at a thin 600 million
shares.
   Traders said investors were apparently reluctant to buy shares
due to the approach of a flurry of earnings reports by Japanese
companies in upcoming weeks, the U.S. Treasury's mid-quarterly
refunding due to start Tuesday, and next week's American trade
figures.
   Yoshio Shimoyama, a trader with Nikko Securities in Tokyo, said
trading picked up at the start of the week's dealings Monday
morning but fizzled out by midmorning as market investors sat back
to await fresh incentives.
   In thin afternoon dealings, steelmakers, shipbuilders and
automakers, such as Toyota and Honda, fell in price. Heavy and
light electricals, including Matsushita and Sony, also came under
selling pressure.
</TEXT>
