<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in moderate European trading
early today, but traders predicted it would strengthen on
speculation the U.S. Federal Reserve will raise interest rates.
Gold prices rose.
   One foreign currency dealer in Milan, Italy, said Friday's
figures showing the U.S. unemployment rate was 5.4 percent in
April, the lowest level in 14 years, has strengthened fears the
American economy is overheating.
   ``The unemployment figure sparked fears of renewed inflation,
forcing the Fed to act soon,'' to raise interest rates, she said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar slipped 0.01 yen to a closing 124.87. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 124.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.6815 West German marks, up from 1.6805
   _1.4000 Swiss francs, down from 1.4015
   _5.7155 French francs, down from 5.7230
   _1.8870 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8860
   _1,252.40 Italian lire, down from 1,254.00
   _1.2365 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2375
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8760, more expensive for
buyers than late Friday's $1.8730.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $443.25 a troy ounce, up
from late Friday's $442.10. It was little changed in quiet trading
at midmorning when the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $443.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $443.45, up from $443 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 79 cents to close at a bid
$446.66.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.37 a troy
ounce, up marginally from Friday's $6.36.
