<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Bush-Noriega     05-09 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Noriega,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ambassador Denies Briefing Bush On Noriega Drug Deals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY15</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former U.S. ambassador to
Panama denied telling Vice President George Bush as early as 1985
that Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega may have been involved in drug
trafficking.
   The ambassador, Everett Ellis Briggs, said on Sunday there was
not enough evidence against Noriega, Panama's de facto ruler, at
that time.
   ``I could not have briefed the vice president on Noriega's
drug-running, drug-smuggling or money-laundering activities because
we simply did not have evidence of those activities at that time
and so any statement to the effect that I did brief him on such
matters at that time simply is not true,'' Briggs told a news
conference in Tegucigalpa.
   The New York Times reported in its Sunday editions that Briggs
had sent cables to the U.S. State Department about allegations of
Noriega's drug dealings, and that Briggs told Bush about the
substance of those cables during a meeting on Dec. 16, 1985.
   Bush, a Republican presidential candidate, has said he knew of
no clear evidence that Noriega was involved in drugs until February.
   Noriega commands Panama's Defense Forces and is the power behind
the civilian government in that nation. The general was indicted by
two federal grand juries in Florida on drug trafficking charges and
has rejected U.S. demands that he resign.
   Briggs was ambassador to Panama in 1985 and is now ambassador to
Honduras. He acknowledged that there were persistent reports about
Noriega and drug trafficking.
   ``Panamanian sources would come to us and say `Why do you have
dealings with this man when it is well known that he is a drug
smuggler?' and our answer always was `Provide us the evidence,' and
unfortunately during the time I was in Panama that evidence was not
forthcoming,'' he said.
   ``Now I am sorry it took so long for us to get the evidence,''
he said. ``I am sorry that we weren't able to get it sooner and I
am very, very glad that the evidence was available finally so that
Noriega could be indicted. I consider him probably the most
pernicious element in this hemisphere at this time.''
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman in Tegucigalpa read a partial
transcript of Briggs' news conference statements to The Associated
Press.
   The New York Times, quoting unidentified Reagan administration
officials, reported that a memo from Bush aides to the vice
president before his meeting with Briggs said the meeting was to
``discuss U.S. relations with Panama and narcotics matters.''
   Briggs said he did not have a written record of what he and Bush
discussed during their meeting, but he imagined it would have been
the slaying of Hugo Spadafora, a critic of Noriega, and the
circumstances leading to Noriega's ouster of elected President
Nicolas Ardito Barletta.
   He said he doubted he would have discussed with Bush the cables
he was sending to Washington at the time.
</TEXT>
