<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 0738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NewCaledonia     05-09 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Caledonia,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scattered Violence In New Caledonia On France's Election Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL DONNET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In scattered violence during the
French presidential election, a bus driver was shot and wounded
while driving people to the polls and police dispersed Melanesian
separatists blocking a street.
   In another development, authorities said funerals were held
peacefully on Sunday on the island of Ouvea in this French Pacific
territory for Melanesian separatist kidnappers killed when police
freed their hostages.
   In Paris, the main Melanesian separatist group, the Kanak
Socialist National Liberation Front, hailed the re-election of
President Francois Mitterrand on Sunday. Djim Ouenei, the group's
representative, said the Kanak people, as native Melanesians are
known, were renewing their proposal to negotiate ``to get out of
this colonialist mess.''
   Conservative Premier Jacques Chirac won a record number of votes
in New Caledonia, 90.3 percent, while Socialist Mitterrand took the
rest. But in France, Mitterrand roundly defeated Chirac.
   Native Melanesians make up 43 percent of the inhabitants of New
Caledonia, colonized by France in 1853. Thirty-six percent are of
European descent and the others are Asians and Polynesians.
   Many Melanesians want independence, but but a majority of the
Europeans and others wish to remain part of France.
   Police in the capital of Noumea said the bus driver was hit in
the legs by buckshot Sunday afternoon as he drove 15 Melanesians to
a polling station in Pouembout, on the west coast of the main
island and 150 miles north of Noumea. No other injuries were
reported.
   In the town of Yate on the south end of the main island, police
used tear gas to disperse a crowd of separatists who erected a
barricade.
   The French High Commissioner reported that 14 of 128 polling
stations were moved ``for reasons of public order.''
   Voter turnout on the archipelego was 61.69 percent, up from 59
percent in the first round of balloting two weeks ago in which
Chirac also took the lion's share of the votes.
   The conservative Rally for the Republic in Caledonia, a local
spinoff of Chirac's Rally for the Republic party, controls the
regional government.
   Separatists boycotted and attempted to disrupt the first round
on April 24, but promised last week not to take similar action this
time.
   On April 22, separatists stormed a police station on the island
of Ouvea, northeast of New Caledonia's main island, killed four
gendarmes and abducted others. A second group of gendarmes was
abducted several days later.
   On Thursday, police stormed the cave where the 23 hostages were
being held and killed 19 of the kidnappers. Two members of the
French military assault team also were killed and five people were
wounded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 0744EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Denmark-Election     05-09 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Denmark-Election,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nervous NATO Watches Danish Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUNILLA FARINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Danes vote in a parliamentary
election Tuesday that will serve as a referendum on this nation's
future in the NATO alliance.
   Prime Minister Poul Schlueter called for the elections just
eight months after the last vote because the socialist-dominated
parliament ignored his objections and passed a resolution
toughening Denmark's non-nuclear status.
   Under parliament's resolution, Denmark must notify each visiting
warship that nuclear arms are barred from Danish ports in peacetime.
   That has been the Danish stand for 31 years, but until now it
has been merely a general statement of policy.
   NATO said such a resolution would undermine the unity of the
Western alliance and could threaten the ability of the United
States and Britain to protect Denmark in an emergency.
   Schlueter, leader of the minority center-right government,
called for new elections rather than implement the resolution.
   The opposition campaign has taken on an anti-American tint,
centered around the slogan: ``Denmark decides for itself.''
   ``If there are two people agreeing on Danish politics, it's
Ronald Reagan and Margaret Thatcher,'' says an election poster
depicting the U.S. president and the British prime minister in an
embrace.
   ``Forty-three years ago Denmark again became part of the free
world,'' counters a poster for the Liberal Party, a member of
Schueter's four-party center-right alliance.
   Polls indicate that most Danes agree with the traditional
anti-nuclear position. One recent survey said 82 percent of those
asked favored a nuclear-free zone in Scandinavia, and 46 percent
said they would support the idea even if it meant Denmark's
expulsion from NATO.
   Early polls indicate that neither the conservative-led
government nor the socialist opposition may emerge as a clear
winner on Tuesday, and Denmark could once again be governed by an
unwieldy minority coalition.
   Surveys trying to forecast Tuesday's outcome have been
inconclusive, but several have shown modest gains for the
opposition partnership of the Social Democrats and the Socialist
People's Party.
   In last September's election, Schlueter's coalition won 70 seats
in the 179-member Folketing, and the socialist bloc took 81 seats.
Each side also had two more supporters from the autonomous
territories of Greenland and the Faroe Islands.
   The balance of power is held by the 11-seat Social-Liberal
Party, which usually supports the government's economic policies
and the opposition's foreign and defense policies.
   The anti-tax Progress Party, with 9 seats, and the far-left
Common Course Party, with 4 seats, make up the balance.
   The shape of the next government could be determined by Niels
Helveg Petersen, the Social-Liberal leader, who could even make a
bid to become prime minister in the event of a deadlock between the
two traditional blocs.
   Three other parties are contesting the election, but none is
expected to pass the minimum of 2 percent of the votes cast needed
to gain a seat.
   Polls open at 9 a.m. for the 3.9 million eligible voters.
Results should be known shortly after they close at 8 p.m.
   Schlueter argues that the anti-nuclear resolution could lead to
a refusal by allied ships to pull into Danish ports. ``It would be
totally devastating for Denmark's defense,'' he told a news
conference Thursday.
   ``We will not accept a resolution that brings our full
membership of NATO into doubt,'' added Foreign Minister Uffe
Ellemann-Jensen, the Liberal Party leader.
   If the resolution is allowed to stand and visiting ships are
given a letter, ``the next step would be to ask for an
acknowledgement of that letter, the next step would be to demand
guarantees, and the next step would be the right to inspection,''
he said on Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
