<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Violence 1stLd-Writethru   05-09 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Violence, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0508,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rival Shiites Fight In Hand-To-Hand Battles, Shoot Up Hospital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE death toll; picks up 4th
pvs: Most of...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shiite Moslem militias battled for
control of high-rise buildings in the south Beirut slums today, and
gunfights were reported inside a hospital. Police said 40 people
were killed and 105 injured.
   The fighting was in its fourth straight day, with both sides
using tanks, mortars and rockets.
   Today's casualties brought the overall toll to 129 dead and 322
wounded since the fighting began Friday between the Syrian-armed
Amal militia and the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   Most of the 18 foreign hostages in Lebanon are believed held in
the labyrinthine slums.
   The fighting flared after two weekend cease-fires collapsed in
the battle for control of slums that stretch for 16 square miles
along Beirut's southern edge. The clashes began when four Amal men
were killed in a street ambush and Amal blamed Hezbollah.
   Gunbattles flared in the al-Sahel hospital, where a doctor said
militiamen forced surgeons to operate at gunpoint on dead comrades
``to bring them to life.''
   One doctor, speaking on condition of anonymity, said rival
gunmen had shot it out inside the hospital.
   ``We've been forced many times to abandon casualties because of
gunfights in the emergency ward,'' she said.
   Doctors confirmed allegations by both sides that wounded
fighters have been dragged from ambulances and hospitals by their
rivals and slaughtered.
   Amal, Syria's main ally in Lebanon, and the Hezbollah fighters,
who are loyal to Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini of Iran, have long
been bitter foes in a struggle for control of Lebanon's 1.2 million
Shiites, the country's largest single sect.
   Police said Hezbollah fighters, wearing red headbands, appeared
to have gained considerable ground in the densely populated
Ghobeiri, Bir el-Abed, Hay Madi and Meshrafieh neighborhoods.
   Much of the fighting centered on high-rise buildings used by
both sides as strongpoints and sniper nests.
   The fundamentalist Hezbollah is believed to be the umbrella
group for Shiites holding most of the kidnapped foreigners in
Lebanon. There has been no word on the captives' fate since the
fighting broke out.
   ``God willing, we will liberate Hay Madi and Bir el-Abed and
free all the foreign hostages,'' said Amal fighter Tarek Saad as he
trained his shoulder-fired rocket launcher at Hezbollah positions
in Hay Madi. ``We know they're imprisoned there.''
   Thunderous shell blasts shook Beirut all night as both sides
mounted grenade-throwing forays against each other's strongpoints
behind barrages of fire from tanks, mortars and multi-barreled
rocket launchers.
   Amal's irregulars, with green or black headbands, control most
of the districts of Haret Hreik, Mreiji, Roweiss, Shiyah and
Kasskass, a police spokesman said. He cannot be named under
standing regulations.
   ``Hezbollah has established control over half of the slums. It
only controlled one-third before the current fighting,'' the
spokesman said.
   A cease-fire at midnight Saturday broke down after 16 hours.
Syrian and Iranian mediators called another cease-fire for 10:30
p.m. Sunday. But the fighting raged on and intensified after
midnight.
   The newspaper As-Safir said the current confrontation has set
the stage for the Syrian army to move into the slums to disarm the
two militias.
   Syria's military intelligence chief in Lebanon, Brig. Gen. Ghazi
Kenaan, met with leaders of both warring factions as well as
government and religious figures today.
   Syria deployed 7,500 troops in Moslem west Beirut in February
1987 to end militia warfare in the capital. It has not sent its
forces into the southern slums, a traditional Hezbollah stronghold.
</TEXT>
