<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Punjab 1stLd-Writethru   05-09 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0503,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Civilians Killed, Five Troops Injured in Golden Temple
Shootout</HEAD>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with two civilians killed,
battle continuing, PICKS UP graf 6 `The Sikh...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikhs inside the Golden Temple opened
fire today on nearby government security posts, police said,
setting off a gun battle in which two civilians died and five
paramilitary troops were injured.
   The Sikh extremists began firing automatic rifles at 1:15 p.m.,
and the troops returned fire with light machine guns, according to
police superintendent Baldev Singh. The fighting continued for at
least three hours.
   Singh said it was not known if any militants where killed or
injured in the exchange.
   The civilians killed in the crossfire outside the Golden Temple
complex were identified by police as Venod Kumar, 30, a Hindu who
worked with the Red Cross, and Dilip Kaur, an 80-year-old Sikh.
   Among the injured was the deputy inspector general of the
paramilitary Central Reserve Police Force, S.S. Virk. He was out of
danger after surgery for a bullet wound on his chin, the United
News of India said.
   Virk and other senior paramilitary officers had gone to
government security posts on rooftops near the shrine to look at a
bunker Sikh militants were building at the western end of the
Golden Temple complex.
   Police said the militants opened fire from at least 16 sites in
the temple complex, mainly with Chinese-made AK-47 automatic rifles.
   The troops returned fire with light machine guns, according to
Singh.
   Shops and businesses in bazaars around the Golden Temple closed
their shutters, and an indefinite curfew was imposed on the old,
walled, central part of Amritsar to keep civilians indoors.
   More than 1,000 police and paramilitary troops were rushed to
the temple to seal exits and prevent people from entering.
   Sikh extremists have been waging a guerrilla campaign since 1982
for more political autonomy or an independent homeland for Sikhs in
Punjab. The Golden Temple is Sikhism's holiest shrine.
   In June 1984, the Indian army stormed the Golden Temple to drive
out militants, and more than 1,200 people were killed. Later that
year, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi was assassinated by two Sikh
bodguards in revenge for the raid, setting off anti-Sikh rioting in
which 2,000 people died.
   The gun battle today was the worst in a series that began
shortly after Jasbir Singh Rode was restored as the temple's chief
priest in early March. Rode had been in custody under the
government's anti-terrorism rules, but was freed in an effort by
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi to placate the extremists and lure them
into negotiations.
   Since Rode's return, there have been persistent reports that the
militants have been building bunkers and firing ports in the temple
complex.
   The militants fired on police outside the temple last week when
security forces tried to arrest a Sikh militant as he was heading
for the shrine. The militant escaped and fled into the temple, but
he was believed wounded.
   Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million population but are a majority in
Punjab.
   Meanwhile, five more people were reported killed by Sikh
extremists in overnight attacks in Punjab, the United News of India
reported. The slayings followed an attack by the radicals in
neighboring Haryana on Saturday in which 13 Hindus were killed
during a wedding party.
   The latest killings raised to about 940 the number of deaths
blamed on the Sikh separatists this year.
   The rate of killings is more than twice that of 1987, when 1,000
people were killed by Sikh extremists. Most victims have been
Hindus or moderate Sikhs in Punjab.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
