<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Airman     05-09 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Airman,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Bishop Condemns IRA at Airman's Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINSFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic bishop today condemned
the ``murderous tactics'' of the Irish Republican Army in his
eulogy for a British airman slain in the Netherlands.
   The Rt. Rev. Joseph Grey, bishop of Shrewsbury, said at the
requiem Mass for 20-year-old Senior Aircraftman Ian Shinner that
there could be no justification for his killing.
   Shinner died in a spray of IRA bullets while sitting in a car
with two other British airmen outside a pub in the Dutch town of
Roermond on May 1. An hour later, two more enlisted men were killed
by an IRA car bomb at Nieuw Bergen 35 miles away.
   Among today's mourners in St. Joseph's Church in Shinner's
eastern England hometown were 35 colleagues from his West
German-based regiment. They included Richard Grant, a 22-year-old
airman who survived the gunfire that killed Shinner.
   ``This young man's life was taken in such a horrifying fashion,
for which really no justification can be found,'' Grey told
mourners. ``No cause can justify the employment of such murderous
tactics.''
   A Royal Air Force squad fired three shots over Shinner's coffin
as he was buried with full military honors. His regimental cap and
the Union Jack flag which had draped his coffin were handed to his
brother Neil, an 18-year-old soldier in the British army.
   Funerals for the airmen killed in the car bombing, John Miller
Reid and John Baxter, both 21, were held Saturday in Scotland.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army is waging a guerrilla
campaign to oust the British from Northern Ireland and unite the
Protestant-dominated province with the mainly Catholic Irish
Republic.
</TEXT>
