<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DramaDesk 1stLd-Writethru a0428 05-09 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drama Desk, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0428,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drama Desk Nominates for Play Awards</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to CORRECT ``Les Miserables'' to
``Phantom'' as one of the two best-play nominees.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Tony Nominations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' a lavish stage
version of the horror film about a singer and the mysterious figure
who pursues her, and ``Into the Woods,'' Stephen Sondheim's
collection of fairy tales without fairy-tale endings vie for the
Drama Desk award as best musical.
   In fact, ``Phantom'' and ``Into The Woods'' were the only
nominees in the category, according to Sunday's announcement by the
association of drama critics, reporters and editors.
   ``Into The Woods'' led the musical division with 13 nominations.
Andrew Lloyd Webber's ``The Phantom of the Opera'' and the Lincoln
Center revival of Cole Porter's ``Anything Goes'' each received 11
nominations.
   ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone,'' August Wilson's look at black
life in the early part of the century, topped nominations in the
play category with seven.
   Awards will be announced May 25 and presented June 2.
   Broadway's most prominent newcomer, the singer-actress Madonna,
did not get a nomination, but her two ``Speed-The-Plow'' costars
did. The David Mamet play premiered last week.
   For the first time in many seasons, none of the 22 categories
was eliminated, but some categories had a small field. James
Lapine, for ``Into the Woods,'' is the only nominee for best book
of a musical.
   For outstanding new play, ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone,'' ``M.
Butterfly'' by David Henry Hwang and ``Speed-the-Plow'' were
nominated from Broadway and ``Boys' Life'' by Howard Korder, ``The
Road to Mecca'' by Athol Fugard and ``Woman in Mind'' by Alan
Ayckbourn were nominated from off-Broadway.
   Actors nominated from musicals were David Carroll for ``Chess,''
Michael Crawford for ``Phantom,'' Joel Grey for ``Cabaret,'' Howard
McGillin for ``Anything Goes'' and George Merritt for the
off-Broadway ``Lost in the Stars.''
   Musical actresses nominated were Sarah Brightman of ``Phantom,''
Judy Kuhn of ``Chess,'' Patti LuPone of ``Anything Goes,'' and
Bernadette Peters of ``Into the Woods.''
   Actors nominated were Derek Jacobi for ``Breaking the Code,''
Delroy Lindo for ``Joe Turner,'' John Lithgow for ``M. Butterfly,''
John Malkovich for ``Burn This'' and Joe Mantegna and Ron Silver
for ``Speed-the-Plow,'' all Broadway performances.
   All the actresses nominated, except Glenda Jackson for her role
as Lady Macbeth, were off-Broadway performances. Other nominees
were Kathy Bates for ``Frankie and Johnny in the Clair de Lune,''
Stockard Channing for ``Woman in Mind,'' Amy Irving for ``Road to
Mecca,'' E. Katherine Kerr for ``Laughing Wild'' and Gordana
Rashovich for ``A Shayna Maidel.''
   The Drama Desk added an outstanding ensemble acting category
this year for the second time in its 39-year history. The three
off-Broadway casts nominated opened in ``Boys' Life,'' ``The Day
Room'' and ``Oil City Symphony.''
</TEXT>
