<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ColemanTrial     05-09 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coleman Trial,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Back for Sixth Day in Sentencing Convicted Killer of Alday
Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After getting a replacement for a juror
described as ``incoherent,'' the jury returned to court today for a
sixth day of deliberations on whether Wayne Carl Coleman should die
for his part in the six 1973 slayings of the Alday family.
   Superior Court Judge Hugh Lawson on Sunday morning excused a
juror and replaced her with one of three remaining alternates. At
3:30 p.m., he sent the jurors back to their hotel with instructions
to return today.
   The jury met briefly with Lawson this morning before resuming
its talks.
   Defense attorney Tom West moved again Sunday for Lawson to
declare the jury deadlocked. That would bring Coleman an automatic
life sentence.
   Coleman was one of three men originally convicted and sentenced
to die for the 1973 slayings of six members of the Ned Alday family
in Seminole County. The verdicts were thrown out in 1985 by a
federal appeals court which cited pretrial publicity.
   The juror who was excused did not accompany the other jurors to
the DeKalb County Courthouse Sunday morning. She arrived separately
and then testified before Lawson.
   Much of her testimony was inaudible. Several times, she said,
``They put a bug in my ear. Remember Mary Alday.''
   Mary Alday was raped and killed in a field near the mobile home
where her husband, Jerry Alday, and four other Alday men were
killed on May 14, 1973.
   A deputy assigned to watch the sequestered jurors testified the
juror ``was mumbling nonsense. She was not coherent. She is not
physically or mentally capable to continue.''
   The deputy said the woman could be made to return to the jury
only by force.
   The jury last Monday convicted Coleman of six counts of murder.
On Wednesday, the jurors began deliberating whether he should be
sentenced to death or life in prison.
   The woman replaced Sunday was the second juror to be replaced by
one of the four alternates.
   West said Sunday he believes the case may now be the longest
penalty deliberation in recent Georgia history. Lawson has given no
indication when he might halt deliberations. On Saturday, he gave
the jurors a second set of instructions and told them he wants them
to reach a decision.
   One of the other two men originally sentenced to death, Carl
Isaacs, was convicted a second time in January and again condemned
to die. The third defendant, George Elder Dungee, is to be retried
later in Columbus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
