<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PowerPlantFire     05-09 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Power Plant Fire,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Erupts in Electric Plant, Causing Roof to Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALATKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire whose smoke was visible for 40 miles
roared through a coal-powered electric plant near here today,
causing a roof to collapse, but no serious injuries were reported.
   The extent of damages in the $1.2 billion plant, which opened in
1984, was unclear, said fire dispatcher Miller Norton. No
disruption in service to utility customers was expected.
   The fire erupted in a system that keeps hydrogen gas from
escaping into the atmosphere, according to Jeff Fela, public
affairs representative for Seminole Electric. Hydrogen gas is a
standard coolant for electric generators.
   One person, believed a worker at the Seminole Electric
Cooperative Plant, was treated at the scene for unknown injuries,
said Capt. James White, shift commander at the Palatka Fire
Department.
   Another person earlier unaccounted for was found, Norton said.
   A plume of smoke was visible in Jacksonville, about 40 miles
north of the plant.
   At least 30 fire units from the local department and surrounding
counties were called to the scene after the fire was reported about
5 a.m., White said. More than 100 fire, rescue and law enforcement
officers were called to help battle the blaze.
   ``It is contained from what we are told,'' Major Paul Usina with
the Putnam County Sheriff's Office said shortly after 9 a.m.
   The two coal-fired generators where the fire erupted are located
on a 2,000-acre site six miles north of Palatka off U.S. 17.
   The fire erupted on the second floor of the six-story main plant
of the 600-megawatt facility after the hydrogen leak developed on
one of the two turbines, officials said.
</TEXT>
