<DOCNO> AP880509-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Argentina-Military     05-09 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina-Military,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Fugitive Returned To Argentina For Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cashiered army Gen. Carlos Suarez
Mason, Argentina's most-wanted military fugitive, was extradited
from the United States today to face trial for the murders of
suspected leftists in the 1970s.
   The extradition was ordered April 27 in San Francisco by U.S.
District Judge Lowell Jensen, who ruled Suarez Mason could be tried
in Argentina on charges of 39 murders allegedly committed by troops
under his command. If convicted, the maximum sentence is life in
prison.
   The 64-year-old former general fled Argentina in 1984 and was
arrested by federal marshals in Foster City, Calif., a San
Francisco suburb, where he has been living under an assumed name.
   Federal Police Chief Juan Pirker confirmed that Suarez Mason
arrived at Ezeira International Airport at 9:05 a.m. aboard an
Aerolinas Argentinas flight from New York. Pirker said Suarez Mason
was accompanied by five guards, but he refused to provide further
details.
   The handcuffed prisoner was escorted off the plane by federal
police officers, witnesses said, was put aboard an armored vehicle
and taken to federal police headquarters in downtown Buenos Aires.
   Suarez Mason was stripped of his military rank in April 1984
after he was declared ``in rebellion'' when he failed to appear
before a military tribunal for questioning in connection with the
abduction, torture and murder of suspected leftists.
   At least 9,000 Argentines disappeared in a so-called ``dirty
war'' waged against leftists by the military regime that seized
power in 1976 after ousting former President Isabel Peron.
   Suarez Mason's trial was personally ordered by President Raul
Alfonsin shortly after he took office in December 1983, ending
nearly eight years of rightist military rule.
   Suarez Mason was commander of the Buenos Aires-based 1st Army
Corps from 1976 to 1978, when he was promoted to head of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff. He retired in 1981 and was named president of the
state oil monopoly Yacimientos Petroliferos Fiscales, a post he
held until 1982.
   Argentina sought Suarez Mason's extradition on 43 separate
charges of murder. He also has been accused of 635 cases of human
rights abuse as well as misappropriation of more than $2 million
while he headed the state oil monopoly.
   In approving Suarez Mason's extradition, Jensen ruled he could
be tried on 39 murder murders, as well as an additional charge of
forging a passport renewal.
   But the judge rejected the four other murder charges after
ruling that identification of the victims was inadequate. He also
ordered the dismissal of 23 kidnapping charges, saying the 5-year
legal deadline for filing the charges expired in 1984.
   Under the extradition law, Suarez Mason can be tried only on
charges for which extradition is approved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
