<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Vietnam     05-09 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Vietnam,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Claims Vietnamese Killed Three in Cross-Border Raid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China claimed Monday that Vietnamese troops
crossed the border and killed three Chinese farmers as they tilled
their fields.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Chinese border guards and
militia ``were compelled to fight back and wiped out the enemies.''
It did not give details of the clash, which it said occurred
Saturday, nor did it say how many troops were involved.
   Xinhua, quoting unidentified military sources, said Vietnamese
troops have crossed into southern China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region two dozen times in the past 10 days and stolen cattle, grain
and cloth from local residents.
   China and Vietnam have regularly accused each other of small
attacks along their 800-mile border ever since they fought a brief
border war in 1979.
   China claimed Vietnamese troops made a series of ``harassing
attacks'' into Guangxi Zhuang in April, beating one Chinese to
death and kidnapping others. It said each time the Chinese militia
sent the invaders fleeing.
   China and Vietnam also have clashed over their rival claims to
the Spratly Islands, also called the Nansha Islands, in the South
China Sea. Large oil deposits are believed to be located near the
islands.
</TEXT>
