<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NASA'sLittleA Bjt   05-09 0812</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NASA's Little A, Bjt,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Down-to-Earth Side of the Space Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANGLEY RESEARCH CENTER, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two years ago, in his State
of the Union message, President Reagan launched a venture to take
aviation into the 21st century.
   ``We are going forward with research on a new Orient Express
that could, by the end of the next decade, take off from Dulles
Airport (outside Washington), accelerate up to 25 times the speed
of sound, attaining low Earth orbit or flying to Tokyo within two
hours,'' he said.
   Research on an aerospace plane already had been going on for
years in the part of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration that gets little public attention _ NASA's first A,
for aeronautics, sometimes also known as the little A.
   ``We are called the space agency by many, probably including
yourself,'' Jeremiah F. Creedon, the director for flight systems at
the Langley Research Center, told a visitor. ``Many of us here
think the (aeronautics) A is a large one.''
   Together with other NASA research centers _ Ames and Dryden in
California and Lewis in Ohio _ Langley's business is to develop
technology and to pass it on, without cost, to aircraft companies.
   Few planes fly today without engines, designs, materials and
structures conceived at NASA. No single company alone could afford
the agency's $2 billion investment in wind tunnels.
   Reagan's rosy prediction followed years of research by NASA
engineers before they decided that the aerospace plane, dubbed the
X-30, was even possible.
   In the summer of 1990, engineers will decide whether to actually
build the X-30. If the answer is yes, it could begin flight tests
that would finish when the 21st century is ushered in.
   It will be the largest experimental aircraft project ever
undertaken by the United States, costing $3.3 billion.
   The idea of the X-30 is to develop technologies that will be
useful for planes at a slower speed _ such as 3{ times the speed of
sound, or Mach 3.5.
   The military, and perhaps package delivery firms such as Federal
Express and United Parcel Service, are the only ones that have use
for a plane flying 25 times the speed of sound.
   ``There is tremendous potential for all kinds of vehicles
operating at high Mach numbers,'' said Douglas Dwoyer, manager of
hypersonic technology at Langley. ``The national aerospace program
is aimed at an experimental aircraft to demonstrate technologies
for this family of hypersonic aircraft.''
   Although the big airplane manufacturers have little interest in
building a Mach 25 plane, they do want a craft capable of flying
between Mach 2 and Mach 3.5, for the years 2000 to 2010.
   At Mach 2.7, a trip from Los Angeles to Tokyo would take just
under four hours.
   The United States did research in the 1960s on a supersonic
transport, the SST, but dropped the program in 1970 because of
costs and environmental concerns.
   ``The nation essentially allowed its entire research and
technology base in hypersonics to disappear,'' said Dwoyer. ``We
are bringing tunnels on line that haven't operated in almost 20
years with instrumentation systems that are 20 years-plus old.''
   Meanwhile, the British and French produced the Concorde, capable
of twice the speed of sound.
   The Concorde was designed with 1960s technology and can barely
carry enough fuel to make it from Europe across the Atlantic. The
business of the future is with the Pacific Rim _ Japan, China,
South Korea _ where a fast, 6,000-mile airplane is needed.
   Roy Harris Jr., director of aeronautics at Langley, sees a real
need for a long-range SST.
   The airlines that serve that market are pushing hard, he said.
Boeing and Douglas are trying to determine how many Mach 3.5 planes
might be needed by the year 2000. ``It looks like it's on the order
of 300 to 400 airplanes for the world market,'' said Harris _
holding out the prospect of a world market for an American plane
that would help untilt the trade balance.
   But the British, the French, the Soviets and the Japanese also
have ambitious aeronautics programs.
   Despite such competition, the United States treats its
aeronautics limb as a poor relative. Out of a $9 billion NASA
budget, aeronautics R&D this year gets only $430 million; $53
million of that is earmarked for the aerospace plane.
   The money issue is a sensitive one at Langley.
   ``I think we are grossly underfunded,'' said Dwoyer. ``On a
$400-million-a-year program, we cannot maintain our capability.''
   Until 1970, the U.S. jet transport industry had 90 percent of
the long-range market. Now that's down to 70 percent.
   ``For 70 years you could go to any airport in the world and look
out on the ramp and you see `Made in the U.S.A.,'' Harris said. Now
the European-built Airbus, a superb plane, can be seen at most
airports, too.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
