<2ND_LINE>AM-North Korea-Japan,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Bans Most Contact With Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea has banned almost all contact with
Japan in retaliation for sanctions Japan imposed against the
communist nation last January, North Korea's official news agency
said Monday.
   ``The travel of all delegations has virtually been suspended
between our country and Japan,'' the Korean Central News Agency
quoted an unidentified Foreign Ministry spokesman as saying.
   The news agency said individuals attending international
conferences or sporting events would still be allowed to go to
Japan.
   Japan imposed sanctions on North Korea on January 26 after
accusing it of downing a South Korean passenger jet last November.
Japan said it would sharply restrict contact between Japanese and
North Korean diplomats and prohibit North Korean officials from
entering the country.
   Last Friday, North Korea canceled a visit to Japan by two
zoological experts scheduled to arrive Tuesday with a rare Korean
wolf for the Kyoto Municipal Zoo. Also Friday, Japan said it would
waive its sanctions to let two North Koreans compete in a table
tennis match here in mid-May.
</TEXT>
