<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds     05-09 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurdish Rebels Kill Eleven Villagers, Three Others Found Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NUSAYBIN, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Kurdish guerrillas raided a
hamlet near the Syrian border and killed 11 villagers, including
eight children, the Anatolia news agency reported Monday.
   The semi-official agency also said security forces found the
bodies of three villagers kidnapped by the rebels on Saturday after
the guerrillas killed another 11 people during a raid on a township.
   It said the bodies were found near the hamlets of Tarakli and
Uckardesler.
   A band of rebels raided Behmenin hamlet in the Taskoyu village
late Sunday and sprayed a villager's house with automatic gunfire,
killing the 11 people inside, the agency said. A 2-month-old infant
was among the dead.
   Sunday's attack was similar to the one Saturday during which
rebels affiliated with the Kurdish Labor Party raided a township 62
miles from Taskoyu.
   In the past, the rebels have aimed such raids at civilians
suspected of collaborating with Turkish security forces.
   The Kurdish party seeks to set up an independent Marxist state
in parts of eastern and southeastern Turkey.
   About 800 civilians and soliders and about the same number of
Kurdish insurgents have been killed since the Kurdish guerrillas
started hit-and-run attacks in 1984.
   Ethnic Kurds make up about one-fifth of Turkey's 52 million
people.
</TEXT>
