<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     05-09 0904</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0941</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American organization has presented a fancy
new wheelchair to the son of senior Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
   Rich Walsh, head of the Resource Center for the Handicapped in
Seattle, said the chair was presented to Deng Pufang. ``His aides
told me he took it home and tried it out,'' Walsh said Monday.
   Walsh said the chair was custom-designed for the 43-year-old
Deng, who has been unable to walk since radical Red Guards forced
him from a fourth-floor window during the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution. His father, Deng Xiaoping, was purged twice during the
decade but rose to power in 1978.
   Walsh said he met the younger Deng when he visited Canada and
the United States in October. Deng toured rehabilitation centers
and raised funds for the China Welfare Fund for the Handicapped,
which he heads.
   ``Deng and I really hit it off,'' said Walsh. ``He's just got a
great sense of humor.'' He said he decided to give him a wheelchair
after noticing that Deng's was ``an antiquated old beater.''
   Walsh, 50, who lost use of his arms and legs in a car accident
11 years ago, said Chinese officials have agreed to send several
disabled Chinese to enroll in his center's vocational training
program this year.
   He said they also discussed preliminary plans for the non-profit
center to set up a pilot program for training the disabled in
Beijing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca and singer
Aretha Franklin are among five celebrities featured in a brochure
urging tourists to ``feel at home in our hometown.''
   Whose hometown? None of the five lives here.
   Iacocca, Franklin and talk-show host-psychologist Sonia Friedman
live in suburban Bloomfield Hills. Writer Elmore (Dutch) Leonard
lives in suburban Birmingham and actor Tom Selleck _ who was born
in Detroit _ lives in Southern California.
   About 100,000 visitors to the Motor City have received the
brochure, including 35,000 members of the American Association of
Retired Persons, which will holds its annual convention here this
week.
   The Metropolitan Detroit Convention & Visitors Bureau, which
produced the brochure, says it is splitting hairs to claim the
featured celebrities lack Detroit addresses because the bureau
represents metro Detroit.
   But Friedman's comment in the brochure may be a giveaway.
   ``It's a wonderful place to visit,'' she says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROSYTH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Andrew took a bumpy step Monday
toward a long-term career in the Royal Navy.
   The Duke of York stumbled over a coil of rope as he boarded his
new ship, the guided-missile destroyer HMS Edinburgh at the Rosyth
Naval Base in eastern Scotland. He recovered quickly to stride up
the gangplank and report for duty as the destroyer's newest junior
watchkeeper.
   Andrew, 27, second son of Queen Elizabeth II, joined the navy on
a medium-term commission in 1979 and, after serving in the Falkland
Islands War against Argentina, became a helicopter warfare
instructor.
   He switched to the navy's ``general list'' last fall so he could
continue his naval training and advance beyond his current rank of
lieutenant.
   The destroyer sails from Rosyth on June 13 for six months in the
Far East and Australia, which means Andrew will have to apply for
special permission to return to England in August when his wife,
the former Sarah Ferguson, is expected to deliver their first child.
   ``The navy tries, wherever possible, to free men in his
situation who want to be at home when their children are born,''
said a Defense Ministry spokesman.
   ``He will be able to apply to take leave, but whether or not he
gets it is up to the captain and depends on whether he can be
spared.''
   Andrew is fourth in line to the throne following his older
brother, Prince Charles, and Charles' two sons, Princes William and
Harry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ZIZERS, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Empress Zita of Austria, widow of the
last Hapsburg ruler Karl I, discreetly marked her 96th birthday
Monday.
   Closest family members gathered to celebrate in this Swiss
village, where Zita has lived for three decades in an old people's
home run by Franciscan nuns, said Bernd Posselt, press agent for
her son Otto von Hapsburg.
   She is in good health except for fading eyesight, he said in
Munich, West Germany.
   Born in Italy as a princess of Bourbon-Parma, Zita is Europe's
last living empress. Her husband, the last crowned head of the
Hapsburg dynasty that ruled for 640 years, died in exile on the
island of Madeira in 1922 at age 34.
   After the Allied victory in World War I, Karl had agreed to
``temporarily relinquish'' his imperial rights, but never
officially abdicated.
   Zita, who had eight children, once held court at Vienna's
Schoenbrunn castle. She now lives in two plainly furnished rooms.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music singer George Jones was in
fair condition Monday at University Hospitals suffering from double
pneumonia.
   Jones was admitted Friday for bronchial problems later diagnosed
as pneumonia, and he responded well to treatment, said hospital
spokesman Hank Black.
   Black said Jones began feeling bad Wednesday night following a
show in Des Moines, Iowa. He entered his tour bus and told the
driver to take him to Alabama, said Black.
   Jones, who used to live in northwest Alabama, has been admitted
to University Hospitals three times in the last year for various
ailments.
   ``We're glad he likes us,'' said Black.
</TEXT>
