<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EscapeeRecaptured     05-09 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Escapee Recaptured,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murderer Recaptured 10 Miles from Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNDSVILLE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A murderer who escaped five weeks ago
with two other inmates from a maximum-security prison was
recaptured today about 10 miles from the prison, state police said.
   Details of the arrest of Tommie Mollohan this morning were not
immediately available, a state police dispatcher said.
   Mollohan, 45, had been sighted several times in the remote,
wooded area of Marshall County since his escape April 3. The two
inmates who escaped with him from the West Virginia Pentitentiary
in Moundsville were recaptured last month.
   Penitentiary officials had described Mollohan as the mastermind
of the breakout. He was serving a life sentence without chance of
parole for the 1973 robbery and murder of a grocer. At the time,
Mollohan had escaped from a Florida prison and also was wanted in
Georgia and North Carolina on armed robbery charges.
   The other two escapees also were serving life sentences without
chance of parole.
</TEXT>
