<HEAD>Israeli Gunships Raid Village, Military Denies Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli helicopter gunships on Monday
raided a village in south Lebanon which is policed by United
Nations peacekeeping troops, security sources said. No casualities
were reported.
   Sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said one house was
damaged in the attack on Kabrikha, 16 miles east of Tyre.
   Kabrikha is policed by Irish troops of the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon. The Irish battalion did not fire on the helicopters, the
sources said.
   They said the house that was hit may have been used by a
guerrilla group to launch cross-border attacks into Israel.
   The raid was Israel's seventh air strike in Lebanon this year.
Forty-nine people have been killed and 71 wounded in the earlier
raids.
   In Tel Aviv, the Israeli military command denied the report,
saying there had been no air raid on Kabrikha.
