<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-09 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPPELL, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not wanting to take a bath on an old water
tower, city officials have been advertising it for sale, but it's
not easy finding a buyer.
   ``It's a cute tank,'' says the mayor of this Dallas suburb, Lou
Duggan. ``It's not like the other tanks _ the cylindrical looking
type of tanks.
   ``It's the kind that has a bell shape to it. It looks like a
golf ball on the end of a golf tee.''
   Coppell's use for the decade-old 250,000-gallon tower dried up
in January with the installation of a 1.5 million-gallon tank to
service its more than 15,000 residents.
   ``There's no used water tower lot where you can go and sell a
used water tower,'' Councilman Tom Morton said recently.
   Duggan said he'd accept a $200,000 offer for the tank, which he
said probably would cost about $250,000 new.
   One thing that may discourage a potential buyer is the cost of
dismantling and moving the tower, which could cost as much as the
tower itself, city officials say.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>POCAHONTAS, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Expertise in botany isn't a requirement
to be a lawman, says Randolph County Sheriff Steve Shults.
   If it were, the sheriff noted Sunday, officers might have
noticed sooner that the five little green plants growing outside a
county courthouse door weren't tomatoes _ they were marijuana.
   ``Back in the winter, we made a drug arrest ... and marijuana
was seized growing in a flower pot. Well, we plucked the little
plant, and we dumped the dirt outside the back door,'' Shults said.
   In late April, sprouts poked through the dirt in a spot where
tomatoes used to grow.
   ``We thought it was the tomatoes, back again,'' the sheriff
said, chuckling again.
   ``Finally, a city officer said, `Are you sure those are going to
be tomato plants?' And we weren't so sure,'' the sheriff said.
   They watched the plants a while longer and decided they were
marijuana sprouted from seeds in the dirt they dumped. They were
``pulled and trashed,'' Shults said.
   ``Everybody kind of took it as a joke. And, of course, there's
nobody in the courthouse suspected of growing this marijuana.''
   Shults said dirt has always been dumped in the spot, where
plumbing work left an indentation in the soil. The practice will
continue, he said.
   ``But next time, we'll poke around in the dirt a little more,''
Shults said.
</TEXT>
