<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Cannes     05-09 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Cannes,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famed French Film Festival Back To Basics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FIONA GLEIZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paparazzi and star-watchers may be disappointed
when the 41st Cannes Film Festival opens Wednesday _ it's going
back to basics.
   Apart from the participation of Clint Eastwood and possibly
Robert Redford _both as directors rather than actors _ the famed
festival is being billed this year as a cozy gathering of movie
buffs and professionals.
   After the 40th anniversary extravaganza last year, some film
purists find the change a welcome return to the style of previous
festivals, when the films themselves outshined the stars, fancy
receptions and big deals being signed.
   The choice facing the Cannes jury each year is whether to select
films which are certain to be a commercial success, or to innovate
and bring some newcomers into the limelight. It is difficult to
achieve the right balance.
   By favoring less commercial films, the Festival runs the risk of
losing the big ones completely. If it loses, a prestigious,
high-budget film loses a lot, but a low-budget film can only gain
if it wins a glittering prize at the world-famous festival.
   Festival officials say the focus this year will be on a search
for the talent of tomorrow. The jury has decided to ``help the
cinema build its future,'' festival President Pierre Viot said at a
recent news conference.
   Fifteen countries are represented by 21 films in the main
competition.
   This year's festival will be an opportunity for film makers
outside the commercial circuit to show their worth. The jury's
selection includes many films by young directors and works from
countries just beginning to gain a reputation for their movie
industries.
   For example, China makes its Cannes debut with ``King of
Children'' by Chen Kaige, and New Zealand is represented by Vincent
Ward's ``The Navigator.''
   One of two French entries is ``Chocolat,'' a story of colonial
life in the African Cameroons. It is the first full-length film of
Claire Denis, who made her mark as assistant to German New Wave
film maker Wim Wenders.
   ``A World Apart,'' a British film directed by Chris Menges,
tells the story of apartheid in South Africa. Menges made his name
as a director of photography, working on films such as Roland
Joffe's ``Mission.''
   A more familiar name on the list of entrants is that of American
director and scenarist Paul Schrader. Known for ``American Gigolo''
and ``Mishima,'' he is represented in Cannes by ``Patty,'' based on
the 1974 kidnapping of Patricia Hearst, William Randolph Hearst's
granddaughter.
   Despite the many litte-known names, stargazers will still have a
chance of seeing a few Hollywood greats.
   Director Clint Eastwood is expected to present ``Bird,'' a
biography of the alto sax player Charlie ``Bird'' Parker.
   Robert Redford, who has been in the Soviet Union showing some of
his films, may appear in Cannes to present his new film ``The
Milagro Beanfield War.'' The feature tells the story of a tiny
village in New Mexico, where residents take up arms against big
business and the establishment.
   In an effort to cater to true movie lovers, the organizers have
even restricted the presence of television at this year's festival.
   Critics said the 1987 festival became a vehicle for the small
screen. Many televised variety shows used the festival as a
backdrop.
   Said Viot: ``We do not want the festival to become the
battleground for a (television) ratings war.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0087 </DOCNO>
