<DOCNO> AP880509-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PollutionOptimism     05-09 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pollution Optimism,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Rules on Gasoline Evaporation May Help Clean Up Hidden Air
Polluter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cities may have been made significantly
smoggier than previously predicted by an unrecognized form of auto
pollution _ a source that planned new regulations should clear up,
according to several analysts.
   The newly recognized source is evaporation of gasoline from fuel
systems while cars are running. The Environmental Protection Agency
has been assuming these ``running losses'' could be neglected in
assessing the formation of ozone, the major component of smog, from
volatile compounds like gasoline.
   New findings suggest the amount of gasoline that evaporates from
a car's fuel system when the vehicle is being used on a hot day may
be five times to 25 times greater than the amount of unburned
gasoline that is permitted to escape in exhaust: 2 grams to 10
grams per mile in ``running losses'' compared with 0.41 grams out
the tailpipe.
   Ten grams of gasoline is about half a liquid ounce.
   ``If all these things fall into place, it's logical to expect
this is a big source and another explanation that could be offered
as to why attainment (of the air quality standards) has been so
hard,'' said Tad Wysor, an engineer in EPA's Emissions Control
Technology Division in Ann Aror, Mich.
   ``Official predictions have been under-predicting'' future
improvement, said Tom Austin, a partner in Sierra Research of
Sacramento, Calif., air pollution consultants.
   All cars must pass tests for gasoline emissions while parked.
Newly proposed EPA regulations are designed to reduce this
stationary evaporation, along with vapors lost during refueling.
   They will require refiners to cut summertime gasoline volatility
_ its tendency to evaporate _ by 22 percent from the current, often
exceeded, voluntary standard. They also will require the existing
auto vapor recovery system to be enlarged to capture refueling
vapors.
   Ozone worsens breathing problems. EPA last week released the
names of 68 urban and rural areas where air did not meet the
federal ozone standard in 1987, up from the 62 on the previous
year's list.
   Though EPA said a warm summer in the East in 1987 helped push up
ozone violations, environmental groups immediately claimed that the
data showed that the smog problem was getting worse.
   EPA has known for years that today's gasoline volatility _ 11.5
pounds of vapor pressure is the summer standard in much of the
country _ will cause cars to flunk its stationary emissions test
badly. The fuel used in that test must be 9.0 pounds, the pressure
the agency wants to make the mandatory maximum.
   Nine pounds was typical of gasoline in 1975 when test
specifications were drawn up.
   Sam Leonard, director of automotive emissions control for
General Motors Corp.'s environmental activities staff, said GM has
found that emissions on one part of the stationary test are 16
times greater with 11.5 pound fuel than with 9.0 pound fuel.
   Hugh Shannon of Exxon Research Corp. outlined one explanation
for the unexpectedly high running losses at a briefing on vapor
recovery systems sponsored by the American Petroleum Institute last
week: the near-abandonment of carburetors for fuel injectors by
engine manufacturers.
   Fuel injection systems continuously recycle uninjected fuel back
to the tank. Accordig to Shannon, the returning fuel picks up heat
in the engine compartment, making fuel in the tank run 20 degrees
warmer than the outside air.
   This heat raises the pressure of the higher-volatility fuel.
That appears to overwhelm the existing charcoal cannister in the
vapor recovery system, leaving the vapor nowhere to go but to the
atmosphere.
   Leonard said he believed the running loss problem was mostly a
warm-climate phenomenon affecting ``probably less than 1 percent of
miles traveled'' nationwide.
   But Michael Walsh, a consultant often used by environmental
groups, said, ``One percent sounds like a low number to me.''
   ``The ozone problem is a warm-weather problem. ... We have a lot
of places in this country with plenty of hot days in the
summertime,'' Walsh said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CyanideDeaths     05-09 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyanide Deaths,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: Juror Received Call About Defendant's Lie-Detector Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A juror in the trial of a woman accused of
killing her husband and another woman with cyanide-laced medicine
received an anonymous telephone call saying the defendant had
failed a lie-detector test _ a detail jurors were not allowed to
hear, the judge said today.
   The anonymous caller asked the juror, ``Don't you all know that
she failed the lie detector test?'' U.S. District Judge William
Dwyer told attorneys in the case this morning.
   Dwyer called the incident ``a most regrettable occurrence, and
most irresponsible by whoever did it.'' He said he would interview
the juror before making a decision on how to proceed.
   The woman juror wrote him a letter in which she reported
receiving the phone call Friday night, Dwyer said. The juror said
she did not recognize the caller's voice, and that the caller hung
up before she could ask who it was, Dwyer said.
   The development came as jurors prepared to return to
deliberations today after a weekend off. Although they told him
Friday they were deadlocked, Dwyer urged them to keep deliberating.
The trial began its fourth week today.
   He also agreed to provide them with addition information they
requested on the legal definition of reasonable doubt.
   Today, Dwyer promised, the court reporter would read backximum sentences
of life in prison, while the maximum for
tampering is 10 years on each count.
   Mrs. Nickell's husband, Bruce Nickell, 52, and Sue Katherine
Snow, 40, died in June 1986 after swallowing cyanide-laced
Extra-Strength Excedrin capsules.
   The deaths resulted in a nationwide tampering scare and prompted
Excedrin manufacturer Bristol-Meyers to recall all its
over-the-counter drug capsules.
   Prosecutors argued that Mrs. Nickell wanted to end her marriage
and financial problems by killing her husband and collecting as
much as $176,000 in life-insurance benefits, and then tried to
cover up the crime by placing more tainted capsules in stores to
give the appearance of random tampering.
   Ms. Snow was an innocent stranger caught in the scheme, the
prosecution said.
</TEXT>
