<DOCNO> AP880509-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     05-09 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Bill Veto Could Hold Up Action on Arms Pact, Byrd Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A presidential veto of the omnibus trade bill
could hold up ratification of the U.S.-Soviet medium-range missile
treaty, Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd said Monday.
   ``Lots of things could happen'' if the president carries out his
threat to veto the 1,000-page bill, Byrd told reporters.
   He stopped short of any specific threat to hold the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces pact hostage to a presidential
signature on the trade bill. But he said an effort to override a
presidential veto could shoulder aside floor debate on the treaty.
   The treaty, which was signed last December in Washington, calls
for the elimination of all U.S. and Soviet missiles with ranges
from about 300 miles to 3,000 miles.
   President Reagan has called on the Senate to ratify the measure
by May 29, the opening date of his Moscow summit with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``When the president promises that we'll have another trade
bill, he has got to remember that a veto would take precedence over
the treaty,'' Byrd said.
   Under Senate rules, he said, House override of a trade bill veto
would automatically force senators to take up a similar effort.
Thus, debate on an override could be the order of business on the
floor on May 29, he said, with the arms pact still pending.
   ``May 29 is just a date on the calendar,'' Byrd said. ``It means
absolutely nothing to me or this Senate.''
   The trade bill was passed by Congress two weeks ago. Instead of
sending it to Reagan's desk, however, lawmakers retained it on
Capitol Hill while they attempted to make further revisions.
   The House last week passed a technical corrections resolution
that also would drop restrictions on export of Alaska oil.
   That measure simply would authorize an official known as the
enrolling clerk to dot the i's and cross the t's in the bill _ and
erase the Alaska provisions.
   Byrd said he hoped to bring up the resolution in the Senate as
soon as possible, but would need the unanimous consent of senators
to do so. He said he would discuss that with Minority Leader Bob
Dole, R-Kan.
   It was expected the Senate would take up the resolution this
week.
   Major provisions of the trade bill would streamline procedures
for use of import restrictions to aid U.S. industry and to
retaliate against international trade violations.
   Scores of other provisions range from billions of dollars in
agricultural subsidies to repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil
companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
