<HEAD>Former Japanese Prime Minister Visits Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Japanese Prime Minister Yasuhiro
Nakasone, beginning a week-long visit to the United States, paid a
courtesy call Monday on President Reagan.
   Amid trade tensions, dialogue between the United States and
Japan expanded during Nakasone's prime ministership, and the two
leaders developed a first-name, ``Ron-Yasu'' relationship.
   Nakasone, 69, remains an influential member of the Japanese Diet
(parliament) in the Liberal-Democratic Party headed by his
successor Noboru Takeshita.
   On Tuesday, Nakasone was scheduled to speak at the inauguration
of the Yasuhiro Nakasone professorship in Japanese studies at Johns
Hopkins University, created in his honor with a $1 million
endowment by the Japanese shipbuilding industry. Later appearances
were scheduled at the University of Pittsburgh and Rutgers
University.
