<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1403EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MartinJet     05-09 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Martin Jet,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Traffic Controller's Error May Have Contributed to Martin
Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An error by an air traffic controller
may have contributed to the 1987 jet crash that killed actor Dean
Paul Martin, the Riverside Press-Enterprise reported.
   A controller warning, which incorrectly gave the location of
Mount San Gorgonio, may have caused Martin to turn too sharply and
lose control of his F-4C Phantom jet, said veteran Lockheed test
pilot Tony LeVier.
   LeVier made his conclusions after reviewing an analysis by the
U.S. Air Force and Air National Guard, according to reports
obtained by the newspaper through the Freedom of Information Act.
LeVier's conclusions were published Sunday.
   Martin, a captain in the California Air National Guard and son
of entertainer Dean Martin, and his weapons officer, Capt. Ramon
Ortiz, 39, died March 21, 1987, when the jet traveling at 600 mph
crashed into a San Bernardino Mountains canyon.
   The accident report draws no conclusions about what happened
during the last seconds of Martin's flight.
   Air Force pilots and air traffic controllers declined to comment
on what might have caused the crash which killed Ortiz and the
35-year-old Martin.
   But LeVier said it is clear Martin made too sharp a left turn,
probably in a moment of panic as he feared hitting the mountain
ahead.
   If you turn the F-4 too quickly, the nose will pull the airplane
up, disrupting the plane's aerodynamics, said LeVier, who has
tested 70 aircraft during his 46-year career.
   ``The airplane simply becomes uncontrollable. The ... thing goes
ape,'' LeVier said.
   According to the accident analysis, Martin was at 11,500 feet,
flying in clouds and had not heard two previous instructions to
turn left. His plane was far off its route and heading toward the
peak. The controller reportedly told the pilot he was three miles
south of a 13,000-foot peak. But the analysis said the peak is
11,502 feet, not 13,000 feet, and Martin's aircraft was 8{ miles
from the summit, not three miles.
   Air Guard Maj. Steve Mensik, spokesman for the Guard in
Sacramento, said the controller's erroneous communication with
Martin-Ortiz was a contributing factor to the crash.
   FAA officials at Ontario International Airport said the
controller who handled the Martin-Ortiz flight committed no error.
   David Fowler, the controller's supervisor, said there were many
factors, including the work-load and weather, that might cause the
controller to miscalculate the distance of the fighter from the
mountain. He said his office has not read the latest accident
investigation report.
   A spokesman for the pilot's family called LeVier's analysis an
assumption. Mort Viner said he had heard other equally plausible
causes for the crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
