<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Shultz-Shuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0579 05-09 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0579,530</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 14 grafs new material, background; inserts byline.
CORRECTS to fourth trip, sted third, in lede.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz will make
his fourth trip to the Middle East this year in a fresh attempt to
promote Arab-Israeli peace talks, the State Department announced
today.
   ``There are problems there that need to be resolved,'' Charles
E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said in announcing that
Shultz would travel to Israel, Egypt, Jordan and Syria next month.
   Redman said Arabs and Israelis had urged Shultz to return to the
region. But he declined to say whether any of the parties had
changed their positions.
   ``All the people in the region have been very insistent on the
fact that the secretary and the administration continue these
efforts,'' Redman said.
   He said President Reagan had directed Shultz to return to the
region.
   There, Shultz again will promote a Mideast peace conference to
be followed by negotiations in two stages. The first would be
designed to provide some form of self-rule to the 1.5 million
Palestinian Arabs who live on the West Bank and in Gaza under
Israeli control. The second would deal with an overall Middle East
settlement.
   ``It is the only workable alternative,'' Redman said.
   Shultz will fly to the Middle East at the windup of the Moscow
summit meeting June 2 and then attend a meeting of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization's foreign ministers in Madrid June
9-10, said the U.S. official, who spoke only on condition of
anonymity.
   Three trips by Shultz to the Middle East this year failed to
produce peace talks. But he refuses to give up. ``Who's afraid to
struggle against odds?,'' he said at the end of the last venture in
April. ``What am I saving myself for, anyway?''
   Shultz told a Senate appropriations subcommittee two weeks ago
that ``under the right circumstances'' King Hussein of Jordan would
be agreeable to the U.S. proposal for a peace conference.
   Shultz also testified, however, that Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir had made the conference the ``centerpiece'' of his
objections to Shultz's plan.
   Shultz also was unsuccessful last month in Moscow in trying to
persuade the Soviet Union to accept a limited role in the
negotiations.
   Shamir and Shultz are opposed to giving the Soviets a chance to
shape the outline of a Mideast settlement. But Hussein is insisting
on Soviet involvement.
   On the other hand, Jordan is reluctant to negotiate with Israel
without a guarantee that it would recover all the land it lost
during the 1967 Mideast war. Shultz has advised Hussein that was
not ``in the cards.'' But he backs the idea of Israel trading some
territory on the West Bank for peace and said the future of
Jerusalem should be decided in negotiations.
   Despite the long odds, Shultz said he did not think his plan was
``fated to failure.''
   Shultz's plan called for a peace conference in mid-April, the
opening of negotiations on the Palestinians May 1 and a second
stage of talks on an overall settlement beginning Dec. 1.
   The first two deadlines have passed. But, Redman said, ``We need
to get this underway as soon as possible.''
</TEXT>
