<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola-Rebels,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebels Say They Killed 72, Shot Down Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola's U.S.-backed rebels said Monday
they killed 64 government soldiers and eight Cubans and also shot
down three Soviet-built aircraft in several attacks last week.
   Rebel casualties were given as 12 killed, 10 wounded and two
missing.
   Also Monday, a press report said South Africa's foreign minister
would meet Thursday with Angolan officials to pursue last week's
ground-breaking Angolan peace talks in London.
   South African soldiers are fighting in support of the
13-year-old rebel movement against Angola's Marxist government,
which is backed by Soviet advisers and an estimated 40,000 Cuban
troops.
   The rebel group, the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola, made Monday's claims in a statement distributed in
Lisbon. There was no independent confirmation.
   The rebels said they killed seven Cubans May 2 in an assault on
a wood-processing plant near Conde in the oil-rich northwestern
Angolan enclave of Cabinda. They said 64 Angolan soldiers were also
killed in actions across six provinces last week.
   The rebels claimed their anti-aircraft batteries shot down a
MiG-21 plane Thursday as it bombed the village of Kanamba in
southeastern Moxico province.
   They said the Cuban pilot died, and two village children were
killed by falling wreckage.
   The statement also said that two MI-17 helicopters were shot
down the previous day in the area. There was no mention of
casualties.
   The guerrillas said violence in Angola would ``continue and
increase'' until the government, the Soviet Union and Cuba agreed
to negotiate an end to the civil war. The rebels were not included
in the U.S.-brokered talks in London between delegations from
Angola, Cuba, and South Africa.
   The South African Press Association said Foreign Minister Roelof
``Pik'' Botha would meet with Angolan officials on Thursday to
follow up on those talks.
   The officials will gather in Brazzaville, Congo, according to
the official sources quoted by the press association. It said the
talks would last until Friday and that Defense Minister Magnus
Malan might accompany Botha.
   The report said the Brazzaville talks would not involve the
United States.
</TEXT>
