him at home with me and I'm very concerned about him physically.
I'm sure he'll continue the hunger strike.''
   She said she had not seen her husband privately since Friday and
police would not let her talk to him during the recess. ``I was
able to touch his cheek,'' she said.
   Soldiers fired on stone-throwing Palestinians at the Deheishe
refugee camp near Bethlehem, killing 34-year-old Ibrahim Mohammed
Haniyah, the army said. Four other Palestinians were wounded.
   A leaflet distributed late in April exhorted Palestinians to
honor Arab ``martyrs'' Monday. Israel radio said the call for a
total work and transport strike was observed.
   Most of the 100,000 Palestinian working in Israel stayed home
and streets in the occupied lands were deserted.
   In Gaza, masked youths threw stones at cars and strike
organizers used mosque loudspeakers to declare: ``Every worker who
goes to work will be punished.''
   Soldiers arrested three women from the Shati refugee camp near
Gaza and ordered them held for six months, said Khaled Kidra, their
lawyer. He said they were members of a camp women's committee and
identified one as Widad Saleh, 35 and mother of seven children.
   The army said it could not confirm the report and was
investigating.
