<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Army     05-09 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Army,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comptroller's Report Shows Deficiencies in Readiness for War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli army does not have enough shells
for its tanks and artillery, which could affect its readiness for
war, the government comptroller's office declared in a report
issued Monday.
   It also said the military does not keep close enough track of
U.S. aid.
   ``Ammunition stockpiles are a central part of army preparedness
for war,'' the report said. ``The findings of our survey show
significant malfunctions which must be rectified as soon as
possible.''
   Comptroller Yaacov Maltz presented the 983-page report at a news
conference. About one-fifth of it was devoted to the military.
   It said management problems have eroded the profitability of
Israel's large weapons industry, and investigators could not
determine exactly what use was made of $1.8 billion in U.S.
military aid in 1986 because it was lumped with other
foreign-currency expenditures.
   Maltz's report did not suggest the money was misspent but said
records of how it was used were inadequate.
   ``Some of the budget in foreign currency is allocated along with
American assistance funds, without any differentiation to monitor
what is being purchased with what money,'' it said.
   The comptroller said the investigations, conducted last year,
found shortages of essential weapons. He blamed them on cuts in the
defense budget, red tape and a need to divert funds to other
projects he did not name.
   His report said surveys found inadequate supplies of 105mm tank
shells, 155mm and 175mm artillery shells and mortars. In keeping
with army regulations, no figures were given.
   Maltz said a more detailed report was delivered to the military.
Eitan Haber, a Defense Ministry spokesman, said the army is
prohibited by law from responding publicly to such reports.
   Other parts of the Maltz document said training courses for
soldiers were inadequate and lists of ammunition storage depots
were outdated, raising questions about public safety. It cited
shortages of emergency medical supplies, food, water and shelters
in northern settlements bordering Lebanon.
   A section on the weapons industry criticized one of Israel's
leading arms developers, Rafael Armament Development Authority, for
losing money in major arms deals. Most losses are covered by the
Defense Ministry.
   It mentioned a $35 million deal by Rafael in which the military
was expected to absorb a $3.3 million loss. Instead, projected
losses had reached $11.7 million and could total nearly $15
million, according to the report.
   Because of censorship regulations it gave no further details of
the 1966 contract, but said ``the economic viability of the project
was not adequately checked.''
   Elsewhere in his report, Maltz was critical of the public health
system, which has been disrupted by strikes and other job actions
by doctors, nurses and maintenance staff. The report said more than
30,000 Israelis had to wait up to three years for operations as a
result.
</TEXT>
