<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Reax     05-09 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Reax,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Europe Welcomes Mitterrand Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western Europe welcomed the re-election of
Francois Mitterrand as president of France, and political leaders
of all persuasions sent their congratulations Monday.
   Commentators foresaw uncertainty for France with a Socialist
president and rightist-dominated Parliament, but that was the case
before the election. They complimented Mitterrand for running a
shrewd campaign and criticized the tactics of his conservative
opponent, Premier Jacques Chirac.
   Congratulations from around the world cut across ideological
lines.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl of West Germany looked forward to
continued cooperation between the two governments. His conservative
Christian Democrats said in a statement: ``The proven
Europe-oriented tandem of Kohl-Mitterrand will be able to continue
its successful work in the future.''
   Austria's Socialist chancellor, Franz Vranitzky, expressed
satisfaction that Chirac failed and praised Mitterrand's ``moderate
and statesmanlike policies.'' Another socialist, Prime Minister
Andreas Papandreou of Greece, said those policies would strengthen
his country's relations with France.
   Some conservative newspapers welcomed the re-election despite
their idealogical opposition to Mitterrand.
   ``If not more than two cheers are in order for Mr. Mitterrand's
triumph, it is hard to weep many tears of chagrin over Mr. Chirac's
defeat,'' said London's Financial Times.
   It accused Chirac of ``grotesque attempts'' to win votes:
gaining the release of French hostages in Lebanon after ``scarcely
glorious negotiations with their captors,'' ordering a bloody
attack on New Caledonian separatists and allowing a French secret
service agent convicted in the bombing of a Greenpeace
environmentalist ship to return home despite an exile agreement.
   The left-leaning Guardian said Mitterrand's victory ``is not
only deserved but also in his country's best interests as well as a
relief for France's Western allies.''
   It said of Chirac: ``The nakedness of the loser's ambition and
his readiness to mortgage French interests at home and abroad in
the pursuit of personal power finally outweighed his undisputed
talents and phenomenal energy.''
   El Pais, a Spanish center-left daily, said said Chirac ``dared
to put at risk traditional values and interests to win votes. It is
the opposite of what a responsible statesman must do.''
   Sweden's main Social Democratic paper, Aftenbladet, said the
result placed Chirac's future in doubt and seriously diminished the
legacy of Charles de Gaulle.
   ``One thing is certain,'' it said in an editorial. ``Most of the
Gaullism that has so long dominated the picture is now eliminated.''
   A conservative Belgian paper, La Libre Belgique, said: ``The
French did not let themselves be impressed by the increased
spectacles put on in recent days by a Jacques Chirac visibly on the
ropes and for whom defeat is all the more scalding.''
   In opposition to Mitterrand, said Switzerland's independent Le
Matin, ``there was nothing but unrest, divisions, sectarianism and
demagogy.''
   In the Soviet Union, leader Mikhail Gorbatchev hailed
Mitterrand's success and expressed a wish for ``our personal
contacts to play their positive role in promoting disarmament,
building the common European house, settling regional conflicts,
building trust, and improving the international climate on the
whole.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
