<HEAD>Motorists Paying Average $1 for Gallon of Gasoline</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS numbers throughout to reflect reporting error from
source. No pickup. A version also moved on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists nationwide are paying an average of
$1 a gallon for gasoline, an increase of more than a penny a gallon
over the past two weeks, an industry analyst said.
   The increase of 1.41 cents a gallon was a ``dramatically slowed
rate compared to the rises surveyed during April,'' Trilby Lundberg
said Sunday.
   The average price of gasoline was 100.25 cents a gallon,
according to the bi-weekly Lundberg Survey check of prices at about
12,000 gas stations in every state. The latest survey was completed
Saturday.
   The previous survey showed an increase of 2.67 cents a gallon in
the average price, which includes all grades, self- and full-serve
pumps, cash and credit prices and taxes.
   As of May 6, at self-service pumps prices per gallon were:
regular unleaded, 91.46 cents; premium unleaded, 105.86 cents;
regular leaded, 88.56 cents.
   At full-service pumps prices were: regular unleaded, 119.56
cents; premium unleaded, 129.50 cents; regular leaded, 115.29 cents.
   The Lundberg Survey inadvertently reported a preliminary rather
than a final set of numbers on Sunday, Ms. Lundberg said.
</TEXT>
