<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Uganda-Minister     05-09 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uganda-Minister,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Acquits Former Minister Of Terrorism Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief magistrate Monday dropped
charges against a former Cabinet minister who was arrested 19
months ago on allegations of treason and terrorism.
   Magistrate Constance Byamugisha said the state failed to produce
enough evidence against David Lwanga, who was minister of
environment protection in President Yoweri Museveni's government at
the time of his arrest in October 1986.
   Lwanga, 45, was arrested with 18 other people and charged with
plotting to forcefully overthrow Museveni's government. Museveni
seized power in January 1986 after a 5-year bush war.
   The treason charges against Lwanga were dropped last year for
lack of evidence, but police immediately re-arrested him on
terrorism charges stemming from the same case in which he was
accused of possessing a machine gun and 150 rounds of ammunition.
   Courts also have freed for lack of evidence most of the 18
people arrested with Lwanga. Among those still in jail is former
Vice President Paulo Muwanga, who faces a reduced charge of illegal
detention.
</TEXT>
