<2ND_LINE>PM-Tony Nominations, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0439,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tony Nominations Announced</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with nominees. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' ``Into the Woods''
and ``Anything Goes,'' three big musical hits, topped the list of
shows receiving Tony nominations today as the best of the 1987-88
Broadway season.
   All three productions received 10 nominations each, with
``Phantom'' and ``Into the Woods'' competing in the best musical
category and ``Anything Goes'' nominated as a revival.
   Also nominated for best musical were ``Romance@Romance'' and the
South African musical ``Sarafina!''
   ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone'' by August Wilson received six
nominations, including best play. It will compete in that coveted
category against ``A Walk in the Woods'' by Lee Blessing, ``M.
Butterfly'' by David Henry Hwang and David Mamet's
``Speed-the-Plow.''
   Nominated for best actor in a play were Derek Jacobi, ``Breaking
the Code''; John Lithgow, ``M. Butterfly''; Robert Prosky, ``A Walk
in the Woods''; and Ron Silver, ``Speed-the-Plow.''
   Nominees for best actress were Joan Allen, ``Burn This''; Blythe
Danner, ``A Streetcar Named Desire''; Frances McDormand, ``A
Streetcar Named Desire''; and Glenda Jackson, ``Macbeth.''
   For actor in a musical, the nominees were Scott Bakula,
``Romance@Romance''; David Carrel Crawford,
``The Phantom of the Opera''; and Howard McGillin, ``Anything
Goes.''
   Actress in a musical nominations went to Alison Fraser,
``Romance@Romance''; Joanna Gleason, ``Into the Woods''; Judy Kuhn,
``Chess''; and Patti LuPone, ``Anything Goes.''
   There were several surprises among the shows and performers not
nominated. Sarah Brightman, wife of Andrew Lloyd Webber who stars
in his `` Phantom of the Opera'' was not nominated for best actress
in a musical. Neither did Bernadette Peters get a nod for her role
in ``Into the Woods.''
   Madonna, making her Broadway debut in ``Speed-the-Plow,'' also
failed to get a nomination as did John Malkovich for ``Burn This''
and Christopher Plummer for the revival of ``Macbeth.''
   Also snubbed was `Chess,'' the big British musical. It received
only two nominations _ for Kuhn and Carroll _ in the acting
categories.
   The Tonys are named for actress-director Antoinette Perry, who
was active in the American Theater Wing during the 1940s.
   The winners, voted by more than 600 theater professionals, will
be announced June 5 in a program broadcast nationally on CBS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
