<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--HermanHouse     05-09 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Herman House,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woody Herman's Daughter Given Half-Interest in Band Leader's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hollywood Hills home where band leader
Woody Herman was nearly evicted shortly before his death must be
sold and half the proceeds given to his daughter, a judge ruled.
   Herman bought the home from Humphrey Bogart in 1946 for $50,000.
He and his wife gave it to their daughter, Ingrid Herman Reese, in
1982.
   But the Internal Revenue Service seized the house in 1985 to
offset a $1.6 million tax debt accrued in the 1960s via delinquent
payments by members of Herman's Thundering Herd band. The house was
sold to William Little for $99,000, a third of its value.
   Ms. Reese, who was given no notice of the IRS sale, argued she
should still hold a half interest in the house.
   Superior Court Judge Robert Mallano agreed, ruling Friday that
the IRS didn't properly notify Ms. Reese of its plans to sell the
property.
   Little had sought to evict Herman and Ms. Reese last September
for failure to pay rent. A judge intervened and Herman was allowed
to live there with his daughter until he died in October.
</TEXT>
