<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CarringtonAward     05-09 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carrington Award,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Leader Honored at Pentagon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter Lord Carrington, the outgoing secretary
general of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, was presented
the Pentagon's highest civilian award Monday and lauded as ``just
the right leader'' for the times.
   ``This ceremony represents the heartfelt tribute of one nation
among the many he served, a tribute on behalf of all citizens who
today live markedly more secure because of this man's dedication,''
said Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci, crediting Carrington with
helping secure a new arms treaty with the Soviet Union.
   Carrington was honored with the Defense Department Medal for
Distinguished Public Service during ceremonies that featured honor
guards from each U.S. armed service, a cannon salute and two bands,
including a fife and drum corps.
   Carrington responded by saying he wished he had a NATO medal
that could be presented to Carlucci and his predecessor, Caspar W.
Weinberger, in thanks for America's commitment to a free Europe.
   ``Nobody ... could fail to be impressed by the morale, by the
readiness, by the competence of the United States forces assigned
to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization,'' hen said.
   ``You should be proud of them, and we should be grateful. I know
that it is a heavy burden for the United States to keep the forces
that you have throughout the world.''
   Carrington, an Englishman who has led the 16-nation NATO
alliance since 1984, will be replaced this month by West German
Defense Minister Manfred Woerner.
   His reference to the heavy burden born by the United States
comes at a time when a growing number of congressional leaders are
demanding that America's allies in Europe along with Japan and
South Korea contribute more to the common defense.
   Carrington said he hoped the United States bore the burden
``because you believe it's in the interest of the United States as
well as in the interests of your allies _ because self-interest is
more lasting a basis than general goodwill.''
</TEXT>
