<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Germany     05-09 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Germany,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Cadet Ship Visits Haifa, First By Military Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAIFA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German cadet ship sailed into this
Mediterranean port Monday in the first visit by a German military
unit to the Jewish state.
   The West German ambassador cited the port call as an example of
solid bilateral relations.
   Some Israelis, however, said they felt uneasy at the sight of
German military men strolling through Haifa's streets.
   ``They are young people and I have nothing against them,'' said
Moshe Biermann, 54, a bank clerk who lived through World War II as
a boy in Romania.
   ``But when I see a German uniform, I still feel a stab in my
heart,'' he added as seven cadets wearing traditional
white-and-blue sailor suits passed him on Haifa's bustling main
street.
   The three-mast sailing ship Gorch Fock is in Haifa for a
five-day stay that will include a soccer match between German and
Israeli cadets, visits to Israeli families and a trip to the
Holocaust memorial Yad Vashem in Jerusalem.
   The port call in Haifa is part of an 11-month sail around the
world for the Gorch Forck before it returns to its homeport, Kiel,
in June. Stops have included France, Mexico, the United States,
Australia and Oman on the Persian Gulf.
   West German Ambassador Wilhelm Haas described the relationship
between the defense establishments of Germany and Israel as good,
and said ``the visit of the ship fits very well into this picture.''
   Israel is selling ammunition, aircraft and remote-control
vehicles to West Germany, and Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin visited Bonn last year.
   Asked about the feelings of unease expressed by some Israelis,
Haas said: ``German officers come here, as Israeli officers come to
Germany. They don't hide their uniforms. Why should they.''
   But some cadets said they were apprehensive before coming to
Israel.
   ``It's a mixed feeling,'' said Peter Fromm, 21, of Duesseldorf.
``We don't know what the reaction is going to be. We were advised
that if there was a problem, we should remain calm.''
   Added Uwe Kroll, 23, of Bremerhaven: ``We are not here for our
amusement, like in Australia, where we had one party after another.
Here especially, you feel like a representative of Germany.''
   As the cadets strolled through the steep streets to buy film and
souvenirs, some passers-by stopped and turned when they heard the
young sailors speaking German.
   ``Who are they, Germans?'' one passer-by asked this reporter.
``You shouldn't be talking to them after what they have done to our
people.''
   During a beer break at a downtown cafe, the cadets said that
before their arrival, they were briefed about Israel, especially
the Holocaust in which six million Jews were killed by Nazi Germany.
   ``We were told that nearly every family in Haifa was affected by
the Holocaust,'' said Kroll, whose grandfather served in Hitler's
navy. He said he would like to meet an Israeli family, but that he
had to stand guard at the time such visits are scheduled.
   ``We talked about the Holocaust, about the guilt of the German
people,'' said Karl Friedrich Schinkel, a West German navy
spokesman who briefed the cadets. ``We didn't prettify anything.''
   An Israeli navy vessel was docked next to the Gorch Fock, and an
Israeli reserve soldier, who would only identify himself as Rafi,
walked over to take a closer look at the 90-meter-long white barque
equipped with 23 sails.
   ``It's beautiful,'' he said. ``I don't care if it's from
Germany, or Holland or any other place.''
   Added another Israeli soldier: ``Time has passed. We are buying
their cars and their machines. But we will never forget.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0120 </DOCNO>
