<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PowerPlantFire     05-09 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Power Plant Fire,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Heavily Damages Coal-Fired Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALATKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two units of a coal-powered electric plant
were knocked out of service Monday when a spectacular fire roared
through one unit, but no serious injuries were reported, a company
spokesman said.
   ``Unit 2 suffered minor damage and should be back in operation
in about a week, but Unit 1 sustained major damage,'' said Jeff
Fela, a spokesman for Seminole Electric Cooperative in Tampa.
   Fela said Monday it was too early to estimate the damage.
   The fire erupted early Monday in the seal oil system in the
turbine generator. Seal oil is a lubricating fluid that forms a
seal that keeps hydrogen gas from escaping into the atmosphere,
Fela said. Hydrogen gas is a standard coolant for electric
generators.
   One person, believed to be a worker at the $1.2 billion Seminole
Electric Cooperative Plant, was treated at the scene for unknown
injuries, said Capt. James White of the Palatka Fire Department.
   Fire crews expected to be on the scene most of Monday, spraying
down hot spots, said Maj. Paul Usina of the Putnam County Sheriff's
Office.
   The two 600-megawatt coal-fired generators are located on a
2,000-acre site six miles north of Palatka.
   The fire ``was all through the building, from the bottom up, but
it was more or less contained on the higher floors by our men,''
Palatka fire dispatcher Elizabeth Ward said.
   The fire was not expected to have any impact on power to
customers of Seminole, Fela said.
</TEXT>
