<2ND_LINE>AM-Refinery Blast,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search For Victim Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORCO, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forensic specialists identified another body
Monday from the Shell Oil Co. refinery explosion, and emergency
crews searched for a final missing person, company officials said.
   Six Shell employees are known dead, and 42 were injured when the
gasoline-refining unit blew up here and caught fire before dawn
Thursday.
   A seventh Shell worker has yet to be found. The blast damaged at
least 250 homes in Norco and broke windows 20 miles away in New
Orleans.
   The dead man identified Monday was Roland Satterlee, 35, of
LaPlace, said Shell spokeswoman Sarah Colletti. His was one of
three badly burned bodies recovered from the plant Friday.
   FBI forensics specialists joined in the recovery effort Sunday
and are helping to identify the victims.
   ``They're directing us in moving rubble and debris so we don't
disturb anything underneath. They'll help us find the missing
employee, hopefully,'' Colletti said.
   Listed Monday as missing or among the unidentified dead were
Jimmy Poche, 36, of Harahan; John Moisant, 38, of New Orleans; and
Bill Coles, 28, LaPlace.
   The refinery won't resume operations until cleanup and repairs
are finished, but some small boilers were started up Monday for
maintenance, Colletti said.
   Shell officials have said the company's 1,600 employees will be
kept on the job cleaning and restoring the plant until it reopens.
   The blast's cause remains unknown.
