<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoPhones     05-09 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-No Phones,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weekend Blaze Keeps Phones Silent; Major Airports Affected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weekend fire at an Illinois Bell switching
station kept telephones idle for 35,000 customers in Chicago's
western suburbs Monday and caused delays at major airports.
   No remedies were expected until at least midweek, Illinois Bell
officials said.
   Crews at the Federal Aviation Administration's control center in
Aurora were using a backup phone system, but the lack of full
service meant controllers had to stagger the arrival of flights by
20 miles.
   ``Major trouble, major,'' said FAA spokesman Mort Edelstein.
   Fire departments from 15 communities battled the fire at the
Hinsdale station, west of Chicago, for three hours before it was
brought under control Sunday evening.
   The facility houses computerized switching equipment that serves
customers by connecting their local calls directly to the number
dialed and routing long-distance calls.
   Customers in the suburbs of Hinsdale, Willowbrook, Clarendon
Hills and parts of Darien, Burr Ridge and unincorporated Oak Brook
lost all service, said Illinois Bell spokeswoman Laura Littel.
   Some pockets farther south had limited phone service because
some of their calls go through the Hinsdale station, Ms. Littel
said.
   She said phones were dead for 35,000 customers, but the number
of consumers with only partial interruption was unknown.
   The cause of the fire was unknown.
   At O'Hare International Airport, Edelstein said 55 to 60
incoming flights were allowed per hour, down from the normal level
of 75. The Aurora air traffic control center also handles traffic
for Chicago's Midway Airport.
   O'Hare's biggest tenant, United Airlines, had delays of at least
30 minutes, spokesman Matt Gonring said.
</TEXT>
