<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1719EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ecuador     05-09 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ecuador's Left-Leaning President-Elect Reassures Business Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Rodrigo Borja, a
center-left politician, urged business leaders not to be frightened
by his election despite his criticism of the free market policies
of his predecessor.
   ``Our victory should not make anyone nervous. No one should
start a financial panic. We intend to respect private enterprise,''
he said late Sunday night after winning the presidency.
   Borja, a 52-year-old law professor, defeated Abdala Bucaram, a
36-year-old populist, by a margin of 52.8 percent to 47.2 percent.
   The president-elect, whose four-year term begins Aug. 10, will
replace Leon Febres Cordero, an arch-conservative who has
championed free enterprise and has been Washington's closest ally
in South America.
   Borja, who lost a bitterly-fought runoff contest to Febres
Cordero in 1984, has pledged to reverse his opponent's free-market
policies and seek close ties with the non-aligned Third World
movement.
   ``Now it is Dr. Borja's turn to show that his political
alternative is valid,'' Interior Minister Heinz Moeller said Monday.
   Borja will face the challenge of governing a small nation that
has seen its oil-generated prosperity fade away in the past few
years as the price of petroleum has dropped.
   Oil has been the main source of income for Ecuador since the
early 1970s.
   The country's foreign reserves have dropped to under $50
million, and Febres Cordero, who took pride in keeping up payments
on Ecuador's $9.2 billion foreign debt, was forced to stop
repayments last year after devastating earthquakes crippled the
country's oil industry for nearly six months.
   The economy shrank by 3.5 percent in 1987 and annual inflation
is running at nearly 70 percent, the highest level in five years.
Less than half of the work force is fully employed.
   Borja's Democratic Left Party espouses a social democratic
doctrine.
   He has said he will impose exchange controls, restrict imports
to save dollar reserves and regulate prices of basic consumer goods
to fight inflation.
   He also announced plans for a more restrictive foreign
investment policy and a moratorium on foreign debt payments if
creditors do not agree to negotiate easier terms.
   ``Either we pay the debt or we develop the country. We can't do
both at the same time,'' he said in a recent meeting with foreign
correspondents.
   Febres Cordero's policies ran against the trend of
left-of-center governments in South America, but Borja's victory
pushes Ecuador back into the regional pattern.
   U.S. officials say they expect no problems in dealing with
Borja, who is widely described as highly intelligent, hard-working
and honest.
   But analysts say demands from organized labor for huge wage
increases and for quick economic solutions will prove to be a
formidable test for the new president, who even his backers say he
may not have the strong leadership ability needed to keep the
confidence of the population while he seeks solutions.
   Borja reflected a sense of the limitations of his power when he
said Sunday night: ``The condition of the country does not permit
miracles.''
   ``Borja's biggest weakness is his lack of charisma,'' said
Benjamin Ortiz, editor of the independent Quito newspaper Hy.
   But Borja, in contrast to the stormy political climate
surrounding Febres Cordero, is expected to enjoy a relatively
tranquil relationship with Congress, which his Democratic Left
Party controls.
   Febres Cordero had engaged in bitter fights with an
opposition-controlled Congress throughout his term, during which
opposition legislators talked about impeaching him.
</TEXT>
