<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Drugs     05-09 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Drugs,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panels Given June 21 Deadline to Draft Drug Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright announced Monday he
has set a June 21 deadline for committees to draft legislation to
step up the government's fight against illegal drugs.
   Wright, D-Texas, said he hoped the package would build upon the
anti-drug programs Congress passed two years ago, just before the
last election. But he denied it was just an election-year ploy.
   ``Anything we do that people like'' is denigrated as motivated
by re-election politics, he said, but that should not deter
lawmakers. ``We cannot sit by as the United States loses the war
against drugs,'' he said.
   Congress has already been attaching anti-drug amendments to
existing legislation.
   The Senate voted to bypass Congress' commitment to limit overall
spending in order to add $2.6 billion to its fiscal 1989 budget for
an upcoming anti-drug bill.
   The House has voted for additional money for the Coast Guard and
new powers for the military to intercept drugs coming into the
country.
   The legislation Wright said would be completed next month would
be like the Senate proposals, with money for programs such as
treatment of addicts, law enforcement and prison construction. He
said the cost had not yet been determined.
   ``We'll see how much it takes and then we'll find ways to pay
for it,'' he said.
   Wright said House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., would
be working with Republicans to make the bill bipartisan. However,
Republicans said the Democrats already were drafting the
legislation without GOP input.
   While the Democratic proposals center on increased federal
spending, Republicans are drafting alternatives that would increase
penalties for drug offenders, including capital punishment for
traffickers involved in deaths.
</TEXT>
