<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AfghanRockets     05-09 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan Rockets,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass reports rockets kill 11 in Kabul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels fired rockets into the Afghanistan capital
of Kabul Monday, killing at least 11 people and most of the victims
were children, the Soviet news agency Tass reported.
   The unusually heavy attack on Kabul came less than a week before
the Soviet Union is to begin withdrawing its 115,000 military
personnel from Afghanistan. The Soviets sent the troops into the
country beginning in December 1979 to help the Marxist government
battle anti-communist rebels.
   In a short dispatch from Kabul, Tass said 17 rockets were fired
into densely populated districts of the city ringed by the Hindu
Kush mountains.
   ``The missiles fell mainly between houses on lawns where
children were playing,'' Tass said. ``According to preliminary
data, not less than 11 people were killed, mainly children,'' and
12 people were wounded.
   The Soviets are to start removing their troops Sunday under
U.N.-mediated accords between Pakistan and Afghanistan that were
signed April 14 in Geneva.
   Under the agreement, the Soviet military units are to leave
Afghanistan within nine months. Soviet officials have said
privately they want all the troops home by the end of the year.
   Rebel rocket strikes on Kabul used to occur frequently, but
Western diplomats based there told visiting reporters in April the
attacks became less frequent in recent months as Soviet and Afghan
troops gained more control of areas aound the capital.
   In Islamabad, Pakistan, rebel leaders issued a statement saying
guerrillas had captured another government post in northern
Afghanistan as Soviet-Afghan forces continued vacating positions.
   It said rebels seized the headquarters of an administrative
district in Takhar province near the Soviet border Sunday. That
brought to nine the number of government strongholds the rebels
claime they have captured since late April.
   Millions of Afghan refugees who fled the war are living in camps
in Pakistan and most of the rebel organizations have headquarters
in Pakistan.
</TEXT>
