<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Algeria     05-09 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Algeria,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US to Seek Information From Algeria About Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior U.S. diplomat headed for Algeria on
Monday to seek information about the whereabouts of American
hostages in Lebanon and to discuss relations with the United States.
   Deputy Secretary of State John Whitehead said he also will ask
Algerian authorities to cooperate with the United States in
apprehending the hijackers who took over a Kuwaiti jetliner last
month and flew it to Algiers, killing two hostages along the way.
   Whitehead spoke to foreign correspondents at the U.S.
Information Agency's Foreign Press Center in Washington hours
before leaving for a week-long swing through Algeria, Tunisia and
Morocco.
   ``We'll be talking, particularly to the Algerians, about the
hostage situation, to determine if there's anything they known
about our American hostages still in captivity and to see if
there's any role that they can play,'' Whitehead said.
   There are nine Americans among 18 foreigners believed held by
pro-Iranian radicals in Lebanon. Algeria, with its history of
international mediation, acted as a broker in securing the 1981
release of 52 American hostages held by Iranians at the U.S.
embassy in Tehran for more than a year.
   Whitehead will likely discuss the fate of the U.S. hostages when
he meets next week in Paris with French officials. France
negotiated the release of its remaining three hostages in Lebanon
last week.
   Softening recent U.S. criticism of Algeria, Whitehead said the
United States ``had no basis to criticize in any severe way''
Algeria's handling of the Kuwaiti hijacking. Algerian officials
mediated an end to the 16-day hijacking, freeing the 31 hostages
and spiriting the hijackers to an unknown destinations.
   U.S. officials initially expressed anger that the Algerians
allowed the hijackers to get away.
   Whitehead said the Algerians had to balance the desire to catch
the hijackers with concern for the safety of the hostages. ``It was
a difficult job,'' he said.
   ``We hope Algeria will participate with us in further efforts to
apprehend the hijackers,'' Whitehead added.
   The United State still does not know whether the hijackers left
Algiers, he said, despite news reports that the seven or nine
pirates flew to Syria and from there made their way to Lebanon.
   Discussing his planned talks in Tunisia, Whitehead said he would
make it clear to the authorities there that the United States did
not have any role in last month's assassination of Khalil Wazir.
Wazir, the number two man in the Palestine Liberation Organization
is believed to have been killed by Israeli commandos.
</TEXT>
