<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Caliguiri 1stLd-Writethru a0677 05-09 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Caliguiri, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Says Goodbye To Late Mayor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 3-4 with 2 grafs to update with governor among
mourners.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City government came to a standstill Monday
while thousands of people streamed by the coffin of Richard S.
Caliguiri in the City-County Building, where he governed Pittsburgh.
   ``I didn't know him personally, but I liked him. He was one of
the nicest persons. I'm going to start crying and I'm not even
related to him,'' said Mary Ronschke, 75, a Pittsburgh resident who
waited in line.
   An estimated 2,000 people viewed the flag-draped coffin in the
first hour after the doors were opened. Gov. Robert Casey was among
those who filed past the coffin.
   Caliguiri's heart stopped Friday from what his doctors said was
an accumulation of protein caused by the rare, incurable disease,
amyloidosis. He was 56 and in his 12th year as mayor. He was
credited with steering Pittsburgh through the collapse of
steelmaking in the area.
   Monday was an official day of mourning. City offices, courts,
public and parochial schools, and buildings were closed.
   After a funeral Mass on Tuesday, Caliguiri will be buried two
plots away from his mother, Catherine, in Calvary Cemetery in
Pittsburgh.
   ``It'll be quite a while before we have another one like him,''
said Jerry Esposito. ``I don't think anybody perceived what a
symbol this young, unpretentious man came to be. He remained true
to the common man, kept his honesty and his values.''
   Esposito, an emergency medical services official, recalled
Caliguiri's efforts as a City Council member to help improve
ambulance service in western Pennsylvania.
   ``Richard was the first member of this city body who was
perceptive enough to know that that was an issue worth giving his
support and understanding to,'' he said. ``This young man had the
courage to support that issue through all the turmoils and battles
that ensued.
   ``This city now enjoys as fine a paramedic protection as any
municipality in the country.''
   William Parker, social service administrator for the
Neighborhood Centers Association, said he liked Caliguiri for
something else the mayor helped give the city.
   ``He has never done anything for me personally, but I appreciate
the fact that he was able to keep our streets in good condition,''
he said. ``He had begun to make Pittsburgh a city that one could be
proud of. I often have visitors from out of town, and I'm just so
pleased to be able to show them the progress that has been made.''
   ``He was a gift at a time when we needed a gift,'' state Labor
Department spokesman Mike Acquaviva said as he waited in line.
   Acquaviva credited Caliguiri for his reaction to the collapse of
steelmaking in the cradle of the steel industry.
   ``Most politicians would be defensive when things are crumbling,
but he drew upon both the public and private sector to make some
pretty bold initiatives,'' Acquaviva said. ``When we deal with
unemployment numbers, we're dealing with numbers, but he looked at
it as people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
