<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1812EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DairyFarmers     05-09 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dairy Farmers,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Milk Producers Federation Asks Farmers to Lobby Against
Price-Support Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nation Milk Producers Federation asked
dairy farmers Monday to join its lobbying effort to stop a further
cut in federal milk price supports scheduled by the Agriculture
Department next year.
   The 72-year-old federation, which represents most of the
nation's dairy cooperatives, wants Agriculture Secretary Richard E.
Lyng to use his authority in the 1985 farm law to cancel the next
reduction in milk supports on Jan. 1, 1989, in favor of an
alternate plan to cut production.
   ``Enough is enough,'' said federation president Tom Camerlo of
Canon City, Colo. ``Dairy farmers are tired of suffering continual
price reductions after having done more to address federal policy
concerns than any segment of U.S. agriculture.''
   Camerlo said Lyng has the authority to set up a new whole-herd
buyout or a diversion program, both of which have been used in
recent years to trim U.S. milk production.
   However, Lyng has been steadfast against reviving the buyout and
diversion programs as an alternative to the reduction in price
supports.
   Camerlo and other federation officials told a news conference at
the National Press Club that the 50-cent reduction scheduled for
next Jan. 1 would put the milk support level at $10.10 per 100
pounds of milk, the lowest since 1979.
   ``Dairy farmers will have to live at 1979 income levels with
1989 costs,'' he said.
   Milk price supports have been lowered progressively from a
record high of $13.10 per 100 pounds since 1983 to help discourage
surplus production. A diversion plan to pay farmers for cutting
back production, and a whole-herd buyout, or Dairy Termination
Program, also were used.
   The 18-month whole-herd buyout program began April 1, 1986, and
continued through October 1987. More than 1.22 million dairy cows,
heifers and calves were sent to market by thousands of producers
who agreed to quit the dairy business for at least five years.
   About 38 percent of the buyout program's cost of $1.8 billion
was paid by dairy farmers themselves who were charged assessments
on milk they sold. Similar arrangements helped hold down costs on
the earlier diversion plan.
   Camerlo said the 50-cent reduction next Jan. 1 would come as
milk production costs, including feed, are on the upswing. The
two-way crunch would add up next year to a 37 percent slide in
dairy farm income from 1987 levels, he said.
   Dairy farmers have contributed $2.9 billion in assessments since
1983 to reduce the costs of their programs by 50 percent overall,
Camerlo said.
   Federation leaders have met frequently with USDA officials,
including Lyng, in an attempt to persuade them to abandon the path
of lower milk supports.
   ``The secretary has been consistent, as has his staff, that they
will cut the price,'' Camerlo said. `` They do not intend to
utilize the authority that they have in the '85 act to implement a
whole-herd or Dairy Termination Program.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1854EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NOW-Democrats 1stLd-Writethru a0578 05-09 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NOW-Democrats, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0578,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NOW Releases List of Women for Convention Posts, Vice Presidency</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds names from the list, inserting 1 graf after 5th graf
pvs, On the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Organization for Women on Monday
released a list of prominent Democratic women and said the
Democratic Party should consider them for key convention roles as
well as for the vice presidential nomination.
   NOW also urged the Democrats to continue official support of the
Equal Rights Amendment, abortion rights and gay rights, and to add
a new platform plank promoting women candidates.
   ``We think it would be a very serious mistake'' to eliminate all
potentially controversial issues from the platform, NOW President
Molly Yard said at a news conference a day before she was scheduled
to testify before the party's platform committee.
   Yard distributed a list of 47 prominent Democratic women, saying
she wants the party to consider them as national convention
speakers and officers as well as potential running mates.
   On the list are current and former office-holders from Congress
down to city council, including former New York Rep. Geraldine
Ferraro, who was chosen by Walter F. Mondale as his running mate in
1984. Women's groups, including NOW, heavily lobbied Mondale to put
a woman on the ticket.
   Others on the list include Rep. Patricia Schroeder of Colorado,
Vermont Gov. Madeleine M. Kunin, Rep. Barbara Kennelly of
Connecticut, Houston Mayor Kathy Whitmire, former San Francisco
Mayor Dianne Feinstein and Sen. Barbara Mikulski of Maryland.
   Asked which vice presidential nominees would be acceptable or
unacceptable to NOW this year, former NOW chief Eleanor Smeal named
Sen. Sam Nunn as a negative example.
   Citing the Georgia senator's support for banning abortion and
for an ERA only with amendments, she said, ``His position on
women's issues would not be called exemplary.''
   ``We want both parties to consider a woman vice presidential
candidate,'' Smeal said. ``There are plenty of prospective
candidates out there who are women and we think they should be
considered seriously.''
   Smeal and Yard said they are confident ERA, abortion and gay
rights, as well as others supporting child care, family leave, pay
equity and a minimum wage hike, will remain in the platform.
   ``They don't have the votes to delete these planks. They're just
not there,'' Smeal said. She said there would be a strong feminist
contingent at the Atlanta convention in July.
   Smeal said she would introduce a new platform plank requiring
equal representation of women candidates in primaries. She noted
the Democrats already have a rule requiring equal numbers of men
and women on committees and at conventions.
   Under her proposal, endorsements by Democratic organizations
would have to be split 50-50 between male and female candidates.
She said she intends to press it at the Republican convention as
well.
   Smeal said the current system amounts to ``incumbent protection
clubs'' that give people ``30 years of job security whether they're
doing the job or not. ... This is just suicide to have a policy
that is keeping their decisionmakers virtually all white men.''
   Democratic leaders, including party chairman Paul Kirk, have
said they may try to win a brief platform acceptable to all
Democrats that excludes specific mention of controversial topics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
