<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SovietDissidents 1stLd-Writethru a0663 05-09 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Dissidents, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissidents Seized, But Others Create Alternate Political Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with witnesses'
accounts of police breaking down cottage doors, arresting people.
No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police broke down the doors of a country cottage
where a dissident group planned to meet and arrested five people
Monday. Sources said 70 other activists met nearby and founded an
alternative party to the Communist Party.
   The new group calls itself the Democratic Union. It seeks a
multiparty parliamentary democracy in the Soviet Union, independent
trade unions, a new constitution and withdrawal of Soviet troops
from Eastern Europe and areas of the present Soviet Union seized in
World War II.
   Over the weekend, 60 of its supporters were reported arrested in
Moscow and one of the group's founders, Yuri Mityunov, said Monday
that 14 remained in jail after being arrested Sunday night.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has called for more
democratic election procedures, including multiple-candidate
elections. But the Communist Party he heads has given no sign that
it will accept any organized opposition to its monopoly on
political power, which is enshrined in the Soviet constitution.
   Andrei Babitsky, an editor of the dissident journal Glasnost,
said uniformed and plainclothes police encircled a cottage in the
woods near the village of Kratovo, 25 miles southeast of the
capital, where the Democratic Union planned to meet Monday
afternoon.
   The two-floor wooden cottage has been used for meetings of the
staff of Glasnost, an unofficial publication that takes its title
from the Russian word for openness. Gorbachev has used glasnost to
describe some of his reforms.
   ``A militia officer asked to see our identification documents,
but we refused, saying there was no grounds,'' Babitsky said in a
telephone interview. ``He then went for reinforcements, and about
50 uniformed militia, plainclothesmen and KGB officers suddenly
appeared. They had obviously been waiting nearby.''
   Sergei Grigoryants, a former political prisoner who is the
founding editor of Glasnost, was arrested on the lawn outside,
Babitsky said. ``We closed all five doors to the dacha, but police
broke them in,'' he added.
   Babitsky said he was arrested along with Yuri Petrovsky, who
also works with Glasnost; Viktor Kuzin, a founder of the Democratic
Union, and a man known only as Volodya who Babitsky said was in the
vicinity of the cottage by chance.
   Babitsky said he was held for almost nine hours without being
charged, then released by police shortly before 9 p.m. with no
explanation.
   Another dissident was in the country house, but fled before he
could be detained, another Glasnost editor, Andrei Krivov, said in
a telephone interview Monday night.
   Krivov said people who talked to Grigoryants at the police
station in Ilinskoye, near Kratovo, reported that Grigoryants ``was
frisked, his clothes were ripped, and a large sum of money he was
carrying was taken.''
   Mityunov reported by telephone that about 70 members of the
Democratic Union, kept from meeting at the cottage, gathered at a
nearby rural club.
   ``In a half-hour, they adopted the basic program for the party,
a declaration and a charter,'' he said.
   ``I think the formation of the party is a big event in the
unification of forces to fight against the bureaucratic
totalitarian regime,'' said Mityunov, a former member of the
Communist Party who was fired from his editorial job on state-run
Radio Moscow in 1986.
   Babitsky said he learned from Grigoryants' wife Tamara that the
Glasnost editor-in-chief was sentenced to seven days in jail for
resisting authorities. ``I saw him arrested, and he did not such
thing,'' Babitsky said.
   Petrovsky, Kuzin and the man known as Volodya received five-day
jail terms, but the dissidents group did not know on what charges,
Babitsky said.
   The Kratovo cottage was sealed by police and newspapers and
books inside may have been taken away by investigators, Babitsky
said.
   `I fear this action may be the defeat of `Glasnost,''' he added.
   The typewritten journal began appearing last year.
   Kratovo is located in a region foreigners are barred by law from
visiting.
   The Soviet constitution calls the Communist Party the ``leading
and guiding force of Soviet society and the nucleus of its
political system.''
   Although new dissident groups and independent publications have
sprung up up throughout the country since hundreds of political
prisoners were freed in early 1987, authorities have crushed
efforts to form an opposition to the Communist Party.
</TEXT>
