<HEAD>Foley Flattered But Not Seeking Veep Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IDAHO FALLS, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley of
Washington is sidestepping suggestions from Idaho Democrats and
others that he be the party's vice presidential nominee this fall.
   Foley, in Idaho Falls for a Democratic gathering over the
weekend, said he was flattered to have his name mentioned, but
``what I'd like to do is stay in the House of Representatives.''
   He did not, however, rule out the possibility of being part of
the Democratic ticket, saying only that that the decision will
belong to the presidential nominee.
   Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus says Foley could fit in well with the
party's hopes for carrying the West in the presidential election.
   ``I'm not saying (Massachusetts Gov. Michael) Dukakis would have
to have Foley to win the West,'' said the governor, who formally
endorsed Dukakis last week. ``But it would make it much easier if
he had someone of that stature.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Robertson Backer Warns of Defections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pat Robertson supporter says Vice
President George Bush could lose voters in November if the Georgia
Republican Party fails to resolve complaints by Robertson backers.
   A party credentials committee met in Columbus on Saturday but
took no action on appeals concerning disqualifications of delegates
to the upcoming state convention. Most of the appeals were filed by
Robertson supporters.
   ``If it's not settled to our satisfaction, we may not vote for
Bush,'' said John Spencer, coordinator of Muscogee County Americans
for Robertson. ``We may write in another candidate ... Robertson or
Dole or Kemp.''
   The party has disqualified 928 delegates out of 2,300 to attend
the state convention in Albany May 20-21. Robertson backers contend
party regulars are trying to keep them out of the convention by
invoking trivial and previously unenforced rules, such as one
requiring proof of advertising of county conventions.
   Of the 30 national convention delegates chosen earlier at
district conventions, 20 were party regulars and 10 were Robertson
supporters.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Casey Endorses Dukakis For President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Robert P. Casey, who declined to
endorse a Democratic presidential candidate before last month's
Pennsylvania primary, said Monday that Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis is the best man for the job.
   In a statement released by his office, Casey endorsed Dukakis as
``the man who has demonstrated the consistency, the experience, the
intelligence and the drive not only to be a good candidate for
president, but to be a great president as well.''
   Casey said Dukakis and Jesse Jackson, the remaining Democratic
candidate, have both ``continued to speak to the needs and
interests, the hopes and dreams of the American people.''
   In his statement, Casey said Dukakis has gained valuable
experience as a governor.
   ``Mike Dukakis knows what it's like to balance a budget, a feat
the Republican administration has never accomplished, despite all
its rhetoric to the contrary,'' Casey said. ``Mike Dukakis knows
how to bring together a wide array of constituencies to enact
programs which serve the needs of people.''
</TEXT>
