<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Hostage     05-09 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Hostage,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostages' Greatest Fear Is Commando Raid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American hostage Terry Anderson's greatest fear is
a commando raid against his captors in Lebanon, an action that
would mean his certain death, a Frenchman who shared a cell with
Anderson said Monday.
   Marcel Fontaine, 45, a diplomat released last week after nearly
three years of captivity, said he and Anderson were in the same
cell for six months and frequently spoke of the possibility that
either the French or the Americans would turn to military action.
   ``We were afraid,'' Fontaine told Anderson's sister, Peggy Say
of Batavia, N.Y., during a meeting in his home. ``Every time
anybody knocked on the door, two guards immediately stepped in,
pointed guns at us and waited for whoever was going to come in.
   ``There is no chance that any commandos would ever get in
without us being killed. We were all of us always afraid that there
would be a commando raid by the French or the Americans.''
   Mrs. Say arrived in Paris Monday to meet with Fontaine and two
other French hostages released Wednesday in Beirut _ journalist
Jean-Paul Kauffmann and diplomat Marcel Carton.
   Anderson, 40, chief Middle East Correspondent for The Associated
Press, was kidnapped in West Beirut March 16, 1985, by pro-Iranian
Lebnanese and is the longest held Western hostage in Lebanon.
Lebanese kidnappers are holding 18 foreigners, including nine
Americans.
   Fontaine said Anderson does not know that his father and his
brother have died since he has been in captivity. The Frenchman
said he knew of those deaths because he had heard of them earlier
on the radio, but he didn't tell Anderson for fear it would have a
serious effect on his morale.
   Probably the second greatest worry of the hostages, said
Fontaine, is becoming seriously ill. He said no medical treatment
is allowed, and if they should suffer a serious ailment, they would
simply die.
   That is what happened to another Frenchman, Michel Seurat. The
Islamic Jihad organization, which claims to be holding Anderson and
others, claimed Seurat was killed. But the recently returned
Frenchmen said he died of illness, probably cancer.
   Fontaine said Anderson's morale is high. The diplomat frequently
praised Anderson's courage. He said Anderson exercises
continuously, walking round and round in his cell to keep fit.
   Fontaine said he began teaching Anderson French, and he has
learned to read it rather well. Anderson, in turn, taught Fontaine
English.
</TEXT>
