<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope 1stLd-Writethru a0635 05-09 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0635,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Ends Uruguay Visit, Flies to Bolivia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-5 Pope arrives in La Paz. Pick up 5th graf: On
his four-nation... with minor editing to conform.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede SALTO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II arrived Monday in
Bolivia, South America's poorest country, flying here from Uruguay
on his four-nation tour.
   Thousands of people, including many peasants in Indian dress and
the traditional bowler hats, welcomed the pontiff at the La Paz
airport, 13,150 feet above sea level and ringed by snow-capped
Andean peaks.
   The pope arrived from Montevideo, Uruguay, aboard a Boeing 727
of the Bolivian state airline.
   The jetliner's oxygen level was reduced to prepare John Paul for
his visit to high-altitude Bolivia.
   A Vatican advance team had already been sent to the mountainous
capital to test the possible effects of kneeling and kissing the
ground at such an altitude.
   On his four-nation, 12-day visit to South America, which began
Friday, the 67-year-old pontiff was also scheduled to travel to
Peru and Paraguay.
   The pope's schedule calls for five days in Bolivia where
government austerity measures that eliminated 20,000-percent annual
inflation have caused serious labor unrest due to mass layoffs. The
country is also a major source of the world's cocaine.
   In Uruguay, where the pope made an overnight stop in March 1987,
John Paul asked for a renewal of religious fervor and for more
priests. This small nation of 3 million is South America's most
secularized society, with an agnostic president and only lukewarm
interest in church affairs.
   After arriving in Uruguay Saturday, the pope visited the towns
of Melo near Brazil, Florida outside the capital of Montevideo and
Salto on the northwestern frontier with Argentina.
   John Paul was presented with gifts ranging from a live fawn to a
nest of a local birds.
   In Salto, Uruguay's second-largest city with 77,000 residents,
John Paul spoke at a mass Monday about his hopes for a renewal of
evangelization in South America, saying ``religious fervor is not
fanaticism but is coherent with Christian life.''
   Earlier Monday, John Paul met privately in Montevideo with
President Julio Sanguinetti, an agnostic. Sanguinetti, a highly
popular leader, became president in 1985 when he restored democracy
to Uruguay after 12 years of harsh military rule.
   Papal aides said in Uruguay that the pope has been buoyed by the
official reception he has received in a country where divorce has
been legal since 1907 and Christmas is called ``Families Day'' to
avoid religious connotations.
   ``We hope this is the start of a new climate,'' said a Vatican
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The pope's tour is his ninth to Latin America since he became
head of the 860-million-member Roman Catholic Church nearly 10
years ago. John Paul ha traveled abroad on papal pilgrimages 37
times.
   This trip takes the pontiff to Bolivia and Paraguay for the
first time. He visited Peru in 1985.
   John Paul is scheduled to spend his 68th birthday in Paraguay on
May 18 and returns to Rome on May 19.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-Heinlein     05-09 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Heinlein,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acclaimed Science Fiction Author Dies At 80</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY33</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARMEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert A. Heinlein, whose science fiction
explored the future while questioning the morals and beliefs of the
present, has died at the age of 80, it was announced Monday.
   Heinlein, who added the word ``grok'' to the language and
dreamed up the water bed, was ranked with Isaac Asimov and Arthur
C. Clarke among the greatest practitioners of science fiction. His
fiction explored the seeming contraditions of his own philosophy,
which embraced libertarianism and a passionate faith in the
military.
   He died of heart failure Sunday at his home in this small
tourist community about 130 miles south of San Francisco, said
Terry Rice of the Monterey County Coroner's office.
   Heinlein had suffered for many years from emphysema and had
undergone numerous operations, including one to relieve restricted
blood flow to his brain.
   ``Robert Heinlein has been writing science fiction now for 48
years and from the very start he was recognized as a grand
master,'' Asimov said Monday. ``In 1975 the Science Fiction Writers
of America set up just such an award, and he was the first to get
it. There was no argument, much like George Washington becoming the
first president.''
   Asimov said he and Heinlein had served together in Philadelphia
during World War II, during Heinlein's second Navy hitch, and
``formed a close friendship wich never entirely broke up.''
   His favorite bit of Heinlein writing was the opening to ``Door
Into Summer,'' in which ``he described a cat better than anyone has
ever described a cat. The work that impressed me the most was
`Solution Unsatisfactory,' written before the Manhattan Project, in
which he accurately described the current nuclear stalemate.''
   Robert Anson Heinlein was born in Butler, Mo., on July 7, 1907.
He graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy and served for five years,
but was forced to retire after contracting tuberculosis.
   Flat broke after a failed campaign for the California
legislature in 1938, Heinlein saw an ad in Thrilling Wonder Stories
magazine offering a $50 prize for a story by an amateur. Instead of
entering that contest, Heinlein sent his first story to Astounding
Science Fiction magazine, which paid him $70.
   His books were written in a spare, matter-of-fact style but
presented readers with thoughtful questions about how life should
be lived.
   In his most popular novel, ``Stranger in a Strange Land,''
Valentine Michael Smith is a human raised by Martians. Smith
challenged his home planet's values with his own priorities,
including universal free love, nudity and many sexual encounters.
He also ``discorporated'' or made disappear authority figures he
felt were bad.
   The book, which became something of a text for the
counter-culture of the 1960s, introduced ``grok,'' Heinlein's word
for intuitive understanding. In that book, Heinlein also introduced
the water bed.
   In ``Methuselah's Children'' and later in other books, character
Lazarus Long provides more food for thought. For instance, on how
to get help, Long says: ``Never appeal to a man's better nature. He
may not have one. Invoking his self-interest gives you more
leverage.''
   Another Heinlein invention, now in common use worldwide, is a
device known as a ``waldo,'' named for the principal character in
the short story, ``Magic, Inc.'' Waldo, who was handicapped,
invented remote-controlled robot arms.
   Two years ago, Heinlein told writer Eric Hoffman that ``writers
don't know how to retire.''
   ``The bottom line,'' he said then, ``is `pay to the order of
...' with the right figures in the blanks. That's the most
important measure of a writer's work. Freelance writing is free
enterprise.''
   Heinlein won numerous awards for his novels and short stories
and was popular with both children and adults, and he was not at
all ashamed that much of his work was for ``pulp'' magazines, under
his own name or pseudonyms.
   ``They didn't want it good,'' Heinlein told The New York Times
in 1980, ``they wanted it Wednesday.''
   Heinlein won the Best Science Fiction Novel award from the World
Science Fiction Convention in 1956, 1959, 1961 and 1966; the Nebula
award from the Science Fiction Writers of America in 1975; and an
unprecedented four Hugo awards, in 1956 for ``Double Star,'' in
1959 for ``Starship Troopers,'' in 1961 for ``Stranger in a Strange
Land'' and in 1966 for ``The Moon is a Harsh Mistress.''
   Other works include ``The Green Hills of Earth'' and ``Puppet
Masters.''
   Heinlein is survived by his wife, Virginia, whom he married in
1948. The couple had no children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
