<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1947EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra     05-09 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers for Hakim, Secord, Drop Insistence on Seeing Ultra-Secret
Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense has removed a minor obstacle to
the review of classified documents in the Iran-Contra conspiracy
case, according to a transcript of a closed court hearing released
Monday.
   Retired Marine Lt. Col. Oliver L. North and former national
security adviser John M. Poindexter and their lawyers will review a
small group of ultra-sensitive documents that government security
officials were reluctant to show to arms dealers Albert Hakim and
retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord.
   Gesell is allowing the defense to review the material to verify
prosecution claims it is not relevant to charges that the four
defendants conspired to illegally divert profits from the U.S.-Iran
arms sales to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   ``We don't want to be viewed as obstructing this process,''
Hakim's lawyer N. Richard Janis told U.S. District Judge Gerhard A.
Gesell, according to the official court transcript of Friday's
closed hearing.
   Janis said he and Secord's lawyer, James E. Sharp, agreed to
abide by the determination of the other defense lawyers that the
documents are not relevant to the case.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh estimated that between 35
and 70 pages of sensitive material not relevant to the case have
been identified by his office and government security experts.
   The defense concession does not dispose of the larger problem of
disclosing sensitive information that may be determined to be
relevant when the case goes to trial.
   Gesell issued an order Monday giving Walsh until May 30 to draw
up a list of secret documents he wants to use as evidence that
won't be declassified by the government.
   Under the Classified Information Procedures Act, only the
government can declassify documents before they are introduced into
evidence. If Walsh is unable to persuade government agencies to
declassify important evidence, Gesell could drop some or all of the
charges.
   No trial date has been set.
   At a hearing two weeks ago, Walsh described some of the most
sensitive documents in his possession as containing information
about U.S. intelligence and military planning. The disclosure of
some secrets could subject some people in the Middle East to
torture or death, Walsh had said, apparently referring to hostages
held there.
   Gesell has ruled that each defendant has the right to examine
the classified material that Walsh has deposited in a secure
facility where the defense lawyers are sifting through a massive
amount of classified documents compiled by the prosecution.
   But government security officials have refused Secord and Hakim
access because the material contains a small number of pages of
ultra-sensitive material.
   Hakim, an Iranian-born U.S. citizen, has never had a security
clearance and Secord has not had one since he left government
several years ago.
   An interdepartmental task force is reviewing some 300,000 pages
of classified material. More than 105,000 pages of documents have
already been put in the secure room that was constructed by the
Justice Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
