<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0650 05-09 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,0876</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>65 Killed In 4th Day Of Battle For Shiite Slums</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT two grafs after 7th graf pvs, The battle ... UPDATING
with truce committees in action. Picks up 8th graf pvs, Lebanon's
1.2 ... with minor editing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival militias fought hand-to-hand Monday
for control of Shiite slums and rained shells on each other's
positions in the grim shantytowns despite Syrian army orders to
stop the four days of carnage.
   Police said 65 people were killed and 150 wounded Monday,
bringing total casualties in the Shiite territorial war to 154 dead
and 367 wounded.
   The thunder of shellfire rolled over the city all day and into
the night. Gunmen atop racing ambulances fired into the air to
clear traffic so the wounded could reach hospitals. Radio stations
appealed for blood donations.
   Doctors confirmed allegations by both sides that wounded
fighters were dragged from ambulances and hospitals and slaughtered
by their rivals.
   Fighting began Friday between the moderate militia Amal, which
means Hope and has Syria's backing, and the radical, pro-Iranian
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   Syria has 25,000 soldiers in Lebanon, about 7,500 in Beirut. It
is the main power broker after 13 years of civil war but is being
challenged by Iran, which the Syrians support in its 8-year-old war
with Iraq.
   The battle for control of Beirut's southern slums, where an
estimated 250,000 Shiites live, raised fears about the fate of 18
foreign hostages. They include nine Americans and most are believed
held by Hezbollah-affiliated kidnappers in the 16-square-mile
Shiite enclave.
   Late Monday, six committees, each grouping a Syrian officer, an
Iranian Embassy official, a representative of Amal and one from
Hezbollah, were formed and charged with enforcing a cease-fire.
   Fighting eased as the committees drove into the slums, but
sporadic bursts of cannon and machine-gun fire echoed in the region
well into the night.
   Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiites are its largest sect. With Syria's
blessing, Amal crushed Hezbollah last month in predominantly Shiite
south Lebanon. The four-day battle cost 62 lives and 150 people
were wounded.
   Among Monday's victims were three Amal militiamen killed with
axes. Their bodies were taken to Beirut's American University
Hospital. Officials there said it was full to capacity and could
not handle more casualties.
   An Amal spokesman said privately the three ``were axed to death
after they were taken prisoner by Hezbollah.''
   Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kenaan, Syrian military intelligence chief in
Lebanon, said he told both factions to stop fighting.
   ``It is impermissible to let the current state of affairs
continue,'' he told reporters after meetings with government,
religious and militia leaders.
   Asked whether Syrian troops would intervene, he said: ``We hope
it won't come to that, but we shall not allow the bloodshed to
continue.''
   Syria moved 7,500 soldiers into Moslem west Beirut in February
1987 to end a monthslong power struggle between Amal, led by
Justice Minister Nabih Berri, and Walid Jumblatt's Druse militia.
   Senior Moslem clerics urged Syria to repeat in the southern
slums ``the successful west Beirut experiment of the past year.''
   Gun battles were reported in al-Sahel Hospital. A doctor said
some militiamen forced surgeons at gunpoint to operate on dead
comrades ``to bring them to life.''
   An American University Hospital employee said: ``We take only
victims needing emergency surgery, then send them to recuperate''
at inadequately equipped clinics in Druse-held mountains outside
Beirut.
   Police said Hezbollah fighters, wearing red headbands, appeared
to have gained ground Monday in the densely populated Ghobeiri, Bir
el-Abed, Hay Madi and Mesharafieh districts.
   Amal's fighters, whose headbands are green or black, control
most of Haret Hreik, Mreiji, Roweiss, Shiyah and Kasskass, a police
spokesman said.
   ``Hezbollah has established control over half of the slums,'' he
said. ``It only controlled one-third before the current fighting.''
   The spokesman, whose name cannot be used because of regulations,
said Amal had an advantage because it and the Syrians control
entrances to the slums.
   ``This is Amal's trump card,'' he said. ``It can move in
supplies and reinforcements from several other areas at will, while
Hezbollah cannot get a fly in or out.''
   An Amal fighter in the Shiyah district, Tarek Saad, aimed his
shoulder-fired rocket launcher toward Hay Madi and said to
reporters: ``God willing, we will liberate Hay Madi and Bir el-Abed
and free all the foreign hostages. We know they are imprisoned
there.''
   There has been no word on the hostages since the fighting began.
   Police said about half the slum residents had fled to west
Beirut, camping on sidewalks or taking refuge in mosques, sports
stadiums or schools.
   Ahmed Kurdi, an Associated Press photo technician, was trapped
with his wife and six children Friday in a shelter in Bir el-Abed,
but escaped Monday.
   ``Shells rained nonstop around us,'' he said. ``Kids screamed
and there was no way to comfort them or feed them.''
   When fighting abated for a short time Monday, Kurdi said, ``I
told my wife `This is our chance to get out.' We did, dodging
sniper fire as we ran out of Bir el-Abed.''
</TEXT>
