<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wedtech-Meese     05-09 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wedtech-Meese,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Levin Asks Reynolds To Detail Any Inaccuracies in Report
Criticizing Meese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate subcommittee chairman challenged the
counselor to Attorney General Edwin Meese III on Monday to detail
any inaccuracies in the panel's bipartisan report criticizing
Meese's involvement with scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp.
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., sent William Bradford Reynolds a copy
of the 244-page report, urging him in a letter to ``kindly inform
us'' of any incorrect information, and pointing out that the report
was the work of five Democrats and four Republicans.
   The report accuses Meese of violating White House ethics policy.
   Reynolds on Sunday branded the report as ``sleaze,'' and said
the policy went into effect after ``the Wedtech thing was referred
over to the attorney general.''
   However, the Senate report noted that memos sent to Meese from
his longtime friend E. Robert Wallach about Wedtech came to
then-White House counselor Meese in 1982 as well as in 1981. The
White House policy barring contact by White House staff with
procurement officers about a contract in which a friend has a
financial interest took effect in October 1981.
   The report is based on ``really a very egregious, incorrect
statement of facts,'' said Reynolds, who also is assistant attorney
general in charge of the Justice Department's civil rights division.
   Reynolds made his comments in an appearance on the CBS News
program ``Face the Nation.''
   ``I don't know whether Reynolds has received the report and
letter (from Levin), but, as usual, he will respond in due
course,'' said Justice Department spokesman Terry Eastland.
   Meese has acknowledged intervening on behalf of the South Bronx,
N.Y., defense contractor to ensure that the company receiving a
fair hearing from the Army in connection with a $32 million no-bid
contract that eventually, after intercession by Meese's office, was
given to Wedtech. The Army initially had opposed giving the work to
Wedtech, saying the company's price was too high.
   Meese's involvement with Wedtech triggered a criminal
investigation of the attorney general last May 11.
</TEXT>
