<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Sikhs 2ndLd-Writethru   05-09 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0674,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikhs, Security Forces Battle at Golden Temple; 5 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-2 ... CORRECTING in 2nd graf from Tuesday to
Monday. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Militants began ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY27</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,500 government troops Monday
fought a gun battle with extremists inside Sikhism's holiest shrine
and sealed off the temple. Police said at least five people were
killed and five others wounded.
   Witnesses said the fighting continued late Monday.
   Militants began shooting from the Golden Temple after they
spotted officers inspecting their positions from outside the
temple. Security forces fired back with light machine guns, said
Baldev Singh, superintendent of police in Amritsar.
   Sikh radicals have used the complex as a haven before. In June
1984, the army raided it. More than 1,200 people, mostly Sikhs,
were killed.
   Less than four months later, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi was
assassinated by two of her Sikh bodyguards, setting off anti-Sikh
riots in which more than 2,000 people were killed.
   On Monday, Amritsar district police chief Suresh Arona said two
civilians and three suspected militants were seen lying in and near
the shrine.
   One of the civilians, a woman, identified as Dilip Kaur, an
80-year-old Sikh, later died in a hospital.
   Venod Kumar, 30, a Hindu who worked with the local Red Cross,
was killed when he was caught in the crossfire just outside the
main entrance of the temple, police said.
   Authorities imposed an indefinite curfew on the walled central
district of Amritsar to keep civilians indoors.
   Extremists have been fighting since 1982 for a separate Sikh
nation in the northern agricultural province of Punjab, and
thousands of people have been killed.Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million people but are a majority in Punjab.
   The Sikh religion was founded five centuries ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam. Sikhs claim Hindus, the vast
majority in India, discriminate against them.
   Also Monday, United News of India news agency reported that five
people were killed by Sikh extremists in overnight attacks
elsewhere in Punjab. On Saturday, Sikh gunmen killed 13 Hindu
migrant workers at a wedding party in neighboring Haryana state.
   At least 941 people have been reported slain so far this year _
more than twice the rate in 1987, when Sikh extremists killed 1,000
people. Most victims were Hindus or moderate Sikhs.
   A government statement released Monday in Chandigarh, capital of
Punjab, called the shooting from inside the Golden Temple a ``great
provocation.''
   At the shrine, troopers sealed off exits and kept people from
entering.
   ``We may have to take drastic action against the terrorists. We
are watching,'' Arora said.
   Among Monday's injured was S.S. Virk, deputy inspector-general
of the paramilitary Central Reserve Police Force, authorities said.
The United News of India said Virk, a Sikh, was out of danger after
surgery for a bullet wound in the chin.
   He and other senior security officers had gone to posts on
rooftops near the Golden Temple to look at a bunker Sikh militants
were building at the western end of the complex, police reported.
   They said gunfire came from at least 16 points in the temple
complex, mainly from Chinese-made AK-47 assault rifles.
   Violence has increased since Jasbir Singh Rode was made the
Golden Temple's chief priest early in March. He had been jailed
under government anti-terrorism rules but released in an effort by
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, the late leader's son, to placate Sikh
extremists and encourage them to negotiate.
   Since Rode's return, there have been persistent reports that the
radicals were building bunkers and firing ports in the complex.
Amritsar residents said they heard midnight target-practice
sessions in the shrine.
</TEXT>
