<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Regan-Reverberations 5thLd-Writethru a0717 05-09 1062</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Regan-Reverberations, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0717,1,010</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Quoted as Calling Regan Book `Bunch of Falsehoods'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 22nd graf bgng ``Earlier, Fitzwater'' to restore dropped
matter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan was quoted Monday as telling
a luncheon guest that Donald T. Regan's tell-all book was ``a bunch
of falsehoods'' and the White House denounced it as a ``breach of
confidence.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater refused to say whether
astrology was used to determine the president's schedule, but said
first lady Nancy Reagan would continue to consult an astrologer and
said ``she has that right.''
   As Regan's new insider account went on sale, syndicated
columnist Carl Rowan, who had lunch with Reagan on Monday, quoted
the president as calling the book by his former chief of staff ``a
bunch of falsehoods'' and saying, ```I'll be damned if I'll just
stand by and let them railroad my wife.'''
   ``He claims, for example, that Mrs. Reagan never asked him to
fire former CIA Director (William J.) Casey,'' Rowan said of his
conversation with Reagan. ``He says Mrs. Reagan didn't fire Regan.
... He says Regan got ticked off when somebody leaked the story
that Howard Baker was going to replace him as chief of staff.''
   Regan was ousted as White House chief of staff in early 1987,
reportedly at the urging of Mrs. Reagan, among others.
   Rowan, in an interview on WUSA-TV in Washington, also said the
president told him a three-month period of inactivity following his
July 1985 colon cancer surgery ``had nothing to with astrology,''
as maintained in the book.
   He said Reagan told him Mrs. Reagan ``was only trying to get
Regan to honor what the doctors had put on paper, and said the
president could or couldn't do.
   ``He said she was very upset and had said to him that she feared
that she had brought all this down on his head, and he had told
her, `No, honey, I brought all this down on your head by taking
this job,''' Rowan quoted Reagan as saying.
   Fitzwater, meanwhile, repeatedly sidestepped requests to say
whether Mrs. Reagan's stargazing has had any connection with her
husband's public outings.
   ``Every first lady since Martha Washington has had a role in the
presidency,'' Fitzwater said, ``and I don't think anyone denies a
role of a wife and her husband. ... But I'm not going to try to
characterize any specific responsibilities.''
   ``The new book by Donald Regan is a kiss-and-tell story in the
mold of all books that seek to exploit the presidency or the first
family for personal self-interest,'' Fitzwater said.
   Regan's book, ``For the Record,'' depicted a passive president
unduly influenced by his wife on many matters, including the
scheduling of public appearances. Regan suggested that Mrs.
Reagan's interference in scheduling harmed her husband's presidency
at times.
   Fitzwater said Reagan feels ``deep personal disappointment with
this breach of confidence.'' Mrs. Reagan was quoted by her press
secretary as saying, ``I was taken aback by the vengefulness of the
attack. It comes through to me that Don Regan doesn't really like
me.''
   Asked about a weekend White House statement labeling his book as
a product of ``vindictiveness and revenge,'' Regan responded in an
NBC-TV interview, ``They ought to know it when they see it.''
   White House officials have acknowledged Mrs. Reagan's interest
in astrology, which it said was heightened in the aftermath of the
March 30, 1981, assassination attempt on Reagan.
   But the officials never have conceded that astrology was a
factor in setting Reagan's schedule _ as Regan alleges in his book.
   As some contents of the book became public late last week,
Reagan emphatically denied that astrology played any role in policy
decisions.
   At the conclusion of a Rose Garden ceremony Monday honoring
small business executives, Reagan was asked whether astrology
played any role in the making of his schedule.
   ``It can't, because it never has,'' Reagan said.
   Fitzwater quickly told reporters the president had misunderstood
the question, and had thought he was being asked the more general
question of astrology's role in policy decisions.
   Reagan's answer, the spokesman said, should be taken as a
reiteration of the president's statement of last Friday, in which
Reagan denied using stargazing in the decision-making process.
   Earlier, Fitzwater was pressed during a news briefing to say
whether astrology still plays a role in deciding the president's
schedule and public appearances.
   Both Fitzwater and Elaine Crispen, the first lady's press
secretary, said Mrs. Reagan will continue to consult with an
astrologist, who has been identified as San Francisco socialite
Joan Quiqley.
   ``She doesn't plan to stop talking to her,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
She said these conversations will take place on an ``as-needed
basis. ... It's not a daily, weekly, type of thing.''
   An administration official, discussing the atmosphere at the
White House on grounds he remain unidentified, said ``I'm not
noticing any disruptions'' as a result of the furor over the Regan
book.
   Fitzwater denied that the brouhaha was adversely affecting
Reagan's ability to perform.
   ``The president's management style and his personal methods of
leadership and management have been discussed in any number of
forums,'' the spokesman said. ``The bottom line is that they work.''
   Fitzwater's predecessor, Larry Speakes, who touched off a furor
with his earlier book acknowledging that he had fabricated quotes
in Reagan's name, said Monday he had some qualms about the newest
revelations.
   ``Who's to say his style isn't the best,'' Speakes said in a
Cable News Network interview. ``He had a good grip on the
presidency. He managed it just right and it worked well with one
notable exception _ Iran-Contra.''
   Fitzwater repeatedly suggested that reporters were blowing the
stargazing matter out of proportion.
   ``Why does every newspaper in America carry a horoscope? Does
every editor and publisher think it's unwieldy? As a personal
comfort, millions of people look to astrology,'' Fitzwater said.
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell, a staunch Reagan political supporter,
expressed dismay over the allegations in the Regan book.
   ``I'm sincerely hopeful that Mr. Regan was exaggerating or
misstating the facts,'' Falwell said in a statement issued by his
office.
   ``As one who believes in God as the creator of the universe, it
is incomprehensible to me to think of consulting the stars rather
than their maker,'' he said. ``A belief in God and a belief in
astrology cannot be reconciled.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
