<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-09 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hail Peppers Michigan, Ohio Valley</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms developed Monday over lower Michigan, Indiana and
western Ohio, producing hail in many communities, while other parts
of the Midwest had rain and gusty winds.
   One-inch-diameter hail was reported in Indiana west of
Greensburg, at Warren and north of Batesville. Hail the size of
quarters fell in parts of Madison County, in east-central Indiana,
and southwest of Muncie.
   Nickel-sized hail fell near Napoleon in northwest Ohio, and
dime-sized hail was reported near Greenville in west-central Ohio.
   Reports of pea- to marble-sized hail were received from across
much of southern Michigan. A resident of Buchanan, Mich., near
South Bend, Ind., reported his yard was covered with
half-inch-diameter hail late Monday morning.
   A thunderstorm at Haggerstown, Ind., was accompanied by 50 mph
winds, small hail and heavy rain.
   Tornado watches were in effect until Monday evening for
southeast lower Michigan, most of Ohio, southeast Indiana and
north-central Kentucky.
   On Sunday as many as 82 tornadoes swept through the Midwest.
There were few injuries, but one man was killed when high wind
collapsed a building under construction in Indiana.
   Elsewhere, Monday, showers fell from western New York across
western Pennsylvania and West Virginia to the southern Appalachians.
   Light rain was scattered over the upper Mississippi Valley.
Spotty showers were reported in western Montana and northern
California.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included three-tenths of an inch at Duluth and Hibbing, Minn., and
about a quarter-inch at Glenview Naval Air Station near Chicago;
Saginaw, Mich.; Fort Wayne, Ind.; and Rochester, Minn.
   The rain at Rochester was accompanied by wind gusting to 46 mph.
Winds were gusty Monday afternoon from the northern Plains to the
upper and middle Mississippi Valley.
   Skies were clear or partly cloudy from the Great Plains to the
West Coast, over the lower Mississippi Valley, the Gulf Coast and
along the East Coast to New England.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42 degrees at
Yellowstone, Wyo., to 97 degrees at Junction, Texas. The morning
low was 20 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Tuesday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms along
the Gulf Coast and East Coast states and in the northern
Appalachians, scattered showers from the central Appalachians to
the eastern Great Lakes and showers and a few thunderstorms in
parts of Washington and eastern Oregon.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the 60s or 70s across
most of the nation, except 80s from the south Atlantic Coast states
across the Gulf Coast, southern Plains and Southwestern desert to
interior California and 90s in parts of southwest Texas and
southern California and Arizona deserts.
</TEXT>
