<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-ChemicalWeapons     05-09 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Chemical Weapons,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Condemns Chemical Weapons Use in Iran-Iraq War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council on Monday condemned
the use of chemical weapons in the Iran-Iraq war and called on the
warring parties to refrain from future use of the outlawed arms.
   The resolution was passed unanimously by the 15-member council.
   Iran has pushed for Security Council condemnation of Iraq for
using chemical weapons. Diplomats said Iran was displeased that the
resolution did not single out Iraq.
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters later told a news conference
the United States has evidence that both sides are using chemical
weapons.
   He said the use of chemical weapons and the ``war of the
cities'' missile attacks on Tehran, Baghdad and other cities
complicated U.S. efforts to impose sanctions and an arms embargo
against Iran for refusing a truce.
   Walters said the horror of the recent use of chemical weapons
underscores the urgency of a negotiated settlement in the
7{-year-old war and the need to implement a U.N. cease-fire
resolution.
   The council resolution called on all countries to impose strict
controls on the export of chemical-weapons materials to both Iran
and Iraq and noted that a Geneva protocol of 1925 bans the use of
chemical arms.
   West Germany, Italy and Japan sponsored the measure.
   The meeting was called to discuss Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar's April 25 report on charges of chemical weapons use by
both sides. The U.N. chief sent a physician from Geneva to visit
both Iran and Iraq and examine victims of chemical attacks.
   Each side accused the other of using chemical weapons and Iran
claims Iraq killed 5,000 people, mostly Iraqi Kurds, in a chemical
attack on the Iranian-held Halabja territory of Iraq.
   Iraq did not deny the charge and said it would use all necessary
means to repel Iranian forces. It also accused Iran of using
chemical weapons.
   The secretary-general's report did not blame one side or the
other, but said evidence existed in both countries of the use of
chemical weapons.
</TEXT>
