<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlantBlast    05-09 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Blast, </2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Formal Disaster Declaration Asked, Executive Buried</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Richard Bryan formally sought
federal disaster aid Monday for a community battered by a fuel
plant explosion, while a funeral was held for one of two plant
executives killed in last week's massive blasts.
   Classes resume in 11 of the 12 schools damaged Wednesday in the
series of thunderous explosions, which are estimated to have caused
nearly $73 million in damage.
   The blasts injured 326 people and destroyed nearly 3 million
pounds of the ammonium perchlorate oxidizer manufactured for the
Air Force's Titan missile program.
   Company counsel Keith Rooker said his firm has been the sole
supplier to the Titan rocket program since its inception over 20
years ago and has been the principal supplier to the space shuttle
program.
   Bryan asked for a federal disaster declaration in a letter to
President Reagan outlining the destruction caused by explosions at
the Pacific Engineering and Production Co. ammonium perchlorate
plant.
   Bob King, the state director of emergency management, said the
estimate included $54.5 million in damage to more than 8,000 homes
surrounding the plant and $17.4 million for the two plants and
other businesses.
   Verne Paule, a Federal Emergency Management Agency spokesman in
San Francisco, said a disaster declaration might not be warranted
because an estimated 90 percent of the damage was covered by
private insurance.
   Seven investigators have been assigned to analyze videotapes and
still photographs taken of the explosions along with evidence from
the debris, said Clark County Fire Department spokesman Bob
Leinbach.
   ``Basically we're taking things very gingerly,'' said Leinbach.
``We're concerned about life safety. We want to make sure what we
touch and move is the right thing to do.''
   A funeral was held Monday for plant manager Bruce Halker, whose
body was found 25 yards from the front entrance to the plant.
   Another executive, company controller Roy Westerfield, was
killed, but his body has not been found.
   Company officials are scheduled to meet with Department of
Defense and NASA officials sometime this week in Washington, where
they will seek emergency help in rebuilding the plant at a site
outside the Las Vegas Valley.
   A second ammonium perchlorate plant remained closed Monday while
its owners, the Kerr-McGee Corp., wait to see what caused the
Pacific Engineering explosions. The plant, the only other in the
country to produce the chemical, is about a mile from the
demolished plant.
</TEXT>
