05-09 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0704-744,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Reaches Guilty Verdicts On 20 of 23 Counts in Bombing,
Standoff</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf and 8th graf ``The jury'' to CLARIFY that Mrs.
Singer acquitted of three charges, picking up 9th graf ``Swapp's
brother...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Prress Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury Monday found four members
of a polygamist clan guilty of 20 of 23 counts stemming from the
bombing of a Mormon chapel and 13-day standoff with police that
left a corrections official dead.
   The jury, deliberating 25 hours over four days, found clan
matriarch Vickie Singer innocent of one count of attempted murder
of FBI agents and two firearms charges, including possession of a
sawed-off shotgun. She was convicted on five counts.
   On the charges of attempted murder against the other three, the
jury returned guilty verdicts in the second-degree, meaning the
panel did not find the crimes premeditated.
   U.S. District Judge Bruce Jenkins scheduled sentencing July 1.
   The siege at the clan's farm in Marion by 100 lawmen ended in a
shootout Jan. 28 that killed state Corrections Lt. Fred House and
injured clan leader Addam Swapp.
   Swapp, 27, was found guilty of maliciously damaging the church
building; attempting to kill FBI agents; assaulting, resisting,
impeding, intimidating and interfering with federal agents; and
possession of an unregistered bomb.
   He also was found guilty of a corollary charge of use of a bomb
on the malicious damage count and two counts of use of a firearm
linked to the assault and attempted murder charges.
   The jury found Mrs. Singer, 45, guilty of the same charges, with
the exception of the attempted murder charge and the corollary
firearms charge.
   Swapp's brother, Jonathan Swapp, 21, and Mrs. Singer's son, John
Timothy Singer, 21, were found guilty of assault-resistance and
attempted murder charges and the two accompanying firearms counts.
   ``We've already won the victory!'' Addam Swapp shouted to
reporters as he was led into court. But there was little
discernible reaction when the verdicts were read.
   ``We were very pleased and satisfied,'' said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Richard Lambert.
   The maximum penalty for attempting to kill federal agents is 20
years, 10 years for bombing the chapel. The corollary firearms and
use-of-a-bomb charges carry minimum-mandatory five-year penalties.
Assaulting federal agents and possession of a bomb each carry
maximum 10-year prison terms.
   Jury deliberations began Wednesday afternoon.
   Prosecutors called 67 witnesses, while the defense called only
three witnesses, including the buckskin-clad Addam Swapp, who
tearfully and defiantly defended the clan's actions.
   Addam Swapp admitted he bombed the Kamas Stake Center on Jan. 16
with 87 sticks of dynamite, but insisted he never fired at any of
the authorities who surrounded the 2{-acre farm in a standoff often
punctuated with gunfire.
   No charges have been filed in House's death, which authorities
have linked to the wheelchair-bound John Timothy Singer. But
Assistant Attorney General Creighton Horton III said his office
intends next week to file state murder charges against an
unspecified number of the defendants.
   The government's final word in the case came Wednesday as U.S.
Attorney Brent Ward denounced the clan as ``a band of outlaws'' who
committed the crimes in the name of religion.
   ``Trust in the Lord but pass me my M-1 rifle,'' Ward said of
Addam Swapp.
   While admitting that Mrs. Singer my not have directly
participated in crimes, prosecutors charged her with the most
counts, alleging her aiding and abetting of family members made her
just as culpable.
   ``She wasn't exactly sitting back in a rocking chair in her
bedroom crocheting and reading Scriptures,'' Ward said.
   Clan members maintained the bombing and standoff were ordered by
God as a sign of the impending collapse of church, state and
nation, but also were intended to draw attention to the 1979
slaying of polygamist patriarch John Singer, Mrs. Singer's husband
and Swapp's father-in-law.
   Singer was shot following an 18-day standoff at the same farm by
authorities trying to arrest him on warrants stemming from his
refusal to send his children to public schools and his defiance of
a court order that he relinquish the children of his second wife to
their father.
   The family contended Singer was murdered in a ``church-state
conspiracy.''
   ``I guess you could say it started back in 1973 when John Singer
took his children out of public schools,'' Addam Swapp testified.
</TEXT>
