<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope 3dLd-Writethru a0748 05-09 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 3d Ld - Writethru, a0748,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope in Bolivia, Appeals for Hope</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 4 grafs after 7th graf pvs, The pontiff ... with
incident indicating pope's weariness. Picks up 8th graf pvs,
Dealers in ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II began a tour of South
America's poorest country Monday with an appeal to its people ``not
to lose hope.''
   ``I will spend five days among you, sharing your aspirations,
seeing first-hand this nation stricken by poverty and a lack of
development and resources,'' he said in an arrival speech at the La
Paz airport, which is 13,150 feet above sea level and ringed by
snow-capped Andean peaks.
   President Victor Paz Estenssoro said in a welcoming speech the
visit would help bolster the flagging spirits of Bolivians.
   ``You come at a time when Bolivia is suffering bitter tests that
could weaken its spirit or perhaps sink it into a state of
desperation,'' the 80-year-old president said.
   He said technological and scientific advances had heightened
aspirations of the Third World without providing the means to
fulfill them. ``The Bolivian people have perhaps been more harshly
punished than most in this respect,'' he said,
   Thousands of people, including many peasants in colorful Indian
dress and traditional bowler hats, greeted the Roman Catholic
leader at the airport. He arrived from Uruguay on a Boeing 727 of
the state airline Lloyd Aereo Boliviano at 5:16 p.m.
   The pontiff, a skier, spoke in a strong voice and showed no
outward signs of being affected by altitude sickness, which
Bolivians call ``sorocche.'' La Paz is the world's highest capital
and the altitude makes many visitors uncomfortable, if not ill.
   However, in a meeting with Bolivia's 39 bishops at the end of
the day, the pope seemed to be wearying. Bishop Julio Terrazas,
head of the local episcopal conference, did not deliver a prepared
speech to the pontiff because ``we see that the pope is tired.''
   ``I believe these words have no place right now because of the
weariness that your first day here has caused to the Holy Father,''
Terrazas said to the pope. He instead handed the pope a copy of the
speech.
   In the text of Terrazas' speech, he told the pope Bolivia
suffers from ``a situation of injustice that consumes thousands of
brothers in degrading misery and inhumane unemployment. To this are
added other ills such as delinquency, immorality and drug
trafficking and other social calamaities that constitute a
devastating scourge to the very being of our people.''
   The pope was spending the night in the papal nuncio's residence.
   Dealers in compressed oxygen said church officials rented
several tanks and face-masks for use if needed by the papal
entourage.
   To review the military honor guard and groups of white-smocked
schoolgirls at the airport, the pope rode in a green army jeep
rather than taking the long walk.
   From the airport the papal caravan descended to La Paz, which is
11,930 feet above the sea in a mountain ravine.
   The vehicles moved down a cliffside highway that was lined by
tens of thousands of people. Crowds cheered and waved banners of
yellow and white, the Vatican colors, and the yellow, red and green
Bolivian flag.
   Peasant shacks perched precariously on the mountainsides were
brilliant white, freshly painted by their owners. The city
government offered special tax incentives to those who painted
their homes.
   John Paul, standing in the glass booth of the popemobile,
traveled 11 miles through the city center to the papal nuncio's
residence, where he is staying.
   He will spend five days in Bolivia, the second and longest stop
on his four-nation tour, which began Friday in Uruguay and will
include visits to Peru and Paraguay. He returns to Rome on May 18.
   The pontiff will visit seven Bolivian cities ranging from the
tin mining center of Oruro, devastated by mine closures, to the
lowland boom town of Santa Cruz, a center of cattle ranching,
agriculture and cocaine trafficking.
   Government austerity measures eliminated an annual inflation
rate of 20,000 percent in Bolivia, but they caused serious labor
unrest because of mass layoffs. The country is also a major source
of coca leaves, the raw material for cocaine.
   This visit is the pope's tour ninth to Latin America since he
became head of the 860-million-member Roman Catholic Church nearly
10 years ago. He has made 37 pilgrimages abroad from the Vatican.
   John Paul is scheduled to spend his 68th birthday in Paraguay on
May 18.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
