<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 3rdLd-Writethru a0716 05-09 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0716,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Democratic Race Remains Tight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with more on Jackson in Nebraska</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEB RIECHMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARTINSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson urged West
Virginians on Monday to vote for him in Tuesday's presidential
primary, acknowledging his uphill fight and saying ``I've always
fought against the odds.''
   ``The race is tight,'' Jackson told a park rally of more than
1,500 people. ``I'm coming to the last lap. I'm running longer and
running stronger because my mind is made up. We've come too far.
We've got to go on now. Press on! Press on! Press on!''
   Jackson, whose presidential hopes have dimmed with landslide
losses in recent primaries, said he would not give up his candidacy.
   ``I've always fought againt the odds. Dukakis has 39 percent and
I have 29 percent,'' he said of cumulative popular votes won by
both candidates. An Associated Press tabulation gives front-runner
Michael Dukakis 37 percent of the primary vote won to date and
Jackson 28 percent.
   ``We're within striking distance. West Virginia, you can make a
difference. We're winning every day, and when I win, you win,'' he
said.
   At several stops in West Virginia, Jackson tailored his talk to
the economically depressed region. He called West Virginia a
``state of extremes _ good minds, reduced opportunity.''
   ``Rich soil and poor people. Brilliant minds. Something has gone
awry,'' he said. ``I call for fairness. Fair wages for workers,
fair prices for farmers. Fair taxes for the rich and the powerful.
I call for fairness.''
   After an overnight stay at the Arnett home of an unemployed coal
miner and an early morning stop at Peabody Coal Co.'s No. 7 mine to
greet miners at shift-change, Jackson took a drive along winding
one-lane roads to visit the Minden Elementary School, located not
far from an abandoned PCB dump that the federal Environmental
Protection Agency estimates will cost $21 million to clean up.
   Jackson said the dump is an example of the ``economic and
environmental violence'' that government _ particularly the Reagan
administration _ has imposed upon poorer citizens.
   ``You can understand poverty in Ethiopia ... where it hasn't
rained in 15 years,'' Jackson said. ``Here we are in West Virginia
... in the richest country in the world, with talented people, rich
soil, and yet poverty abounds.''
   ``The state is not poor; its wealth is not getting to the
people.''
   Later, Jackson flew to Nebraska, which also holds its primary on
Tuesday. At an airport news conference in Omaha, he told reporters:
``I don't take Nebraska voters for granted. This is a live race.''
   Jackson was upbeat despite polls indicating he trails Dukakis in
the state.
   ``I'm here working,'' he said. ``I'm not just here
by...commercials, I'm here in person.''
   Jackson made stops at a park in downtown Omaha and walked
through a mostly black housing project. At the housing project, he
declared: ``Every vote counts, every voter counts.''
   Monday's visit was Jackson's second to Nebraska, and his extra
time in the state could help him at the polls Tuesday. The
Democratic candidate who spends the most time in Nebraska
traditionally does well in the presidential primary in the mostly
Republican state.
   Jackson insisted he could still win the battle for the
nomination.
   ``I have the longest legs, the strongest legs ... As the days
get longer, the race gets stronger,'' he said.
</TEXT>
