<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TonySnubs     05-09 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tony Snubs,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sarah Brightman Heads List of Tony Non-Nominees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tony Nominations Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Phantom of the Opera'' received 10 Tony
award nominations Monday, but none for its leading lady, Sarah
Brightman, who is married to Andrew Lloyd Webber, the composer and
co-producer of the show.
   It was Lloyd Webber who waged a fight with Actors Equity to
bring his wife to Broadway in the musical, which is a lavish
retelling of the Gaston Leroux novel about a deformed composer and
his love for a beautiful soprano in the Paris Opera.
   The American actors union twice refused permission for Brightman
to appear in the show in New York, but it relented after
``Phantom'' producers agreed to employ an American actor in a major
role in London within the next three years.
   Michael Crawford, Brightman's co-star, received a Tony
nomination as did Judy Kaye, who plays the actress' operatic rival
in ``Phantom.'' The production, which won a best musical
nomination, also was nominated for score, Lloyd Webber, Charles
Hart and Richard Stilgoe; director, Harold Prince; book, Stilgoe
and Lloyd Webber; scenic design, Maria Bjornson; costume design,
Maria Bjornson; lighting design, Andrew Bridge; and choreography,
Lar Lubovitch.
   Brightman was not the only musical star to be passed over for a
nomination. Bernadette Peters failed to receive a nod for her
performance in ``Into the Woods.''
   In other acting categories, several big stars were snubbed. John
Malkovich was not nominated for his performance in Lanford Wilson's
``Burn This'' and neither did Christopher Plummer for his role in
``Macbeth.'' Both their co-stars, Joan Allen in ``Burn This'' and
Glenda Jackson in ``Macbeth,'' received best actress nominations.
   Also absent from the list of nominees was Madonna, whose highly
publicized debut in David Mamet's ``Speed-the-Plow'' took place
last week.
   The best actress in a musical nominations went to Patti LuPone
of ``Anything Goes''; Judy Kuhn of ``Chess''; Joanna Gleason of
``Into the Woods'' and Alison Fraser of ``Romance-Romance.''
</TEXT>
