<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Angola     05-09 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Angola,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Foreign Minister To Meet Angolan Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Roelof Botha
is to meet Angolan officials this week in a high-level follow-up to
last week's ground-breaking peace talks, the South African Press
Association reported Monday.
   The talks will be held Thursday and Friday in Brazzaville,
Congo, according to official sources quoted by the agency. It said
Defense Minister Magnus Malan may accompany Botha.
   The Foreign Ministry said arrangements for the next round of
talks with Angola were not complete, but said South Africa ``is not
opposed to Brazzaville as a venue.''
   The SAPA report said the Brazzaville talks would not involve the
United States.
   Last week, South Africa, Angola and Cuba met in London for their
first head-to-head talks on the withdrawal of foreign troops from
Angola and on the related topic of independence for South-West
Africa, also known as Namibia. One of Botha's subordinates headed
the South African delegation in the U.S.-brokered discussions.
   South African soldiers are fighting in support of the
13-year-old rebel movement against Angola's Marxist government,
which is backed by Soviet advisers and an estimated 40,000 Cuban
troops.
   Earlier Monday, the U.S.-backed Angolan rebels reported killing
64 Angolan soldiers and eight Cubans and shooting down three
Soviet-built aircraft in attacks last week. Rebel casualties were
listed as 12 killed, 10 wounded, two missing.
   The rebel organization UNITA, standing for the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola, made the claims in a
statement distributed in Lisbon, Portugal. Angola is a former
Portuguese African colony.
   There was no independent confirmation of UNITA's claims.
   UNITA said it killed seven Cubans in a May 2 attack on a
wood-processing plant near Conde in the northwestern Angolan
enclave of Cabinda. It said 64 Angolan soldiers were also killed in
actions across six provinces last week.
   The rebels also said that the Cuban pilot died and and two
village children were killed by falling wreckage when rebel
anti-aircraft batteries shot down a MiG-21 plane Thursday as it
bombed Kanamba in southeastern Moxico province.
   The statement said two MI-17 helicopters were shot down on
Wednesday in the area.
   UNITA said violence in Angola would keep up and increase until
Angola's Marxist government, the Soviet Union and Cuba agreed to
negotiate an end to the civil war. The rebels were not included in
the London talks.
</TEXT>
