<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bennett 1stLd-Writethru a0661 05-09 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bennett, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,xxx</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Education Secretary To Resign Post In Mid-September</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 9th graf bgng, `Bennett made,' to
UPDATE with statement from National Education Association</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Bennett, a scourge of school
bureaucrats, teacher unions and slipshod standards during 3{ years
as secretary of education, said Monday he will resign his Cabinet
post in mid-September to return to private life.
   The Department of Education made the announcement after Bennett
met privately with President Reagan at the White House and then
informed his senior staff of his departure plans.
   Bennett told the staff he had recommended that Linus Wright, the
undersecretary of education and a former superintendent of schools
in Dallas, succeed him.
   Bennett told education reporters last month he probably would
not stay for the final few months of the Reagan administration.
   In somewhat uncharacteristic fashion, he refused to take calls
from reporters Monday to discuss his plans, which include hitting
the lecture circuit and writing a book spelling out his vision for
improving America's schools and colleges.
   His spokesman, Loye Miller, read this terse statement:
   ``Secretary Bennett met today with the president and
subsequently with Education Department staff to say that he intends
to leave his position in mid-September. He expressed his gratitude
to President Reagan for the opportunity to serve in his Cabinet.
The secretary reiterated to his staff his intention to continue at
`full speed ahead' during the next few months.''
   Bennett plans to issue two new reports on a model elementary
school curriculum and on improving colleges before he steps down,
said Bill Kristol, his chief of staff. The college book will try
``to shed some light on the black box of higher education'' with
practical advice for parents, policy-makers and others, he said.
   Bennett made headlines throughout his tenure with acerbic
criticisms of teacher unions, the ``blob'' of school bureaucracy,
the ``greed'' of colleges raising tuitions twice as fast as
inflation, and the ``Jim Crow math and back-of-the-bus science''
meted out to black children in ghetto schools. He called Chicago's
schools the nation's worst and said that system was in an
``educational meltdown.''
   The National Education Association said in a statement Monday
that it wishes Bennett well and and expressed hope that the next
secretary of education ``will use the power of the office to be a
positive force in support of public education.''
   ``The nation needs a secretary of education who will work
cooperatively with parents, teachers, school administrators,
college faculty and the community at large,'' the NEA statement
said.
   Two weeks ago, in a report called, ``American Education: Making
It Work,'' Bennett warned that the public has little to show for
five years of school reform. The schools are ``slightly improved,''
he said, but ``we are certainly not doing well enough, and we are
not doing well enough fast enough.''
   He called for using the U.S. military to wage war against drug
traffickers, and quarreled with the surgeon general over what to
teach children about AIDS and condoms.
   His penchant for controversy was evident from his first news
conference in 1985, when he suggested that college students cope
with aid cuts through ``stereo divestiture, automobile divestiture,
three-weeks-at-the-beach divestiture.''
   The remark drew howls from outraged college administrators _ and
tongue-in-cheek ripostes from collegians on spring break in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla.
   Bennett, 44, championed what he called ``the three C's'' of
education: choice, character and content.
   He failed to convince Congress to offer poor parents vouchers to
buy remedial education at either public or private schools. But his
criticism of bilingual education led Congress to ease restrictions
on aid for English-immersion programs.
   He argued strenuously that teachers had a duty to impart strong
morals to their students.
   And, as with his attack on ``Jim Crow math,'' he insisted that
tough, unyielding standards _ such as those he outlined in a model
curriculum called ``James Madison High School'' _ were essential
for all children. He said the civil rights challenge of the 1990s
was to ``ensure equal intellectual opportunity'' in school.
   He was an unapologetic defender of Reagan efforts to slash the
federal education budget, arguing that more money did not guarantee
better results and that state and local school budgets were rising
inexorably anyway.
   Bennett has been a peripatetic Cabinet officer, visiting nearly
100 elementary and secondary schools. He has also proven a big draw
as an after-dinner speaker on the Republican fund-raising circuit.
   Bennett, who switched from the Democratic to the Republican
Party two years ago, has spoken at 63 GOP functions in the past
three years, according to the trade publication Education Week.
   There has been speculation that Bennett may eventually run for
office, possibly from his adopted state of North Carolina.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
