<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bing     05-09 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bing,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Restricts Lady Bing's Contact With Husband</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Monday ordered the wife of former
Metropolitan Opera director Sir Rudolf Bing to relinquish control
over his movements for six hours a day so he can rest and nurses
may care for him.
   State Supreme Court Justice Carmen Beauchamp Ciparick, a
trial-level judge, also directed that male nurses be hired to care
for Bing to assuage Lady Carroll Douglass Bing's apparent jealousy
of female nurses.
   Mrs. Ciparick ordered Lady Bing`to stay away from her husband
from 10 a.m. until noon for his nutrition and hygiene needs, from
3:30 p.m. until 6:30 p.m. so he can nap, and from 9 p.m. until 10
p.m. for further care.
   After 10 p.m., she may stay with Bing until 10 a.m. the next
day, the judge ruled, and if Bing has to see a doctor, his wife may
not go with him.
   ``I'm not convinced that you are such a danger that you have to
be restricted altogether,'' Mrs. Ciparick told Lady Bing.
   The judge's ruling was an interim measure taken during a hearing
on a request by Bing's lawyer, Paul Goldhamer, to bar Lady Bing
from her husband's apartment. The hearing will continue Monday.
   Goldhamer, who maintains Lady Bing is dangerous to her husband,
charges that Lady Bing has abused her husband verbally and
physically. The lawyer has also asked Mrs. Ciparick to annul the
Bings' marriage. He says the former Met impresario has Alzheimer's
disease and did not know what he was doing when he married Lady
Bing in Arlington, Va., on Jan. 9, 1987.
   Lady Bing, a former mental patient, frequently disrupted the
hearing which has been underway since Thursday. She has yelled that
witnesses were lying and she has tried to get Bing to leave the
proceedings with her.
</TEXT>
