<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 2305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Press-Meeting     05-09 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Press-Meeting,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Glasnost Debated At IPI Meeting Attended by Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet journalists debated the meaning
and the future of glasnost with their Western colleagues Monday at
the International Press Institute's annual meeting.
   This was the first IPI general assembly attended by Soviet and
Chinese representatives. About 400 publishers and editors from 43
countries are taking part in the IPI assembly.
   Alexander Pumpyansky, editor in chief of the Soviet weekly Novoe
Vremia, described Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
glasnost _ or greater openness on certain issues in Soviet society
_ as realism, ``seeing the world as it is, not in ideological
dogmas.''
   Delegates laughed and applauded when he added, ``It is like in
the fairy tale when the little child says the king has no clothes .
.. or badly dressed if dressed in a Soviet suit.''
   Conor Cruise O'Brien of Dublin University in Ireland said forces
exist in the Soviet Union that want to reduce the substance of
glasnost.
   He said the policy would have a better chance for success if
confined to the Soviet Union. Developments in other Warsaw Pact
countries could prove to be the ``Achilles heel'' of glasnost,
letting loose revolutionary forces, O'Brien stated.
   ``There are ominous signs in Poland,'' he said.
   Pierro Ottone of Italy's La Repubblica said glasnost should be
viewed as the instrument of a power struggle in the Soviet Union as
a new class wants to get rid of the old mentality in search of a
pragmatic solution to Soviet problems.
   ``There could be unpredictable consequences of this struggle,''
Ottone said. He said it could let loose tensions not only in the
other Warsaw Pact countries but in the Soviet Union as well, citing
recent Armenian unrest as an example.
   In Monday's opening ceremony of the general assembly, IPI
officials demanded a lifting of restrictions on the press in Turkey.
   IPI President Peter Galliner said Turkey had made significant
progress in restoring democracy since the return to civilian rule
in 1983.
   But he said a constant threat to the news media exists from
legislation providing for prosecution and imprisonment of
journalists and hefty fines for publications deemed pornographic.
   The publishers and editors of two men's magazines, Playboy
Turkey and Bravo, were fined a total of $750,000 on Dec.10.
   The fines have not yet been paid, and the government has
announced plans for legislation to substantially reduce the fines.
   Galliner also noted that state-produced newsprint prices have
gone up 200 percent in the past 16 months.
   He and Juan Luis Cebrian, IPI board chairman, appealed for an
amnesty for political prisoners jailed during military rule in
Turkey and an end to prosecution of journalists for what they write.
   The IPI, an independent organization with offices in London and
Zurich, represents 2,000 publishers and editors in more than 60
countries and is dedicated to defending press freedom.
   The Turkish military took over in 1980, following widespread
political violence which claimed 5,000 lives in the three years
prior to the coup. The generals relinquished power after 1983
general elections won by the Motherland Party of Premier Turgut
Ozal.
   Since return to civilian rule, no journalists have been
imprisoned but several are on trial on charges of insulting the
president or the premier or dealing with taboo subjects such as the
problem of the Kurdish minority.
   Ozal defended his pricing policies, saying state subsidies,
including those on newsprint, were lifted as part of his program to
establish a free-market economy in Turkey.
   He conceded that a chief function of the press is criticism of
the government but complained that ``a pervasive pessimism'' is
spreading through the society because of too much negative news.
   Ozal, without citing specific examples, told the delegates that
in Turkey ``people are shying away from a political career''
because of invasion of privacy.
   The premier recommended a peaceful approach in covering foreign
news so not to fan hostilities among nations, especially with
neighbors.
   On the agenda for the three-day meeting are, among other topics,
problems on reporting from Islamic countries, protection of privacy
and the future of UNESCO.
   END (EA)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0181 </DOCNO>
