<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 2335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ScarfoTrial     05-09 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scarfo Trial,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberations in Scarfo Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury began deliberating the fate of
reputed mob boss Nicodemo ``Little Nicky'' Scarfo and eight
associates Monday after hearing the prosecutor defend her two key
witnesses in the murder case.
   The jury will return to the courtroom of Common Pleas Judge
Albert Sabo on Tuesday morning to continue deliberations.
   The 59-year-old Scarfo, who police allege ran the area's Mafia
from his home in Atlantic City, N.J., before his arrest in 1986,
and the other eight defendants are charged with the Sept. 14, 1984,
murder of rival Salvatore Testa.
   Testa's body, with two bullets in the head, was found trussed
with rope and wrapped in a blanket in a wooded area in south Jersey.
   The trial began more than two months ago. Jury selection took
more than four weeks, and the testimony phase took another month.
   Assistant District Attorney Barbara Christie's 78-minute closing
statement followed almost eight hours of defense arguments over two
days last week and an hour Monday morning.
   She acknowledged that prosecution witnesses Nicholas Caramandi
and Thomas DelGiorno were despicable men.
   ``Rats? Yes,'' Ms. Christie said. ``But when you enter a sewer
don't rats lead the way? ...
   ``DelGiorno and Caramandi told you that Nicky Scarfo was the
boss and that Scarfo' organization eliminated problems and
dissension by simple execution.''
   Caramanda and DelGiorno testified Testa was murdered in a south
Philadelphia candy store, closed for renovations, and the body was
driven in a van across the Delaware River and dumped along a road.
   Scarfo's lawyer, Robert Simone, on Monday morning continued the
attack on the two witnesses that his eight colleagues had made in
their closing arguments.
   ``When are DelGiorno and Caramandi telling the truth and when
are they lying?'' Simone asked. ``We have to guess, and you can't
convict these men on guesses. If Testa was killed in that sweet
shop, you would have evidence, blood, something.''
   He maintained that Testa actually was killed in his own home and
that the murderers were Caramandi and DelGiorno.
   Scarfo, who still faces murder charges in two other slayings,
was convicted last year of trying to extort $1 million from a
developer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
