<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SkyscraperFire     05-09 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skyscraper Fire,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Complete, But Cause May Be Impossible to Determine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire officials said Monday that they failed
to determine how a fire ignited in California's tallest building
because 2,000-degree flames destroyed clues, but they said arson
was not suspected.
   City fire investigators and agents from the U.S. Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms completed their inquiry and turned
over control of the building to First Interstate Bank on Sunday.
   ``They pretty much ruled out it being a case of arson,'' said
bank spokesman Bob Campbell.
   ``At this time, the cause has been listed as undetermined in
origin,'' said city fire Capt. Ralph Ramirez. ``The extent of the
damages prevents us from listing a ... definitive cause.''
   Further questions about the investigators' inquiry were referred
to Fire Chief Donald Manning, who scheduled a Tuesday news
conference to discuss the findings.
   Earlier, Battalion Chief Gary Bowie played down suggestions that
the bank's decision to sell its securities unit the day of
Wednesday's fire played a role in the blaze that killed one person
and injured 40 others.
   ``No one interviewed has said that there's a possibility of an
incendiary fire of any type,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, suitcase- and box-toting employees of companies with
offices in the First Interstate Bank tower retrieved documents from
the fire-scarred, 62-story tower.
   Wearing hard hats and accompanied by security officers,
employees boarded elevators for the ascent to offices above and
below gutted floors 12 through 16. Many of the employees filled
boxes, bags, suitcases and briefcases with files, computer disks
and telephone lists.
   ``They had 15 minutes to select the things they need the most,''
said bank spokesman John Popovich.
   He said the bank had gotten many of its employees back to work
either in the undamaged parts of the building or in nearby leased
space, thanks to an emergency plan designed for earthquakes. He
said it would take 10 days to four weeks to clean up smoke and
water damage, but there was no estimate on the time to rebuild the
gutted floors.
   The fire department's preliminary estimate of $450 million was
``exceedingly high,'' Popovich said.
</TEXT>
