<HEAD>Shooting Incident at TV Transmitter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs, He said ... UPDATING with
report that drunken guards may have started gunfight. Pick up 5th
graf pvs, Cadag said ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen fired from a passing van at
troopers guarding a television transmitter Monday, wounding at
least one soldier, the military reported.
   Officials said shooting continued for more than half an hour
because the guards were confused and fired at policemen and other
soldiers coming to their aid.
   ``The guards thought the responding troops belonged to the same
group that had attacked them,'' police Sgt. Estelito Cadag said.
   He said it took military officials about two hours to determine
what had happened at the compound housing the Kanlaon Broadcasting
System transmitter in suburban Quezon City.
   Another television station, ABS-CBN, reported that soldiers
guarding the transmitter were intoxicated and began firing their
weapons into the air. It said those soldiers then fired at police
who responded to complaints from residents.
   The military's Capital Regional Command said it could was
investigating the ABS-CBN report.
   Cadag said the lone military casualty was a corporal with a
gunshot wound in the right thigh. Officials said they did not know
if anyone body in the van was hit in the exchange.
   Military guards are posted at radio and television stations
because of at least six coup attempts against President Corazon
Aquino's 2-year-old government.
   Col. Toto Arroyo, legal officer of the army unit guarding the
Kanlaon transmitter, said: ``The guards were momentarily taken
aback because the firing was so intense and they didn't know where
it was coming from. After a few seconds they returned fire and the
van sped away.''
   Arroyo would not speculate about the identities of the attackers
or their motive, saying only that they were ``a van of armed men
who had a lot of weapons ... automatic weapons.''
   The last and most serious coup attempt occurred Aug. 28 led by
Lt. Col. Gregorio Honasan, who escaped from a prison ship last
month and threatened more attacks. At least 53 people were killed
and hundreds wounded in the August attacks.
</TEXT>
