<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv15,0522</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, May 15, the 136th day of 1988. There are 230
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On May 15, 1972, Democratic presidential candidate George C.
Wallace was shot and left paralyzed while campaigning at a Laurel,
Md., shopping center. Wallace's assailant, Arthur Bremer, was
sentenced to 63 years in prison, although the sentence was later
reduced.
   On this date:
   In 1602, Cape Cod was discovered by the English navigator
Bartholomew Gosnold.
   In 1886, poet Emily Dickinson died in Amherst, Mass.
   In 1911, the U.S. Supreme Court ordered the dissolution of
Standard Oil Co., ruling it was in violation of the Sherman
Antitrust Act.
   In 1918, U.S. airmail began service between Washington,
Philadelphia and New York.
   In 1930, Ellen Church, the first airline stewardess, went on
duty aboard a United Airlines flight between San Francisco and
Cheyenne, Wyo.
   In 1940, nylon stockings went on sale for the first time in the
United States.
   In 1948, hours after declaring its independence, the new state
of Israel was attacked by Transjordan, Egypt, Syria, Iraq and
Lebanon.
   In 1957, more than 18,000 people filled Madison Square Garden in
New York as evangelist Billy Graham launched a crusade.
   In 1958, the Soviet Union launched Sputnik Three.
   In 1963, U.S. astronaut L. Gordon Cooper blasted off aboard
Faith Seven on the final mission of the Project Mercury space
program. Cooper orbited the earth 22 times in 34 hours.
   In 1969, Supreme Court Justice Abe Fortas resigned amid a
controversy over his past legal fees.
   In 1986, searchers on Oregon's Mount Hood found two teen-age
survivors of a hiking expedition that became trapped in a
``whiteout'' blizzard. Nine other climbers died.
   Ten years ago: By a vote of 54-to-44, the U.S. Senate expressed
support for President Jimmy Carter's proposal to sell fighter
planes to Israel, Egypt and Saudi Arabia. Carter said he was
``deeply gratified'' by the vote.
   Five years ago: Israel and Lebanon reached agreement on the text
of a U.S.-sponsored accord under which Israel would withdraw its
troops from Lebanon, as soon as Syria and the PLO agreed to
withdraw their forces.
   One year ago: President Reagan told a gathering of out-of-town
reporters at the White House he did not consider himself ``mortally
wounded'' by the Iran-Contra affair. (The president also got a
chance to relive his radio-announcer days when he complied with a
reporter's request to read a promo for Nashville station WSM.)
   Today's Birthdays: Actor Joseph Cotten is 83. Actress Constance
Cummings is 78. Singer Eddy Arnold is 70. Playwrights Peter Shaffer
and Anthony Shaffer -- twin brothers -- are 62. Actress-singer Anna
Maria Alberghetti is 52. Playwright Paul Zindel is 52. Singer Trini
Lopez is 51. Singer-songwriter Brian Eno is 40. Baseball player
George Brett is 35. Actor Lee Horsley is 33.
   Thought for Today: ``Comedy is the last refuge of the
non-conformist mind.'' -- Gilbert Seldes, American critic
(1893-1970).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
