<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-FishandChips Adv13   05-09 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fish and Chips, Adv 13,0722</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, May 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fish and Chips Shops Spruce Up to Meet Hamburger Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARKINGSIDE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hi-Tide is no longer your
run-of-the-mill fish and chips shop. The American hamburger, fried
chicken and pizza have seen to that.
   Instead of the greasy, colorless decor that typifies many
British fish and chips places, the Hi-Tide is a large combination
restaurant-takeout business refurbished with ``Old English'' decor
of wood beams, exposed brick and lanterns.
   The kitchen gleams and the large staff is eager to please.
   The reason for this is just down the main shopping street of
this tidy northeast London suburb: a hamburger stand, a Kentucky
Fried Chicken outlet and a pizza parlor. McDonald's is coming soon.
   Fish and chips are still Britain's biggest-selling fast food,
but the trade is under siege and having to fight back.
   ``The competition is very, very fierce,'' said Hi-Tide's owner,
Eric Laycock. ``I'd be lying to you if I said it didn't hurt.''
   Not only is there competition, there are image problems too. The
health-conscious are shunning fried foods, and young Britons say
eating fish isn't trendy.
   Bob Kennedy, marketing director for Edinburgh-based Sea Fish
Industry, says fish and chips shops ``are maintaining their level
of sales but they are not sharing in the expansion of hot food
takeaway as a whole.''
   Said Brian Phelps, president of London's Fish Friers
Association: ``We're having to pull our socks up, obviously.''
   Fish and chips have been a national food since the 19th-century
industrial revolution, when trains and steam trawlers started
bringing it to the neighborhoods of the new working class.
   The meal usually consists of succulent cod, deep-fried in
batter, and stubby French fries called chips, all sprinkled
liberally with malt vinegar and salt. Mushy peas are optional.
   Until the advent of modern packaging, the fish and chips came
wrapped in an old newspaper to soak up the grease. A order now
costs an average of 1.25 pounds ($2.34), about half the price of a
Big Mac, fries and soft drink.
   Nicknamed ``chippies,'' fish and chips shops generally have been
small businesses run by married couples out of the front rooms of
their terraced houses.
   But gentrification of these terraces has driven out many shops,
and they are scarce even in central London today.
   As the new competition has intensified in the past 10 years,
``chippies'' are becoming larger, and chains and partnerships are
forming. Although most shops remain English-owned, Chinese, Greek
and Indian immigrants are moving in.
   Britain had 9,500 fish and chips shops in 1986, representing
52.1 percent of the multibillion-dollar fast food market, down from
10,750 shops and 55.3 percent in 1981, according to Sea Fish
Industry.
   Today, annual fish and chips sales total the equivalent of about
$935 million, the National Federation of Fish Friers said.
   The fight for survival is multi-pronged.
   More are providing seating for their customers.
   Laycock, who offers 42 seats, says: ``Takeaway is too blunt, it
is too quick. You can't converse with a customer like in a
restaurant.''
   The shops have improved flavor by using better batters and oils,
and are packaging meals in lidded cardboard boxes, Phelps said.
   Industry associations now run training courses for their members
and are countering the health issue with a low-key public relations
campaign.
   ``People say that fried food is unhealthy and too much fried
food will lead to heart disease,'' said Arthur Parrington, head of
the Leeds-based national federation. ``We say, `Moderation in all
things.'''
   Laycock, 45, says he spent 100,000 pounds ($187,000) renovating
the run-down fish and chips shop he bought in 1974. He reports
business is better, and he is considering getting a liquor license.
   As a director of Old Bylands Ltd., a 20-shop chain, Laycock
travels to outlets to teach managers how to fight the competition
from the hamburger, fried chicken and pizza.
   ``There will be less of us. The ones that are left will be
highly specialized and efficient,'' he said.
   ``This is a very dying trade, but I think we still have a place
in English society.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, May 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Sudan'sTroubles Adv16   05-09 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan's Troubles, Adv 16,0840</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, May 16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sudan Has Severe Problems after Two Years of Civilian Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reminiscent of the 1970s oil crisis
around the world, Sudanese wait in line these days as long as 12
hours for gasoline. Lines form as well for sugar, bread and other
necessities in short supply.
   Two years after army generals gave power to Prime Minister Sadek
el-Mahdi, his civilian government is having to contend with a
faltering economy and a costly war in the south.
   Inflation reaching 70 percent has sent prices soaring, and
strikes are commonplace as workers try to deal with it.
   The war costs the government an estimated $1 million a day in
borrowed money.
   El-Mahdi won national elections in April 1986, a year after the
military overthrew Gaafar Nimeiri, the president for 16 years.
   But el-Mahdi sees a bright side to his two years as the nation's
leader.
   ``We have moved the country from a famine-stricken, collapsed
economy to a working economy which is able to feed itself and which
has resumed its contacts with the international community on an
equitable and just basis,'' he said in an interview.
   Many Sudanese and foreign diplomats disagree.
   Sudanese joke about it: ``There's democracy, a lot of democracy,
but that's about the only commodity available.''
   Said a diplomat: ``In theory, if el-Mahdi's government continues
to drift with no firm program, that plus economic distress surely
will affect the democratic process and increase the possibility of
a military takeover. That's been the cycle historically.''
   It has taken most of el-Mahdi's time and all his political
prowess in the last two years to maintain equilibrium among the
country's 35 diverse political parties and 597 tribes.
   He fired his Cabinet on grounds of inefficiency in the spring of
1986, and the next one lasted less than a year.
   The crisis that followed remains unresolved as el-Mahdi seeks to
put together and effective coalition of the five largest political
parties _ a mixture of center-right, Moslem fundamentalists and
non-Moslem southerners.
   The major stumbling block is finding alternatives to Islamic law
that Nimeiri implemented in 1983. Although ignored since the 1985
coup, the law of Islam remain officially as Sudan's basic law.
   Nimeiri avoided economic problems by securing foreign loans. The
Transitional Military Council that replaced him froze interest
payments on those loans.
   El-Mahdi, whose government must deal with a $12-billion foreign
debt, says his government can't be responsible for the mistakes of
past leaders.
   That position enticed countries like Canada, Sweden and Norway
to write off Sudan's debts to them.
   But Sudan is not likely to hold out much longer on the foreign
aid it is now getting and foreign lenders are expected to extend
more loans without some form of economic reform.
   Saudi Arabia, Libya, Kuwait, Britain, Japan, the United States
and other foreign donors pour in $700 million to $800 million
annually in cash, oil and other commodities. A Western economist
estimated that Sudan needs $1 billion to $1.5 billion a year for
the next four years ``just to keep up its present position.''
   The civil war in southern Sudan is a constant financial drain,
as is the huge public sector.
   For example, the government's railway corporation, which moves
less than 10 percent of Sudan's freight, employs 370,000 people. It
moved more than 80 percent of the freight 30 years ago with fewer
than half as many people.
   Government sugar factories produce 600,000 tons of sugar a year,
which should satisfy local annual consumption needs of 560,000
tons. Nevertheless, the government imports 200,000 tons a year
because 250,000 tons of domestic sugar are smuggled to neighboring
countries for higher prices.
   The International Monetary Fund and other lenders are calling
Sudan to cut back on such costly ways.
   The Oxford-educated el-Mahdi said in the interview that one of
the first tasks once the new government is formed will be to adopt
a four-year economic reform plan. It will include rehabilitation of
agricultural, industrial and service institutions and the
construction of new roads and dams, he said.
   Closely linked to the economic morass is the civil war in
southern Sudan, where the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army has
held the upper hand for almost a year, its first sustained success
since the conflict began in 1983.
   The Ethiopian-backed rebels, mainly Christians and animists
fighting the Moslem-dominated government in Khartoum, demand
autonomy and a larger share of Sudan's assets for the southern
zone. They also want Islamic law abrogated.
   The country is thought to have extensive oil reserves, mostly in
the south, but the war prevents exploitation. Southern farms can't
till their fertile fields because of the fighting and work has been
halted on a major canal project, which if completed would divert
Nile River water throughout Sudan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
