<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--EyeBank Adv22-2Takes   05-09 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Eye Bank, Adv 22-2 Takes,0746</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 5 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Two questions. What was the first human
transplant, and which is the most successful? The answer to both is
the cornea, which gives sight to 35,000 people a year. The irony is
that the very success of America's eye banks has caused their
biggest frustration, a lack of donors.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JULES LOH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Their battle cry could properly be ``an eye for
an eye.'' But there is no vengeance in the hearts of these
crusaders, only mercy.
   They work in a small, quiet lab high above Manhattan's blare and
glare, and, with dawn-to-midnight effort, seem to be gaining on
their quest: the gift of sight for all who can have it _ without
delay.
   ``We're providing more corneas for transplant every year,'' says
Patricia Dahl. ``Dramatically more in recent years, but still not
enough.
   ``When I came here seven years ago the waiting period was four
months. Now it's down to five weeks. The pity is that there
shouldn't have to be any waiting time at all. The eyes are there,
the donors are not.''
   Ms. Dahl is the lab director for New York's Eye-Bank for Sight
Restoration, Inc. It is the nation's first and largest eye bank
among the more than 100 throughout the nation. Last year it
provided 1,400 corneas for transplant, all it could obtain, but, as
Ms. Dahl said, not enough.
   The irony is that the very success of corneal transplants, the
first human tissue transplanted successfully, is the eye bank's
biggest problem.
   ``The large organ transplants, the hearts, the kidneys, the
lungs, are the ones that get all the publicity and national appeals
for donors,'' says Mary Jane O'Neill, the eye bank's executive
director. ``Corneal transplants have become so commonplace people
assume one will be available every time one is needed. That, of
course, is far from the case.''
   Since its beginning two generations ago, New York's eye bank has
provided corneas for 30,000 transplants. And, yes, the procedure
has become so routine that that number now equals almost as many as
are done in America every year. On an average day in America, one
heart, 20 kidneys and 65 corneas are transplanted _ one cornea
every 22 minutes, more corneas than all other transplants combined.
   The New York eye bank was established in 1944 by a pioneering
physician, the late Richard Townley Paton. He used eyes donated by
consenting convicts on death row at Sing Sing Prison, just up the
Hudson River, and lost a housekeeper in the process when she opened
the fridge one morning, saw two eyes in a saucer of liquid, and
left. Paton, who died four years ago, wrote the first textbook
published in the United States on corneal transplants, forerunner
of all organ transplants.
   The cornea is not an organ. The eye is the organ, the cornea a
tissue. At least at this stage doctors see no way the eye, once
severed from the optic nerve, can ever be transplanted.
   The cornea is the transparent front surface of the eye, about
the size and thickness of a dime. It is the window through which
light passes to the lens and onto the retina. The brain completes
the job; the result, vision. For it all to work, the cornea must be
crystal clear.
   ``It's an amazing thing, the cornea,'' said Ms. Dahl, the lab
director.
   ``It's the most sensitive tissue in the body, which is why the
tiniest grain of sand on it will hurt. Yet it also is very
resilient, and the fact that it contains no blood vessels makes it
easily passed on. Rejection by the recipient is extremely rare. The
success rate is better than 90 percent.
   ``Some recipients who received a transplant when they were
young, from a middle-aged or even elderly donor, are looking
through corneas perhaps 100 years old.''
   Ms. Dahl's education was in biology and chemistry, not medicine.
She got her job at the eye bank through a help-wanted ad and
trained on the job. She was certified by the Eye Bank Association
of America, sort of a national clearinghouse which sets the
standards for technicians.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--EyeBank Adv22-1stAdd   05-09 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Eye Bank, Adv 22-1st Add,0731</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: for technicians.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Her lab is a simply furnished room: no microscopes or bubbling
beakers or any of the exotic paraphernalia you might expect in a
place where medical miracles are wrought.
   It contains only a table, brightly lit, where the corneas are
removed, and a single instrument called a split-light, a device
like one an eye doctor uses for examinations, except less
complicated.
   Ms. Dahl's eyes (20-20, hazel) brighten with enthusiasm when she
explains what goes on there.
   ``We have four people in the lab and four in the field
collecting eyes from donors. As soon as we hear of a donor we
dispatch someone to the hospital to collect the eyes. We cover 138
hospitals in an 11-county area. Unlike other organs, the eye can be
taken six to eight hours after death. It's a simple job and leaves
no disfiguration. Takes about 20 minutes.
   ``We receive the eyes in the lab and examine the cornea through
the split-light. If it is acceptable, we remove it and send it
right away to the next recipient on the list. If not, it is used in
research. None is wasted. Our procedure takes about 20 minutes as
well.
   ``We maintain the recipient list by computer. The corneas go out
first come, first served, unless there's a priority, such as
someone being in danger of losing the entire eye because of an
accident.
   ``The doctor removes the damaged portion of the patient's eye
with an instrument called a trephine, sort of a cookie cutter. He
cuts out the donor cornea with the same instrument, so the
replacement fits exactly. He works through a high-powered
microscope and stitches it in with nylon thread finer than a human
hair. He can do the operation in his office using local anesthesia
if he chooses.
   ``Some patients can see when the bandages come off the next day.
With others it's more gradual.
   ``What we do here is the easy part. The hard part is getting the
donors.''
   Even many doctors, well aware of the need, are often reluctant
to approach a family at the moment of their grief to ask permission
to remove their loved one's organs.
   The result is the loss in America each year of an estimated
18,000 to 20,000 potential kidneys, livers, hearts, lungs and other
organs, but especially eyes. Since the eyes do not have to be
removed as urgently, the brain-dead body does not have to be
maintained artificially, and the cornea may wait four or five days
before transplanting.
   To prevent this loss, two years ago New York, California and
Oregon enacted laws not simply encouraging but requiring that
hospitals, where 80 percent of Americans die, make that painful
request of the bereaved. Since then all except eight states (Idaho,
Wyoming, South Dakota, Vermont, South Carolina, Iowa, Alabama and
Utah) have passed similar ``required request'' laws.
   New York, among other states, sends out counselors _ including
the energetic Ms. Dahl _ to teach nurses and other hospital workers
how to make the delicate request.
   They have discovered that in many cases the request actually
comforts a family since they can feel the relative lives on through
someone else.
   ``There is one final act of love you can do for your beloved,''
one hospital chaplain tells sorrowing relatives. Others approach a
relative with a gentle question: ``Do you know whether the person
was an eye donor?''
   ``Two-thirds of those asked say yes,'' says Ms. Dahl, ``Since
the law's enactment, donations to the New York eye bank increased
78 percent.''
   Still not enough.
   A decade ago, only 7,000 corneal transplants were performed in
the United States. But eyes judged beyond repair back then can now
be restored. Last year 35,000 Americans received corneal
transplants and another 5,000 who needed them lacked donors.
Doctors say that technology continues to develop and today's demand
could double in the next decade.
   ``I don't know whether we ever will have a cornea immediately
for everybody who needs one, but that's the goal,'' Ms. Dahl says.
   ``Until it happens, we'll continue to be a bank in name only. No
deposits here, only withdrawals.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
