<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-APN--WhiteHouseFellows Adv22-2Takes   05-09 0862</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--White House Fellows, Adv 22-2 Takes,0883</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ In a program that began under President Lyndon
Johnson, more than 300 White House Fellows have spent a year
working in various federal departments and agencies, learning the
ways of government from within. Some have stayed, and now occupy
high posts in the government. Others have gone home, but with a
different outlook.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the Old Executive Office Building next door
to the White House, James L. Nuzzo scans column after column of
numbers in a budget book and prepares a memorandum for Vice
President George Bush.
   Nuzzo is a neurologist from Boston.
   Over at the Agriculture Department, George M. Drysdale makes his
way through the intricacies of farm price supports, soil
conservation and consumer services.
   Drysdale is a venture capitalist from San Francisco.
   In the office of the U.S. trade representative, Karen S.
Kellerhouse fields inquiries from mayors and governors about U.S.
foreign trade policy.
   Ms. Kellerhouse is a financial executive on leave from the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey.
   Nuzzo, Drysdale and Ms. Kellerhouse are among a dozen Americans
in their early or middle 30s who are working as White House Fellows
in a program that has survived from Lyndon Johnson's Great Society
to Ronald Reagan's New American Revolution.
   Since 1965, more than 300 of them have passed through
Washington, spending 12 months working in federal departments and
agencies to learn the ways of government. Some have stayed, and
occupy high posts in the government. Others have gone home.
   White House Fellows work at the National Aeronautics and Space
Agency, the Department of Energy, the Pentagon, the Office of
Management and Budget, the Justice Department, the Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency and in the White House.
   Of the current crop, one is a newspaper marketing executive,
three are attorneys, one is vice president of a scientific products
firm. Three are Army majors, one a captain in the Marine Corps.
   During their September-through-August stint, for which they were
chosen from among about 800 applicants, they receive a salary of up
to $55,000 a year. Officials say most of them, successful in their
own careers, absorb a pay cut. Anyone is eligible except federal
civil servants.
   Some of the program's graduates have big offices in Washington.
Lt. Gen. Colin L. Powell, who worked as a fellow under then-Budget
Director Caspar Weinberger in 1971-72, is now President Reagan's
national security adviser. Another alumnus, Michael H. Armacost, is
undersecretary of state for political affairs.
   Another, David Karnes, says, ``I wouldn't be United States
senator today if it weren't for the White House Fellows program.''
The Nebraska Republican is one of two who have made it to the
Senate. Tim Wirth, a fellow in the Department of Health, Education
and Welfare in 1967-68, is a Democratic senator from Colorado.
   Henry G. Cisneros of the class of 1971-72 is mayor of San
Antonio; Joe Barton, '81-82, is a representative from Texas; Garry
Carruthers, '74-'75, is governor of New Mexico. Tom Johnson,
'65-66, is publisher of the Los Angeles Times; James K. Stewart,
'81-82, is director of the National Institute of Justice; Robert
Haas, '68-69, is president of Levi Strauss & Company; Doris Kearns
met Lyndon Johnson when she was a fellow, and became his biographer.
   Several former fellows are generals or admirals.
   It all started in 1957 with John Gardner, then president of the
Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching.
   ``I had been doing quite a bit of reading about the founding
fathers and I was struck with the fact that just about every single
one of them had very early opportunity to observe government,''
Gardner recalls. ``It was right across the street, so to speak, the
government of their colony.'' He also found, he says, ``that the
ablest kids in the country today never saw anybody governing.''
   ``I wrote a memo proposing the idea of a group of White House
fellows and had the idea that it could be financed by
foundations,'' he said. ``The only problem was the bill was very
high and there wasn't any foundation interested in it.''
   Seven years later, Gardner was having lunch with Eric Goldman, a
Princeton University historian, then an aide to President Johnson.
Goldman said Johnson was concerned that too few young people were
interested in government.
   ``Look, I've got a memo,'' says Gardner, who would later become
Johnson's secretary of health, education and welfare. Goldman
showed the memo to the president and first lady Lady Bird Johnson
and the program was launched.
   Today it has a budget of slightly less than $500,000 a year,
supplemented by private funds raised by a foundation set up by
former fellows.
   In its early years, the program was limited to applicants
between the ages of 24 and 36, but the age requirement was
abandoned in response to an anti-discrimination suit. All of the
current fellows, however, would have qualified under the original
limits.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-APN--WhiteHouseFellows Adv22-1stAdd   05-09 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--White House Fellows, Adv 22-1st Add,0786</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: original limits.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The youngest fellow in history, David Neuman, was 23 when he
served in the White House Office of Cabinet Affairs. Neuman says
the experience has been ``very useful and helpful'' in his present
job _ vice president for current comedy programs at NBC.
   ``Relationships between the White House and the departments and
agencies are much like that between a television network and the
various studies and production companies,'' he says. ``The
political dynamic is very similar.''
   Neuman says the program needs to be better publicized.
``Everybody knows what the Rhodes scholarship is and very few
people know what the White House fellowship is.''
   Applications are first reviewed at a January reunion of alumni,
who cut them to about 130. Those applicants are invited to travel
at their own expense to 11 cities to be interviewed by panels of
prominent citizens.
   This cuts the field to 33, who come to Washington at government
expense for a weekend for more interviews by members of the
presidentially appointed Commission on White House Fellowships.
   For some, like Karnes, the interview will be their first trip to
Washington. For others, the capital is familiar ground. Nuzzo, for
instance, had been a House page and attended Georgetown University
Medical School.
   Nuzzo, 31, said he heard about the program while in college.
After completing medical school and residency, he applied so he
could ``decide whether I'm going to be a practicing clinician or
whether I wanted to get involved with policy full time.''
   He says he reached his decision on his third day in the job: he
chose a life of public service.
   On one recent day, Nuzzo sat in on a meeting of the subcabinet
Interagency Trade Policy Review Group from 8:30 until sometime
after 9:30 a.m., came back to the office and did some reading in
the budget and the annual economic report to the president, ``sort
of summarized some of the key kernels of material that were
necessary from that,'' analyzed some taxation and civil rights
issues and ``looked at the whole notion of banking deregulation.''
That was in the morning. In the afternoon, he had a meeting about
AIDs financing.
   Not everybody's cup of tea, but for Nuzzo it's heady stuff.
``Here I am, I'm a doc from Massachusetts,'' he said. ``A couple of
months ago my big thing was figuring out whether I ought to give
somebody a high colonic, and now I'm writing memoranda for the vice
president.''
   In addition to their regular duties, the fellows spend at least
a day on Capitol Hill following a member of Congress around.
   ``That, from the fellows' point of view, is a real eye opener,''
says Ann Lavin, assistant director of the program. ``I think up
until then a lot of them have really believed in their government
textooks on how it works.''
   Drysdale, 32, a general partner in Hambrecht & Quist Venture
Partners of San Francisco, for instance, was assigned to track Rep.
E. (Kika) de la Garza, D-Texas, chairman of the House Agriculture
Committee.
   ``There are parts of it that are very, very different from the
way decisions are made in the business world,'' Drysdale says.
``Often in business one or two people make a decision; in the
political process it's much more open.''
   The fellows also attend meetings, about once a week, at which
big names in government and journalism speak.
   They also make trips abroad, which come out of the budget of the
agency they work for. This year's group went to the Soviet Union in
April. When President Reagan met with the fellows on Jan. 5,
according to Nuzzo, he asked them, ``Please let me know what you
find out.''
   Although one out of three of the current fellows are from the
armed services, officials deny there is any tilt in favor of the
military.
   Whatever their background, said Nuzzo, ``There is almost a White
House fellows Mafia of both old and new fellows, people from
outside and inside the government who talk to each other a great
deal.''
   One alumnus of the program, Elaine Chao, recently named chairman
of the Federal Maritime Commission, came to the fellowship from a
career in banking, to which she expects to return.
   ``Being an immigrant to this country, I was personally
interested in how the government works,'' the Taiwanese native
said. But she added, ``It was only through my business dealings
that I began to understand that business and government really
didn't understand each other.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
