<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--Cuomo Adv22-2Takes   05-09 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Cuomo, Adv 22-2 Takes,0781</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Before Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis surged
far ahead of the pack, New York Gov. Mario Cuomo was the most
talked-about non-candidate for president of this primary season.
Here's a look at the statehouse record of Cuomo, who's keeping the
door slightly ajar for another ``Mario scenario.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mario Cuomo, one of the Democratic Party's
most eloquent voices, has toiled for 5{ years as chief executive of
the nation's second-largest state, much of the time at the center
of waxing and waning speculation about a possible run for the White
House.
   From his base in Albany, Cuomo has tackled national issues such
as the federal deficit; international issues such as Third World
debt, and the most basic issue of all _ life and death.
   ``We do innovation so casually that we don't even get credit for
it,'' says Cuomo, who with one 1984 speech became an instant
national celebrity and kept people talking about him as a likely
presidential candidate even while he insisted he had no intention
of being one.
   Until recently, Cuomo's avowed non-candidacy was regarded with
much skepticism. Now the march toward the Democratic nomination by
a fellow governor, Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, seems to have
all but obliterated lingering thoughts of a ``Mario scenario.''
   Whatever Cuomo might have wrought as a candidate, in New York
State his handiwork has accumulated and is plain to see _ though
not, as usual in matters political, uncontested.
   A list of administration accomplishments compiled in Cuomo's
office includes the mandatory seat belt law, the nation's first;
the start of the largest tax cut in the state's history, and
raising the drinking age from 18 to 21.
   The seat belt bill originated in the Legislature, and the
governor at first expressed reservations about its effect on
``short people'' who might find wearing the belts uncomfortable.
   Reminded of this recently, Cuomo said, ``I signed it.''
   In 1984, Cuomo fought hard to raise the state's drinking age,
but members of the state Assembly's majority, complaining of the
administration's strong-arm lobbying, voted it down. It passed the
following year after the federal government threatened to withhold
federal highway money from any state that failed to raise its
drinking age to 21.
   The tax cut approved last year was on the Legislature's
initiative, says state Assembly Speaker Mel Miller, a Brooklyn
Democrat. After initial opposition to the tax-cut proposals, first
championed by the Senate's Republican majority, Cuomo came on board
and signed the measure into law.
   In March, a television reporter noted in a broadcast the critics
were saying the governor hadn't come up with many new ideas. It's
an accusation Cuomo has heard repeatedly, and it makes him bristle.
   The official keeper of the Cuomo administration's scorecard,
first assistant to the governor Elaine Ryan, sent the reporter a
three-page list titled, ``Highlights of Cuomo Administration
Innovations.''
   Said the governor himself, when asked about initiatives: ``It
would probably be difficult to find a five-year period in the
history of the state where you had more innovation.'' He cited a
string of them.
   One such was his fight for creation of the National Economic
Commission to study the national deficit, Third World debt and
productivity. With a strong push from Congress, President Reagan
signed legislation in December creating the commission.
   ``The governor of a state gets an idea. The vice president
doesn't want it. The president doesn't want it. And we get it. The
president signs it. I think that was kind of innovative,'' says
Cuomo.
   ``That certainly has the sound, if not '88, then 1992,'' says
Cuomo's chief Albany antagonist, Warren Anderson, the Republican
majority leader of the state Senate, suggesting that Cuomo has his
sights set on the White House.
   The commission, derisively labeled ``the Cuomo Commission'' by
Vice President George Bush, this year's expected GOP presidential
nominee, is composed of luminaries such as New York financial
expert Felix Rohatyn and Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca. Co-chaired
by former Democratic Party Chairman Robert Strauss and Republican
Drew Lewis, a former secretary of transportation, the commission
will report after the November election.
   A real Cuomo Commission is the governor's Commission on Trade
and Competitiveness, a group of nationally known executives, labor
leaders and economists brought together by the governor to study
the same problems as they affect New York.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
