<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Bikini, Adv 22-2 Takes,0670</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo, 1 graphic. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ They were early exiles of the Atomic Age,
removed from their rich fishing grounds at Bikini Atoll so the
United States could test its nuclear bombs. Today, 42 years later,
some 1,500 Bikinians are scattered across the Marshall Islands,
living on U.S. aid and waiting for America to fulfill its promise
and clean up their homeland.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIKINI ATOLL, Marshall Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kilon Bauno looks out on
the lagoon that once provided his people an abundant life and
recalls those better days, before U.S. atomic bomb tests poisoned
this remote, coral atoll with radiation.
   ``When I was here, life was great. We had fish, we had turtles,
we had coconuts. We lived together and we took care of each
other,'' Bauno, the ceremonial chief of the Bikini Islanders, says
through an interpreter.
   ``You always felt you were getting a big gift from God,'' adds
Bauno, who is believed to be in his late 80s, although elderly
Bikinians don't keep track of their ages.
   Today, 42 years after 167 Bikinians left so their atoll could
become a laboratory for the bomb tests, they see a glimmer of hope
that their ``nuclear exile'' will be coming to an end.
   Under an out-of-court settlement to a lawsuit in 1985, the
United States agreed to pay for Bikini's cleanup and the eventual
resettlement of the atoll.
   Scientists are still trying to determine how best to get rid of
the lingering radiation. However, it's no longer a question of
``if'' the exiles can return home, but when.
   An estimated 1,500 Bikinians are scattered throughout the
Marshall Islands, living off aid from the U.S. government and
longing for the day when America fulfills its promise.
   ``When we left, they promised us we would be the children of
America,'' Bauno says. ``The only thing we can do now is look to
America and wait for them to do something.''
   So far, the United States has spent $123 million on the
Bikinians, including $95 million in trust funds to resettle, house
and feed them. America also has paid for studies of the radiation
problem in the atoll, site of 23 atomic blasts between 1946 and
1958.
   With each passing day the elder Bikinians believe the chances of
resuming their traditional way of life become slimmer.
   ``There are only a few elders left who know our traditional
customs and it will not be long until they are gone also,'' says
Tomaki Juda, mayor of Kili Island, which has the largest population
of Bikinians. ``We hope it will not be long before we can restore
our traditions.''
   The Bikinians, described in 1946 as a primitive fishing people,
now enjoy a lifestyle they couldn't have imagined 42 years ago.
With American dollars they have bought Western-style clothes, TV
sets, videotape recorders and even cars. But Bauno and his fellow
elders say those comforts are only sedatives to ease the pain of
their exile.
   Some 700 of the Bikinians now live on Kili, a 200-acre island
500 miles south of Bikini which was uninhabited when they arrived.
Unlike Bikini, whose 23 remaining islands enclose a 240-square-mile
lagoon teeming with fish, Kili is an isolated coconut island
pounded by heavy surf.
   A $6 million trust fund provides each Bikinian about $30 a
month, giving them a higher standard of living than most
Marshallese. The Bikinians depend on canned meat and surplus food
provided by the U.S. government to supplement the coconuts and
breadfruit grown on Kili.
   U.S. aid has provided the Bikinians plywood houses, electricity
and medical care. The Bikinians also have built what local pilots
call the best airstrip in the Marshalls outside of Majuro, the
capital.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
