<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--Bikini Adv22-1stAdd   05-09 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Bikini, Adv 22-1st Add,0602</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>BIKINI ATOLL, Marshall Islands: the capital.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Some people call them rich, but a Toyota and a plywood house
isn't rich,'' says Jack Niedenthal, an American who is an adviser
and interpreter for the Bikinians.
   While the Bikini elders try to keep tradition alive on Kili, the
American influence is strong. Some of the 100 children attending
Kili's three-building school have first names such as Rambo, George
Bush, Kennedy and Chuck Norris.
   A popular activity on Kili is to drive one of the island's
30-odd Japanese cars at midday with the air conditioner running _
an event they call ``jumbo.''
   ``The cars are a way of taking away the burden of living on
Kili,'' says Mayor Juda. ``Getting in a car and riding around gives
you a feeling of not being so stuck, even though driving from one
end of Kili to the other takes only a couple of minutes.''
   Twenty police officers take turns patrolling Kili's two miles of
dirt road in a pickup truck equipped with a $15 dollar siren.
Police hand out tickets of up to $25 for offenses ranging from
running one of the island's dozen stop signs to exceeding the 5 mph
speed limit established in the island's living area.
   The greatest thrill for the Bikinians is when the elders return
to check the progress of work at Bikini. The latest trip was made
in early April, when 50 joined U.S. officials to mark the start of
construction of a $30 million base camp once the method of cleaning
Bikini is agreed upon.
   The Bikinians and their Washington attorney, Jonathan Weisgall,
continue to lobby the U.S. government for money for the cleanup and
resettlement, which is expected to cost between $120 million and
$215 million. So far, the government has appropriated a few hundred
thousand dollars to begin construction of the base camp, Weisgall
says.
   Weisgall has proposed that the U.S. government establish another
trust fund that would allow the Bikinians pay for the resettlement
themselves. The plan, which Weisgall said would involve a
commitment of about $100 million, has received support from some
congressional leaders and from Larry Morgan of the Department of
the Interior, the Bikini project officer.
   ``I think all our problems can be addressed and resolved by a
trust fund,'' Morgan says. ``The trust fund we think puts the
responsibility on the Bikinians themselves rather than bureaucrats
in Washington.''
   For the past 10 years, American scientists have studied the
radiation problem on the main island of Bikini, whose soil is laced
with radioactive cesium-137 from the explosion of America's most
powerful hydrogen bomb in 1954. The researchers say it will take
between five and 10 years to clean Bikini Island, where most of the
Bikinians will live.
   Scientists say that without treatment locally grown food won't
be safe until well into the 21st century.
   They are considering three cleanup alternatives: removing the
topsoil in which the radioactive material is concentrated, treating
the soil with potassium to prevent the uptake of radioactivity by
plants and irrigation with sea water.
   For now, the Bikinians remain at the mercy of America.
   ``They give us a little money and we buy our food,'' Bauno says.
``Then we stare at them again and they give us a little more.
   ``That's all we can do. We just look to these Americans, saying,
`Continue helping us because we're still away from where we want to
be.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
