<1ST_LINE>s i BC-BoatPeople-Camps Adv15   05-09 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Boat People-Camps, Adv 15,0436</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Vietnamese Refugees, the Wait for Resettlement Seems Endless</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Boat People, b0638</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUEN MUN CLOSED CAMP, Hong Kong (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They are not soldiers but
they live in military barracks; they are not prisoners, but guards
watch over them.
   Soldiers and prisoners usually know when their terms are up, but
the 2,000 or so Vietnamese boat people at this camp have little
idea when they will find a home.
   They are not allowed to leave the prison-like camp in Hong
Kong's rural New Territories, about 500 miles northeast of the
homeland they fled, until the United Nations arranges for their
permanent resettlement elsewhere.
   For some refugees, the wait already has lasted a decade and the
effects of lengthy confinement are reflected on their blank faces.
   A woman sitting on the top deck of a three-tiered bunk bed
stares into space; a man stands motionless outside his barracks.
Children who have known no other life run and play.
   For all the refugees, the matless wooden bunks are the center of
their lives. Family pictures, calendars, clothes and other
belongings are packed nearby.
   No one knows how long they will remain. Some meticulously count
the days they've been here.
   ``Nine months and 19 days,'' said Pham My Linh, 29.
   ``You don't understand what it's like in Vietnam,'' she said in
explaining why she's doing it. ``There are wars in Cambodia and all
17-year-olds have to join the army.''
   She was happy this day because she had an interview with a U.S.
delegation the day before, although she received no promises of
going to the United States.
   Another refugee, 17-year-old Le Thi Luyen, left North Vietnam
five years ago. Her mother and brothers had planned to leave with
her but could not find space on the boat.
   ``I don't know why I'm here,'' she said. ``I was only 12 (when I
left). Everybody left so I left.''
   Miss Le said she is willing to return to Vietnam to rejoin her
family but dares not ask about doing so.
   ``Some people have applied to go back in 1984 but were
refused,'' she said.
   Despair also is widespread in the many other camps dotting
Southeast Asia.
   Two Vietnamese refugees recently hanged themselves, one in a
Thailand camp and another in Malaysia. One had complained of being
in the camp too long and going nowhere; the other reportedly missed
his family in Vietnam.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
