<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i BC-Ethiopia-Starvation Adv15   05-09 1149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ethiopia-Starvation, Adv 15,1181</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ethiopia: Again Drought, Again War, Again Starvation</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fierce fighting is overwhelming
foreign relief efforts in Ethiopia's drought-stricken north, where
more than 3 million people are threatened with starvation.
   The government expelled foreign aid workers and withdrew from
much of the northern provinces of Eritrea and Tigre, where rebels
are waging war against Ethiopia's Marxist-led government in Addis
Ababa.
   The government now forbids food distribution to the regions,
leaving as many as 2 million people beyond the reach of the foreign
emergency aid.
   A limited emergency operation continues through the government's
Relief and Rehabilitation Commission and a consortium of Christian
and indigenous groups organized under the Joint Relief Project.
   After intervention by a special United Nations envoy, the
government allowed U.N. personnel to return to the area where they
coordinate the relief effort's trucking and airlift operations.
   But officials say that, at most, only 1.5 million people can be
reached under current conditions and of that number, just 1 million
now are being fed.
   Overall, an estimated 3.2 million people are in danger of
starvation and depend on food aid following near-total crop
failures last year.
   ``We've got a lot of people who are not going to get food,''
said Patrick Johns of Catholic Relief Services, the primary
coordinator of the Joint Relief Project's food distribution efforts.
   Relief officials and diplomats are expecting hungry peasants to
migrate from the cut-off areas.
   All aid officials interviewed in Addis Ababa said such a mass
movement almost certainly would create huge hunger camps like those
of Ethiopia's famine of 1984-86, when diseases caused by
overcrowding and unsanitary conditions accounted for many of the
estimated 1 million deaths then.
   This time, people arriving at food distribution centers still
looked relatively healthy when the foreign aid workers were
expelled, said Vincent Bernard of the International Committee of
the Red Cross, which has employed about half of the foreigners
working in the northern relief effort.
   However, he and others said the peasants' health could
deteriorate rapidly unless they get food.
   ``We're talking about people who can't wait days or weeks 'til
their next meal,'' said James Cheek, the U.S. charge d'affaires in
Addis Ababa. ``I think we're going to see people moving pretty
soon. ... The future looks pretty grim right now.''
   An added complication is the thousands of local government
officials and leaders of the Marxist Workers Party of Ethiopia who
are fleeing rebel retaliation in the contested areas. They now are
gathered in Asmara, Eritrea's capital, and in Mekele in Tigre.
   The government's chief relief official in Addis Ababa, Berhanu
Jembere, said in an interview that full relief operations would be
resumed and foreign aid workers would be allowed to return to the
north only after the area is ``cleansed of bandit activity.'' He
could not say when that might be.
   Secessionist rebels in Eritrea have been fighting for 27 years
in Africa's longest civil war. In Tigre, guerrillas seeking greater
autonomy and a say in the government took up arms in 1974.
   Relief officials fear the foreign aid workers were withdrawn
from the northern provices to keep them from seeing what is
happening in the war zone. They say the government's exemption of
U.N. personnel from the expulsion order weakened its argument that
the foreigners were removed from Eritrea and Tigre for their own
safety.
   At best, they say, the government hopes to avoid the
embarrassment of foreigners becoming war casualties or the
inconvenience of dealing with relief convoys while it tries to
fight the rebels.
   The worst case offered is that the governemnt wants to conceal a
scorched-earth policy in the embattled territories, or to hide a
policy of genocide by starvation.
   Despite the limited access, Western diplomats and relief
officials said they had been able to confirm a government air
strike on an important food distribution center in the Tigrean town
of Wukro, which in recent weeks had fallen into rebel hands.
   These sources, citing accounts of eyewitnesses, said the bombing
April 8 killed at least 50 people and wounded many more, minutes
after several thousand peasants were given emergency food rations.
   Berhanu said he could not confirm an air attack, but added that
the government's policy against the rebels would be ``an eye for an
eye, if not more.''
   He also said the safety of the drought-sticken peasants depended
on their own patriotism.
   ``They are expected to join hands with the military so that the
enemies can be wiped out,'' he said. ``The people themselves, I
think, should decide _ and that decision is just to cleanse
themselves of bandits.''
   The military priorities also are impinging on relief efforts in
other provinces less severely affected by the drought but still in
need of aid.
   Relief workers in Hararghe province, east of Addis Ababa, and
Northern Shoa, north of the capital, say some peasants have been
afraid to leave their homes _ either to plow their fields or
receive food rations _ for fear of being picked up by local
officials and taken to the war zone.
   Sources say an emergency conscription is reaching into all
corners of this North African nation to bring tens of thousands of
able-bodied young men into military ranks to fight in the north.
   The military difficulties inhibit a well-prepared relief
operation, in contrast to the food disaster three years ago, when
foreign assistance arrived too late to save many of those who died.
   With the drought this time, food distribution began early,
before malnourishment reached desperate levels, and enough grain
was pledged to fulfill the projected need, estimated at 1.23
million metric tons by the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization.
   But even before the expulsion of foreigners from the north and
rebel offensives in March, the war already was hindering the relief
effort. Rebel attacks and land mines destroyed more than 100 trucks
used in the relief effort and often forced the closing of roads
over which food moved. Now, hundreds of governent-controlled trucks
that had been hauling relief food have been diverted to the war
effort.
   The transportation shortage exacerbates problems at Ethiopia's
two Red Sea ports, Massawa and Assab, where food is piling up
without sufficient storage facilities, said David Morton of the
U.N. World Food Program.
   ``We're particularly concerned it could be diverted to the
military,'' said Ambassador David MacDonald of Canada.
   Cheek, the U.S. diplomat, said the United States would not allow
its relief assistance to be administered by indigenous
organizations whose operations were not subject to on-the-scene
monitoring by foreign aid officials.
   ``We now have a war disaster imposed on a drought disaster,'' he
said. ``We have yet to solve that, to figure out how, in the
context of the double disaster, to perform our humanitarian
function.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday May 15</NOTE>
