<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Ethiopia-War Adv15   05-09 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ethiopia-War, Adv 15,0597</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Africa's Oldest War Fought in Obscurity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Ethiopia-Starvation, b0640</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the mean terrain of northern
Ethiopia, secessionist rebels and black Africa's biggest and
best-armed military force are fighting one of the world's longest
and most obscure wars.
   Every so often, the conflict pops to the world's attention, only
to fade like a smothered flare.
   It has gained attention once again because a spate of recent
rebel victories, drought and a cut-off of routes for food aid have
combined to raise the threat of famine for 3.2 million people in
the area.
   Eritrea's civil war began in 1961 against the feudal rule of
Emperor Haile Selassie. Today it is against the Marxist,
Soviet-backed government that ousted Selassie in 1973.
   The original rebel group, the Eritrean Liberation Front (ELF),
broke up into four groups over religious and ideological
differences. The largest and most powerful of the splinter groups
is the Marxist but anti-Soviet Eritrean People's Liberation Front
(EPLF), with 30,000 fighters.
   The ELF, which is predominantly Moslem and conservative, now
numbers about 5,000 fighters and has not been effective since its
clash with the EPLF in 1972-74.
   The East and the West, particularly the Soviet Union and the
United States, have a stake in the outcome of the conflict because
of Ethiopia's place on the strategic Horn of Africa.
   Conservative Arab states like Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Egypt and
Sudan, fearful of the Soviet Union's current influence in Ethiopia,
openly support the EPLF, even though it is mainly Christian,
because it opposes the Soviet presence in Ethiopia.
   Syria and Iraq back the ELF.
   Black Africa generally has remained aloof from the conflict.
   While the Ethiopian government receives weapons from the Soviet
Union and troops from Cuba, the West does not provide any similar
support to the rebels. Most of their weapons and supplies are
captured from the government.
   Cuba, one of the first countries to back the rebels at the start
of their campaign against Selassie's pro-Western government nearly
three decades ago, now sides with the central government. Libya
followed in Cuba's path.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization and Israel both train the
rebels.
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam has said his Ethiopian forces
soon will launch a major offensive against the rebels. A dozen
previous ``major offensives'' failed in the past.
   The rebels have Eritrea's rugged terrain as their chief ally and
they have been able to stand off 120,000 Ethiopian soldiers, 20,000
Cubans and hundreds of Soviet advisers.
   The rebels main tactics are hit-and-run attacks and ambushes of
government troops as they move through narrow, mountainous passes.
   For most of its 3,000-year history, Eritrea has been coveted by
foreign powers and neighbors.
   It is about the size of Pennsylvania and has mineral resources,
including gold, iron and copper, none of which is exploited because
of the war. Its 3.5 million people are mostly peasant farmers.
   Eritrea's allure is its geographical position.
   The province sits strategically at the crossroads of the Horn of
Africa and the Middle East, commanding the gateway to the Bab el
Mandab Strait from the Indian Ocean, nowadays one of the main
routes for Middle Eastern oil.
   It's 625-mile Red Sea coastline includes the ports of Assab and
Massawa.
   It has the only non-Arab access to the Red Sea.
   Without Eritrea, Ethiopia would be landlocked.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
