<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0522</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A class action suit was filed on
behalf of Texaco Inc. shareholders who claim takeover strategist
Carl Icahn manipulated the price of the oil giant's shares so he
could buy them cheaply.
   The suit, filed on Friday, is a companion to one lodged by
Texaco alleging massive securities law violations by Icahn, who is
Texaco's largest shareholder and chairman of Trans World Airlines
Inc.
   Texaco filed for bankruptcy protection last year and emerged in
April under a court-approved reorganization plan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allied Stores Corp. President Robert H. Morosky,
who was expected to become chairman of Federated Department Stores
Inc. after its merger with Campeau Corp., has agreed to resign,
Campeau said in a surprise announcement.
   Campeau said late Friday its chairman, Robert Campeau, would
serve as chairman of both Allied and Federated for the foreseeable
future.
   The statement said Robert Campeau would hold both positions ``in
light of the size and importance to Campeau Corp. of its
acquisition of Federated.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. has proposed a settlement to lawsuits
filed by shareholders who objected to parts of the company's plan
to recapitalize in the face of a hostile takeover bid.
   An unspecified number of suits were filed in Delaware Chancery
Court sometime after last Monday, when USG unveiled details of its
$2.2 billion recapitalization plan. The Chicago-based building
products company is incorporated in Delaware.
   The proposed settlement, which was announced Friday and still
must be approved by the court, would add $92.4 million to the cost
of the recapitalization.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government charged E.F.
Hutton & Co. Inc. in connection with an alleged money-laundering
scheme that helped organized crime figures and businessmen conceal
at least $532,000 from the Internal Revenue Service.
   Hutton was expected to plead guilty to the three felony counts
of conspiracy and money laundering, U.S. Attorney Lincoln C. Almond
said.
   Two former Hutton brokers also were named in documents, known as
a criminal information, filed in U.S. District Court on Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saying the country is ``fed up with
white-collar crime,'' the head of the Justice Department's
antitrust division has urged longer jail terms for business
executives engaging in price-fixing and larger fines for companies
engaging in anti-competitive practices.
   Assistant Attorney General Charles Rule said there is a trend
toward more jail time and heavier fines in antitrust cases, but
``the averages are still too low.''
   His remarks were prepared for delivery in San Francisco, but
were released Friday in Washington.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined for the third straight session Friday,
faced with employment statistics that raised fears of higher
interest rates. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped
12.77 to 2,007.46, bringing its loss for the week to 24.87 points.
   The dollar finished mostly lower while gold prices fell.
   Bond prices also declined.
   Platinum and silver futures advances.
</TEXT>
