<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 0924EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Pound     05-09 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Pound,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Bank Intervenes As Pound Rises On Lawson Resignation
Rumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bank of England intervened in the foreign
exchange market to stem a surge in the pound, as rumors flew Monday
that Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson was planning to
resign, dealers said.
   The intervention was light to moderate, dealers said.
   A Bank of England official declined to comment on the reports of
intervention. A Treasury official denied the rumors about Lawson.
Neither official was identified, in accordance with British custom.
   The pound rose to $1.8785 by midday local time from $1.8730 in
London on Friday. It was quoted well above 3.1300 West German marks
at 3.1587 marks.
   Dealers said sterling began to climb in overnight trading, in
the wake of a bullish report by the investment firm Goldman Sachs
International Corp., which was highlighted in The Sunday Times.
   In the report, Goldman Sachs chief international economist David
Morrison said the pound was significantly undervalued against the
Deutsche mark and could climb over the next few months.
   The report contended that British industry would still be
competitive if the pound rose as high as 3.27 marks.
   Dealers said the report served as an excuse to buy pounds.
   Rumors that Lawson would resign sent sterling surging in the
early afternoon before the intervention took place, dealers said.
Lawson favors intervention to stem the pound's rise.
   When Lawson stated on March 10 that any further rise in the
pound's rise could not be sustained, the pound stood at 3.08 marks.
   Lawson clashed at that time with Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, who said the pound should be allowed to rise in foreign
exchange markets to contain inflation.
   Morrison's report argued that fears that the pound's rise could
lead to the devastation of British industry were totally unfounded
and he said Lawson's quest for stability was ill-founded.
   Morrison said the British economy's growth rate this year will
be double West Germany's and that while Britain has a budget
surplus, West Germany is facing an ``exploding budget deficit'' _
higher even than America's as a percentage of national income.''
   At the same time the American economy is on course for higher
inflation than Britain by the end of this year, and is saddled with
huge trade and budget deficits for the forseeable future, Morrison
said.
   He said the pound could surge over the next few months, perhaps
to 3.20 marks and $2.
   ``People don't appreciate how dynamic the British economy has
become,'' Morrison said.
   He said that because of Britain's lack of political worries and
its budget surplus, foreign investors see Britain as a more
attractive country in which to invest than the United States or
West Germany.
   The Sunday Times said the Goldman Sachs report ``contradicts a
widely held view in the City (of London financial district) that
sterling will slide in response to a rising balance of payments
deficit.''
   Morrison said the balance of payments deficit in prospect for
this year, which he expects to be between 5 billion and 6 billion
pounds _ or $9.35 and $11.22 billion _ can be readily financed
without any increase in interest rates.
   He said Britain has no fundamental balance of payments problem.
</TEXT>
