<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 0934EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AccountingSuit     05-09 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Accounting Suit,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accounting Firm Pays $15 Million to Settle Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laventhol & Horwath has paid $15 million in an
out-of-court settlement of a lawsuit charging the accounting firm
with racketeering.
   The firm made the settlement last Friday with attorneys for
2,850 investors who lost a total of more than $20 million in a
failed tax-shelter program audited by Laventhol.
   The settlement must be approved by a judge in the U.S. District
Court in Sacramento, Calif., Laventhol General Counsel Barry S.
Augenbraun told The Associated Press Monday.
   Laventhol, based in Philadelphia, is the nation's ninth-largest
accounting firm.
   A jury found in favor of the investors in February, making
Laventhol the first big accounting firm to lose a jury trial under
the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act. Under the
federal law, known as RICO, plaintiffs are automatically eligible
for triple damages.
   Under the racketeering charge, Laventhol was accused of
complicity in the tax-shelter scheme. The shelters were offered by
Dairy World Genetics Partnerships, a series of limited
partnerships, in 1970, 1980 and 1981.
   The settlement of the class-action suit is entirely covered by
Laventhol's liability insurance, Augenbraun said.
   Some attorneys believe the magnitude of the Laventhol settlement
could have negative implications for the accounting profession.
   ``As long as the plaintiffs allege that accountants are in
cahoots with the company in defrauding investors, any accounting
firm can get caught up in RICO,'' Victor Earle, former general
counsel of accounting firm Peat Marwick, told the Wall Street
Journal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
