<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed To Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed to lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade but prices steadied when it
appeared soybean prices could not be pushed more than about 5 cents
lower per bushel.
   The opening drop in the soybean and corn pits was linked to
weekend rains over much of the Midwest, analysts said.
   But the rains were not heavy and the latest forecasts _ calling
for dry conditions to prevail until this weekend _ lent support to
the markets, said Joel Karlin, an analyst in Chicago with Research
Department Inc.
   ``Once values were able to hold at certain levels, that was
enough to encourage a little buying,'' he said.
   Wheat futures were slightly higher in response to dry-weather
forecasts for the northern Plains states. Position-evening ahead of
Tuesday's winter wheat production report from the Agriculture
Department also helped boost prices, Karlin said.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent lower to 2\ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $3 a bushel; corn was } cent to
1 cent lower with May at $2.01 a bushel; oats were unchanged to }
cent lower with May at $1.60\ a bushel; soybeans were 3\ cents to
4{ cents lower with May at $6.89 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .28 cent higher with June at 72.92
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .23 cent higher with
May at 80 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .50 cent higher
with June at 51.65 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .18 cent
lower to .18 cent higher with May at 51.82 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Friday while pork futures
retreated.
</TEXT>
