<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     05-09 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pound Surges on Rumors of Lawson's Resignation, Other Factors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British pound surged Monday in European
trading, partly on rumors that Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel
Lawson was resigning. The rumors were denied later.
   The sharp rise in the British currency prompted the Bank of
England to intervene by selling pounds in the foreign-exchange
market, dealers said.
   The dollar turned mixed and gold prices rose.
   The pound was supported early in the day by a forecast from
investment bank Goldman Sachs International Corp., highlighted in
the Sunday Times, suggesting that the pound could rise to $2 and
3.20 marks.
   It was further boosted by rumors of huge sterling buy order,
dealers said. Estimates of the size of the order ranged from $500
million to $1.5 billion, and dealers said the buyer was a U.S.
investment bank, a U.S. investment management firm, or a major New
York bank.
   The British currency was given a push by rumors, later firmly
denied by the Treasury, that Lawson was resigning.
   Lawson is seen as the major government official most opposed to
allowing the pound to rise. Dealers said the Lawson rumor is
frequent usually disregarded, but that in this instance it gave the
currency an extra boost.
   The pound was quoted late in London at $1.8790, up from $1.8730
late Friday, and at 3.1606 marks, up from 3.1300 marks.
   The Bank of England intervened around midday to hold down the
pound's rise, dealers said. The bank sold pounds when the currency
broke above $1.88, dealers said.
   The French franc was strong following the resounding victory by
Francois Mitterrand in the presidential election. The dollar fell
to 5.7075 francs from 5.7230 francs.
   Other late dollar rates compared with late Friday included:
1.6820 marks, up from 1.6805; 1.4010 Swiss francs, down from
1.4015; 1.8805 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8860; 1,250.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,254.00; 1.2396 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2375.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar slipped 0.01 yen to a closing 124.87 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted slightly lower at 124.82 yen.
   Gold sold in London at a late bid price of $444.00 a troy ounce,
up from late Friday's $442.10.
   In Zurich, the late bid price was $445.00, up from $443 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 79 cents to close at a bid
$446.66.
   Silver was quoted in London at a late bid price of $6.43 a troy
ounce, up from Friday's $6.36.
</TEXT>
