<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1408EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OfficeSpace     05-09 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Office Space,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Better Office Absorption Forecast For Next Four Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The worst is over for Houston's ailing office
market, and a long-term recovery is gaining momentum that should
increase occupancy over the next four years, researchers said.
   Most economic indicators point to a bottoming of the market in
the first half of last year, said Rice Center vice president James
P. Gaines, who oversees the organization's Houston Real Estate
Forecasting System.
   ``Since then, we've had positive absorption, positive job growth
and generally positive economic indices,'' Gaines said. ``We are
forecasting a good year for office absorption, with just over 2
million square feet absorbed in 1988.''
   By 1991 or 1992, the city should not only see marked
improvements in employment, but office absorption should increase
to between 3.7 million and 6 million square feet, Gaines said.
   If a national economic downturn occurs in late 1989 or early
1990, however, about 40 percent less space will be absorbed, Gaines
said.
   Yet even during the recession that is predicted by Rice Center's
computer models, office space absorption _ the difference between
the amount of space at the beginning of a certain period and the
amount at the end _ will remain positive, albeit less robust.
   ``Assuming that no more buildings are constructed, the overall
occupancy rate in 1992 is projected to be approximately 81 percent,
which is halfway between the current rate of 70 percent and a
`marginally healthy' rate of 90 percent,'' Gaines said. ``For Class
A office space, however, the occupancy rate is expected to be
slightly above 88 percent by 1992.''
   A Class A building is generally of a high-quality finish, is new
or competitive with new structures, and has a excellent location.
   The largest office market in terms of square footage if
Houston's central business district. Rice Center forecasts an
overall occupancy rate this year in the central district of 80.1
percent, with Class A buildings having more tenants and a better
occupancy rate of 84 percent.
   By 1992, the overall occupancy rate is projected to be 88
percent, with the occupancy level of Class A space pegged at 90
percent.
   Rice Center's Houston Real Estate Forecasting System was two
years in the making.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
