<HEAD>London Shares 0ff 6.2 Points
^Eds: New throughout to update with close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange closed
lower on Monday on nervousness about the stronger pound, which
could hurt British exports and corporate profits.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended 6.2
points, or 0.3 percent, lower at 1,794.9 at the close.
   The index hit a low of 7.8 points off and a high of 4.1 points
up during the session.
   Volume was a low 368 million shares, compared with Friday's
609.4 million shares.
   Participants played it cautiously after sterling began its rise
Monday on currency markets. The pound continued to gain against the
West German mark on the widespread belief that the West German
central bank won't raise short-term interest rates, throwing the
focus back onto sterling, traders said.
   Activity continued to cluster around the takeover stocks,
dealers said, although less than in previous sessions.
   ``The only feature of this market is takeover chatter, but we
didn't see that much of it,'' said one dealer.
   Market watchers said activity may pick up later in the week when
various companies are scheduled to release earnings figures.
   The Financial Times 30-share index finished off 2.1 points at
1,438.0 at the close.
   The Financial Times 500-share index fell 2.0 points to close at
1,019.49.
