<HEAD>Soybeans Soar; Grains Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures ended sharply higher Monday on
the Chicago Board of Trade, boosting the near-month contract to $7
a bushel for the first time since mid-1984.
   Wheat also finished higher while corn futures retreated.
   Speculative and large-fund buyers led the soybean rally, which
ran its first leg early in the session and accelerated near the
close after prices surpassed contract highs set last week, analysts
said.
   Despite weekend rains that dampened the soybean-producing areas
of the Midwest, weather forecasts provided much of the impetus for
the rally, said Joel Karlin, an analyst in Chicago with Research
Department Inc.
   ``The bulls can point to the fact that rain coverage over the
weekend was pretty spotty and no additional rain is forecast until
this weekend, perhaps. And that's an important point, that
`perhaps,''' Karlin said.
   Wheat futures advanced moderately ahead of Tuesday's winter
wheat production report from the Agriculture Department, he said.
Corn retreated slightly amid a lack of export demand.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 4 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.01} a bushel; corn was \ cent to
1 cent lower with May at $2.00\ a bushel; oats were 1} cents lower
to 1} cents higher with May at $1.59\ a bushel; soybeans were 7\
cents to 9{ cents higher with May at $7 a bushel.
</TEXT>
