<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WeeklySteel     05-09 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Fell 0.9 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production fell to 2.028 million tons in
the week ended May 7, a decrease of 0.9 percent from the previous
week's 2.046 million tons, the American Iron and Steel Institute
reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 94.6 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 95.5 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
35.681 million net tons, an increase of 26.7 percent from the
28.157 million net tons in the previous year. The steel operations
of USX Corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down
by a strike during the first month of 1987.
   Production so far this year used 90.9 percent of capacity,
compared with 72.1 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended May 7: Northeast
Coast, 277,000; Pittsburgh, 214,000; Youngstown, 130,000; Lake
Erie, 173,000; Detroit, 164,000; Chicago, 544,000; Midwest,
193,000; Southern, 230,000; and Western, 103,000.
   Separately, the institute said steel shipments during the first
quarter of 1988 rose 20.8 percent to 21.006 tons, compared with
17.387 tons in the 1987 quarter.
   It was the best performance since 1981's first quarter of 23.415
million tons.
   ``That was the last of our relatively strong years, just before
the recession took over and made hash out of the industry,'' said
Sheldon Wesson, spokesman for the organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
