<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ComputerExecs-Campaign     05-09 0123</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Execs-Campaign,0128</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Computer Execs Lean Toward Bush, Poll Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top computer industry executives prefer George
Bush over Michael Dukakis or Jesse Jackson for president, according
to a poll conducted by the Gallup Organization Inc. for Computer
Systems News.
   Bush outdistanced Dukakis 80 percent to 18 percent in a
one-to-one faceoff and outpolled Jackson 93 percent to 4 percent,
the weekly newspaper reported Monday.
   The poll included responses from 100 chairmen, presidents or
chief executives of large computer companies. Two-hundred had been
asked to participate.
   The results were consistent with the executives' political
affiliations. Gallup said 81 percent were Republicans or leaned
toward the Republican party, while 18 percent were Democrats or
leaned toward the Democratic party.
</TEXT>
