<2ND_LINE>AM-Western Publishing, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0134,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ends Merger Talks with Gulf & Western</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, Western Publishing's ..., with one graf to
UPDATE with closing stock price. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, In a ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf & Western Inc. and Western Publishing Group
Inc. said Monday they had ended talks about a possible takeover of
Western Publishing, a children's book publisher and commercial
printer.
   Western Publishing's stock tumbled after the announcement,
closing down $3 a share to $19 in over-the-counter trading. Gulf &
Western was off 50 cents a share at $36.87{ on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   In a statement, the companies said they had ``mutually agreed to
terminate their preliminary discussions with respect to the
possible acquisition of Western Publishing by Gulf & Western.''
   The statement provided no reason for the decision. A spokesmen
for Gulf & Western declined to elaborate, while a spokesman for
Western Publishing failed to return three telephone calls.
   Western, which publishes the Golden Book children's series, had
indicated two weeks ago that it was in talks about a possible
merger. Last week, it identified Gulf & Western as the other party
in the talks.
   But in doing so, both companies noted there were a number of
unresolved issues and there were no assurances that an agreement
would be reached.
   Western Publishing has about 20 million shares of common stock
outstanding.
   In addition to its Golden Book series for children, Western has
an extensive distibution system for its books, puzzles, games and
crayons and is a major commercial printer.
   Gulf & Western, which has extensive interests in entertainment
and financial servicves, has spent heavily to expand its publishing
business in recent years. It owns Simon & Schuster, which publishes
books for mass circulation, and Prentice-Hall Inc., an educational
and professional publisher.
</TEXT>
