<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FordHiring 1stLd-Writethru f0101 05-09 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford Hiring, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0101,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Journal: Ford Hiring For First Time Since Early Eighties</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, Ford, which ..., with four grafs to
CORRECT number of layoffs to 69,000 sted 100,000, and to UPDATE
with comment from Ford spokesman. Picks up 6th graf pvs, William
Novotny ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co., which earned industry-record
profits in 1987 and in the first quarter of 1988, is hiring new
workers for the first time since the layoffs of the early 1980s, a
trade journal reported Monday.
   In addition, Ford is using hiring techniques learned from
foreign automakers who have U.S. factories _ methods that include
intense testing, screening and interviewing, Automotive News
reported.
   The so-called transplants _ Mazda Motor Co., Nissan Motor Corp.,
Toyota Motor Corp. and Mitsubishi Motors Corp. factories in the
United States _ take as many as 100,000 applications to fill 2,000
openings.
   Ford, which laid off about 69,000 workers at the beginning of
the decade, has only about 2,000 remaining on indefinite layoff.
The others were recalled or dropped off the recall rolls after
several years.
   ``In recent months we have in certain locations been able to
hire new people because even these 2,000 people with recall rights
are limited by certain restrictions to plants in their area,'' Ford
spokesman Tom Foote told The Associated Press.
   ``It's on a small scale, just a smattering here and there,'' he
said. ``It's been going on for a few months.''
   The latest hiring process takes about a month, a big change from
practices of the past, when a worker hired Friday was put on the
assembly line Monday. New workers are put up in a hotel and given a
week of orientation by the company and the union.
   William Novotny, time standards representative at United Auto
Workers Local 879 at Ford's Twin Cities truck plant in St. Paul,
Minn., said it represents ``a totally new way of hiring.''
   At the Twin Cities plant, about 50 workers will be chosen from
among 2,000 applicants, Novotny said. About 150 workers already
have been hired at the plant, most of whom have never worked in an
auto plant, said Local 879 Chairman Doug Knight.
   The new workers include former teachers and members of the
military.
   Some of the applicants not selected were children of current
workers who failed drug tests, Novotny said. Drug use is one of the
biggest problems in auto plants, although few union officials want
to discuss it publicly.
   ``That has caused some heartbreak,'' Novotny said, ``but it will
make a better work place in the long run.''
   In addition to Twin Cities, Ford also has been hiring at its
Wixom assembly plant, which builds the Lincoln Town Car and
Continental, at its Climate Control Division plant in Plymouth, and
at its Plastic Products Division plant in Milan. Those three plants
are outside Detroit.
   The hiring has been prompted by new UAW contract rules that
allow workers who took jobs at other plants to return to their home
plants as openings occur. When they leave, Ford often has to hire
new workers to replace them.
   By comparison, General Motors Corp., the nation's largest
automaker, is doing no new hiring because it still has 60,000
workers on indefinite layoff and is shrinking some of its
operations.
   Chrysler Corp. has at least 8,000 workers on indefinite layoff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880509-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-88 1828EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-LuckyStores 1stLd-Writethru f0100 05-09 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lucky Stores, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0100,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grocery Chain Agrees To Share Info With American Stores</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th grav pvs, Lucky stock ..., to UPDATE with closing
stock prices. Picks up 6th graf pvs, American Stores ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucky Stores Inc. said Monday it has
provided confidential information to rival American Stores Inc. in
exchange for an agreement that it will sweeten or end its hostile
takeover bid by May 17.
   Lucky said it continues to recommend that its shareholders
accept the leveraged buyout offer of $61 a share, or $2.35 billion,
made on April 28 by the New York investment firm Gibbons, Green,
van Amerongen Ltd.
   But analysts said Salt Lake City-based American Stores remains a
strong contender under the new agreement, which Lucky said also
provides a number of protections to its stockholders.
   ``My continuing belief is that American Stores will acquire
Lucky,'' said Edward Comeau of Wood Gundy Corp. in New York. ``From
the beginning, it was apparent that American badly wanted Lucky,
needed Lucky and can afford to pay more for it than anyone else.''
   Lucky closed down 37.5 cents a share at $61.37{ on the New York
Stock Exchange. American Stores stock fell 50 cents a share to
$59.75.
   American Stores, which initiated the bidding with a $45-a-share
offer that Lucky rejected in March, is the owner of the Alpha Beta
grocery chain. With an acquisition of Lucky, the nation's
sixth-largest supermarket chain, American Stores would surpass No.
1 Kroger Co. of Cincinnati to become the industry leader.
   The Lucky transaction would be by far the biggest ever for the
Gibbons-led buyout group, which specializes in leveraged buyouts.
If Lucky breaks the merger agreement, the New York investment firm
must be paid a $20 million fee plus expenses.
   Comeau said a supermarket chain can afford to pay more than
anyone making a leveraged buyout.
   ``When you put supermarket chains together, one plus one equals
three'' because of ``synergistic and strategic benefits,'' he said.
   Ron Rotter, an analyst with Morgan, Olmstead, Kennedy and
Gardner in Los Angeles, said he would not be surprised if American
Stores makes a new offer even though the pending bid is fairly
valued.
   ``If this operation is worth $61 to an independent party, it
should be worth more to American Stores, which could reap many
benefits by integrating Lucky's operations into their operations,''
Rotter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
